<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama 4thLd-Writethru a0888 03-01 0980</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0888,1008</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Violence in Second Day of General Strike</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 1-20 UPDATE with Zuniga beaten, freed, other
details. Pick up 15th graf pvs: Journalists saw ... with deletions
to trim and conform</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Plainclothes police stormed a
building housing an opposition party office and its radio station
Tuesday, setting off a rock-throwing protest by foes of Gen. Manuel
Antonio Noriega's military rule.
   Carlos Ivan Zuniga, leader and presidential candidate of the
Popular Action Party in 1984, was beaten and arrested. Zuniga,
owner of Radio 10-FM, was released hours later.
   The plainclothes police and later a riot squad fired dozens of
shots into the air to disperse the crowd outside the building. The
brawl occurred as an anti-Noriega strike called by the opposition
Civic Crusade entered its second day and appeared to be picking up
support.
   Witnesses, who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of
reprisals, said plainclothes police with shotguns and pistols
rushed into the Popular Action building on Via Espana, smashing
furniture and equipment inside the radio station.
   Radio 10-FM was under censorship orders to play only music, but
had been broadcasting news supporting the strike.
   An angry crowd gathered outside the building and started
throwing rocks at the officers. An unidentified radio station
employee was slightly injured.
   Leaders of the Civil Crusade, a coalition of 180 business,
professional, labor, student and political groups, told a news
conference Tuesday night the strike shut down 85 percent of
Panama's economic activity. They said 90 percent of industry and
construction were paralyzed.
   They conceded that transportation was down by only 10 percent,
but said retail commerce was 40 percent of normal.
   Carlos Gonzalez de la Lastra, a Crusade leader and a strike
organizer, said ``this demonstrates the Panamanian people's
repudiation of the dictatorship of Gen. Noriega and the fervent
desire for complete democracy.''
   The government, through some of the news media it controls, has
been calling the strike ``a complete failure,'' alleging business
and transportation were functioning normally.
   The young security men at the radio station, dressed in jeans
and T-shirts, outnumbered the protesters and broke up the
demonstration after 40 minutes.
   The demonstrators were banging pots and pans in the streets and
distributing leaflets.
   At least four men were punched, kicked and beaten with rubber
truncheons during the melee as they were arrested and shoved into
police vehicles.
   Two women were among those arrested on Via Argentina, an upper
middle-class neighborhood. They were not beaten, but one was
slapped on the buttocks as she was hustled into a car.
   At first only about 15 demonstrators from the Popular Action
Party were involved at the radio station building, but the crowd
swelled to about 150 when residents came out on balconies or
sidewalks to join in beating pans. Many people bolted for cover,
however, when security agents came to screeching stops in
4-wheel-drive Toyotas.
   The agents jumped out and began shooting. Some residents
returned to balconies from time to time, shouting ``Murderers!''
and ``Cowards!''
   Zuniga, leader of Popular Action, was beaten and shoved into a
vehicle. The car was blocked by another vehicle and Zuniga, a
white-haired man of about 60, fled down the street with his torn
shirt fluttering and security men in pursuit.
   Bystanders created interference and Zuniga dived into a car that
sped away, but he was caught later.
   Eric Arturo Delvalle, ousted as president last week by Noriega,
remained in hiding Tuesday. He predicted serious economic trouble.
   Delvalle's successor, Manuel Solis Palma, accused the United
States of ``lies and defamation'' about Noriega and the Panama
Defense Forces, the 17,000-member military and police organization
commanded by Noriega, the real power behind the civilian government.
   Journalists saw at least three people wounded by birdshot fired
by either the plainclothes agents or soldiers who arrived later.
One man was bleeding from the head, but did not seem to be
seriously injured.
   Calm was reported elsewhere in Panama City. By midafternoon, the
strike had drastically thinned traffic and the crowds on the
streets.
   Strike leaders said 12 Panamanian-owned banks were closed. Most
international banks opened, but did comparatively little business.
   Only one employee and five guards occupied the main area of the
large Chase Manhattan Bank branch. The scenes were similar at
Citibank and the Bank of Boston.
   Some international institutions shut down, including the Bank of
Tokyo.
   Solis Palma, Delvalle's replacement, inaugurated a new session
of the Legislative Assembly with an anti-American speech. The
assembly, which Noriega controls, dismissed Delvalle last Friday.
   ``Noriega has been the victim of the most violent and terrible
campaign of lies and defamation that any leader has ever
received,'' Solis Palma said. He accused the United States and
opponents of the government of ``the clear political intention of
bringing ill repute on the Panama Defense Forces.''
   He said the United States ``wants to asphyxiate the Panamanian
people economically.''
   Solis Palma said the United States has been ``a traditional
enemy'' of Panama. ``They send to our country destabilizing agents
who try to sow chaos in a nation that let its entrails be opened to
serve the world,'' he said in a reference to the Panama Canal.
   Panamanian officials have claimed protests at home and the
indictment of Noriega on drug charges in Florida are the work of
American conservatives who oppose the 1977 treaties under which the
canal is to be turned over to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   In a videotape of Delvalle distributed by his associates, the
former president pledged to remain in Panama and continue
resistance to Noriega.
   He said the crisis would make it impossible for Panama to get
new loans from abroad and described the country as ``totally
bankrupt.''
   Delvalle predicted the lack of credit would force the government
to raise taxes, which he said ``will increase unemployment and
social unrest.''
</TEXT>
