<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScotusRdp     03-01 0692</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus Rdp,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Accepts First Drug Testing Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mandatory drug testing in the workplace will
be studied for the first time by the Supreme Court in a case that
involves government workers but could have an impact on private
businesses as well.
   The justices on Monday agreed to decide whether the U.S. Customs
Service, in the interest of fighting drug smuggling, may force
those applying for or holding drug-enforcement jobs to be tested.
   The court will hear arguments in the case next fall, with a
decision on the constitutionality of the Reagan administration
program not expected until 1989.
   The court also may be called upon soon to study drug and alcohol
testing for federal railway workers. A federal appeals court in San
Francisco ruled on Feb. 11 that the railway testing program is
unconstitutional and the Reagan administration said it will appeal
that ruling to the high court.
   Allan Adler of the American Civil Liberties Union said the high
court's action on testing of government workers could influence
private employers, depending on how broad the court ruling is.
   ``The big question is whether the court is going to determine
this on a narrow, fact basis or will it attempt to articulate broad
principles'' involving workers' reasonable expecations of privacy,
he said.
   He said a narrow ruling relying on the special security needs of
the Customs Service would limit the impact in part because ``most
(private) employers have shied away from random, generalized
testing.''
   But a sweeping endorsement of testing by the court could change
that.
   The case before the justices is limited to whether public
officials violate constitutional rights by testing those who are
not suspected of using drugs.
   The outcome will affect tests conducted by federal, state or
local governments but not by industry. Under the law, governments
may not violate any rights protected by the Constitution, but
private individuals or corporations have more leeway.
   Customs Service workers in sensitive jobs must provide urine
samples in restroom stalls as a person overseeing the procedure
waits outside the stall. The tests are conducted by an independent
company hired by the service.
   Administration lawyers said the tests are needed to prevent
agents who used drugs from being bribed or blackmailed. They said
any sacrifice of personal privacy is outweighed by the need to stop
drug smuggling.
   Government lawyers said the tests are particularly important now
because the Customs Service plans to recruit some 3,000 new
employees, including many in the 18-25 age range in which use of
illegal drugs is most prevalent.
   The Customs Service adopted the test procedure under an
executive order President Reagan signed in 1986.
   The procedure is being challenged by the National Treasury
Employees Union, which said subjecting workers to the test is a
humiliating invasion of privacy.
   The union welcomed the high court's intervention.
   Union President Robert M. Tobias said the court's ruling will
clear up ``a legal and moral morass ... and, we hope, destroy
Reagan's plans for wholesale testing of the federal work force.''
   The Transportation Department, with 30,000 employees, has
adopted random testing for its workers. The program covers those in
safety-related jobs such as air traffic controllers, Federal
Aviation Administration pilots and workers with high-rated security
clearance.
   The Customs Service tests, which are not administered randomly,
were upheld by the New Orleans-based 5th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals.
   The appeals court said the tests may be considered searches but
do not intrude unnecessarily on the privacy rights of workers.
   In other actions Monday, the court:
   _Agreed to decide whether states may bar a man from trying to
prove he fathered the child of a woman married to someone else. The
``reverse paternity'' case challenges a California law, similar to
those in many other states, that always considers the woman's
husband the father.
   _Asked the Reagan administration, in a case from Oklahoma,
whether it thinks high-stakes bingo games run by Indian tribes are
subject to state sales taxes.
   _Said it will decide whether employees of a Pentagon
intelligence agency are entitled to administrative hearings when
the government fires them as security risks.
</TEXT>
