<1ST_LINE>r p PM-KennedyRe-Election     03-01 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Re-Election,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kennedy Raises $1.32 Million While GOP Still Searches For A
Candidate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While Massachusetts Republicans searched for a
candidate for what many believe is a hopeless situation, Sen.
Edward M. Kennedy raised $1.32 million in preparation for his
re-election bid.
   Federal Election Commission reports show the Massachusetts
Democrat has $1.01 million in his campaign account after spending
$457,640 during 1987. He raised $826,790 in the last six months of
1987 alone.
   ``We will have a strong candidate,'' promised Joe Malone,
executive director of the state Republican Party, in a recent
interview. ``As of now, discussions are still going on.''
   But it is no secret that the state's few big-name Republicans,
including party chief Raymond Shamie, have no desire to put on a
quixotic campaign against Kennedy, who is seeking his sixth term.
   One potential candidate is Thomas Carhart, a program analyst at
the Pentagon's strategic defense office who is considering a Senate
run. His family is from the Amherst area.
   Carhart said in a recent interview he would decide in several
weeks whether to run.
   Carhart, 44, is a graduate of West Point and the University of
Michigan Law School. He has been a platoon leader in Vietnam, an
analyst at the Rand Corp., the editor of a tax journal, author of a
book about Vietnam, an attorney and a leading activist against the
controversial Vietnam Memorial in Washington.
   But Carhart has little experience in politics and is a virtual
unknown in Massachusetts. Republican Party strategists are quietly
working to get a better-known candidate to run against Kennedy.
   The senator's year-end FEC report showed he received most of his
1987 campaign contributions _ $1.06 million _ from individual
contributors. The remaining $263,000 came from political action
committees.
</TEXT>
