<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OfficerStrength     03-01 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Officer Strength,510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Soldiers Holding up Lots of Brass</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress may be upset about the number of
officers in the U.S. military, but the armed forces of some of
America's closest allies are much more top-heavy, a survey has
found.
   Of 11 nations surveyed by a military journal, only two had a
lower ratio of admirals and generals to active-duty personnel than
the United States _ Austria and West Germany.
   Moreover, the No. 1 country among those surveyed _ Canada _ has
built a military force whose ratio of generals and admirals to
active-duty forces is more than three times that of the United
States.
   The survey was conducted by the monthly magazine ``Armed Forces
Journal'' and the results summarized in its March issue, published
today. The magazine said it contacted the defense ministries
directly or else turned to foreign embassies in Washington for the
information needed to make a comparison of active-duty forces.
   Austria possesses easily the leanest of the military
establishments surveyed, with just 5 generals leading an
active-duty force of 54,700, the survey found. That translates to
just 0.9 generals per 10,000 active-duty personnel, the magazine
reported.
   The next eight countries fall into a range that runs from 4
generals and admirals per 10,000 active-duty personnel to about 9
generals per 10,000. The United States is in this group with a
ratio of 4.9 generals and admirals for every 10,000 active-duty
personnel.
   The final two countries _ Britain and Canada _ are in a class by
themselves, the magazine reported. Britain has 476 generals and
admirals to lead its 320,000 men and women on active duty, or a
ratio of 14.9 per 10,000, while Canada has 141 generals and
admirals for 87,254 active-duty personnel, or a ratio of 16.2 per
10,000.
   At the other end of the scale, West Germany followed Austria
with 199 generals and admirals for its 495,000 on active duty, or a
ratio of 4.0 generals and admirals per 10,000 troops.
   The United States has slightly more than 2.1 million men and
women under arms. As of November, when the information was
compiled, Congress had authorized 1,073 slots for generals and
admirals and 1,057 of those jobs were filled.
   Either number produces the same ratio of roughly 4.9 per 10,000.
   Congress, complaining about what it calls ``grade creep,''
imposed the cap of 1,073 active-duty slots for generals and
admirals in 1981. Lawmakers have refused ever since to raise it
despite repeated Pentagon entreaties.
   Congress also ordered the Defense Department in its fiscal 1987
budget to begin reducing the number of lower-ranking officers in
the military. The Pentagon is under orders to reduce its officer
corps of colonels and captains by 6 percent by fiscal 1990 _ or
more than 18,000 job slots.
   Before the cutting began, the Army, Navy, Air Force and Marine
Corps had more than 308,700 officers on active duty, or roughly one
officer for every 5.9 enlisted personnel. By next September, that
number must fall to 302,620, with additional cuts to follow.
</TEXT>
