<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0117EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-OMB-CreditCards     03-01 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-OMB-Credit Cards,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government, $150 Billion In Red, To Become World's Largest Charge
Card User</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government still prints money on paper for
all debts public and private, but the Reagan administration says it
will gladly take plastic.
   The Office of Management and Budget on Monday announced a new
progam to increase dramatically the government's use of credit
cards _ both for buying and selling.
   Not only will the government start accepting credit cards from
the public for such items as passports and payments on college
loans, but the OMB said it also hopes to develop a plan under which
government officials and purchasing agents will use cards.
   ``Eventually, the Office of Management and Budget will be able
to require that all purchases made (by the government) under $2,500
be by credit card,'' the OMB said in President Reagan's
``management'' report on the federal government.
   In fact, the report itself can be purchased by mail with VISA or
MasterCard, for $6.50. (The president's fiscal 1989 budget costs
$18).
   Budget Director James C. Miller III told a White House news
briefing he did have a few qualms about use of credit cards as an
alternative to legal tender _ for a goverment that was $150 billion
in the red last year.
   But, he added, by allowing citizens to repay their government
debts with credit cards, ``We're collecting some of this (debt)
rather than just letting it ride.''
   Under the expanded program, the government is expected to
process 130 million credit-card transactions annually by 1991, or
$6.5 billion worth, said Joseph Wright, deputy OMB director.
   ``It will make us the largest credit card user in the world,''
Wright said.
   Wright said, however, that the cards won't be accepted for tax
payments _ at least not yet. That would require seeking legislation
from Congress, something the administration isn't now prepared to
do.
   However, Wright said the subject is being explored with the
Internal Revenue Service.
   The government for some time has accepted credit cards for
specified items, including publications of the Government Printing
Office.
   More recently, the Customs Service has accepted credit cards for
duty collection at most U.S. airports and the U.S. Mint is now
accepting them for coin sales.
   The management report also said that the government is studying,
for possible future use, a system under which ``smart cards'' would
be issued by the government to people who receive Social Security
and other payments and benefits.
   ``These cards (would) have embedded on them information about
the cardholder that can be accessed electronically. Potentially
(the) cards could make available funds for food stamps, social
security payments, or grants and control their use electronically
through central computers.''
   And what's to keep the government from running up large interest
payments on its past-due credit card accounts, just like it has
with the national debt?
   ``We're not going to pay (interest) because we're not going to
let them go beyond 30 days,'' Wright said.
</TEXT>
