<DOCNO> AP880301-0010 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0142EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Soviet-Arms Bjt   03-01 0587</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Arms, Bjt,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Hold to Optimistic Timetable for START Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials are optimistic about a
strategic arms accord being reached before a summit this summer
despite President Reagan's remark last week that not enough time is
left.
   The Soviets hope major disagreements in the Strategic Arms
Reduction Talks can be settled at a March 22-23 meeting in
Washington between Secretary of State George P. Shultz and his
Soviet counterpart Eduard A. Shevardnadze.
   ``We remain optimistic,'' said a Soviet diplomat who has been
involved in the negotiations in Geneva on long-range weapons. He
spoke only on condition of anonymity.
   ``We are near the finishing line,'' he said, and ``there is
still plenty of time'' before Shultz and Shevardnadze meet.
   Shultz and Shevardnadze ordered their aides to draft, before
that March meeting, agreements on three areas: verifying
compliance, dismantling weapons, and exchanging data on the
arsenals.
   ``These three drafts constitute the bulk of the work to be
done'' on the treaty, although several major points of disagreement
remain, the Soviet official said.
   Reagan, in an interview published last Friday by The Washington
Post, said he did not think it possible to reach an accord before
the summit, which is expected in late May or early June.
   ``We're not at this moment anticipating that it would be ready
for signature then,' Reagan told the Post. But he said the deal was
possible before he leaves office next January.
   The proposed treaty would cut strategic nuclear arsenals by 35
percent to 50 percent, setting a limit of 6,000 on the overall
number of warheads with ranges of more than 3,400 miles.
   The Soviets are balking at a U.S. demand to limit the number of
warheads on land-based missiles to 3,300 and the number of warheads
aboard so-called heavy missiles to 1,650, according to U.S.
officials.
   And the Soviets want to set a limit on numbers of sea-launched
cruise missiles, above the 6,000 warhead ceiling. U.S. officials
have objected to such a limit, in part because it would be
difficult to verify.
   The Soviet official repeated a remark by Kremlin leader Mikhail
S. Gorbachev that technology exists to detect nuclear weapons
aboard naval vessels, a statement that U.S. experts question.
   ``Such things as sublimits need to be worked out at the highest
political levels,'' such as the Shultz-Shevardnadze meeting in
March, the official said.
   ``The bulk of the work, the technical details, is in the three
drafts and needs to be worked out at the expert level'' before the
tough political decisions, he said.
   The official also said the Kremlin might drop its objections to
tests in space of Reagan's Star Wars missile defense system if some
limits could be negotiated beforehand.
   He said the Soviet Union would countenance some space tests as
long as both sides agreed they did not violate the 1972
Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty.
   The diplomat noted that Reagan and Gorbachev agreed at the
December summit in Washington to abide by the ABM treaty.
   But the joint communique issued at summit did not address
U.S.-Soviet disagreement on the extent to which the treaty
restricted space tests of weapons such as lasers and other devices
that were not in use when the ABM pact was signed.
   The Soviets are seeking a U.S. response to their proposal to set
limits on tests for various Star Wars components such as lasers,
the official said.
   U.S. negotiators have rejected such limits, saying that
compliance would be impossible to verify in space.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
