<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CorpsAircraft     03-01 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corps Aircraft,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Corps Of Engineers Loses Control Of Its Executive Aircraft</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional critic of federal officials'
flying in style on taxpayer-supplied executive aircraft says he's
unhappy with an Army move to clip the wings of the Corps of
Engineers.
   Rep. Mike Synar, D-Okla., expressed his displeasure Monday after
the Army told him the corps had been been stripped of day-to-day
control of three aircraft that have been called wasteful by Army
and congressional auditors.
   James Ambrose, who stepped down Friday as undersecretary of the
Army, said he ordered the executive aircraft placed in a central
pool, forcing the corps brass to compete against other Army
commanders for their use.
   ``The pooled operation, we anticipate, will yield economies,''
Ambrose told Synar's Government Operations subcommittee on
environment, energy and natural resources.
   Lt. Gen. Elvin Heiberg III, the three-star chief of engineers,
told the hearing that ``I concur with the decision made by my boss.
... We'll have to compete.''
   Last summer, the Army Audit Agency said the corps had been using
the aircraft not for emergencies such as floods but for routine and
ceremonial matters, many of them overseas trips on which leaders
were accompanied improperly by spouses.
   Ambrose said that before they can use any of the aircraft,
Heiberg and other corps leaders will have to get flight-by-flight
permission from the director of Army staff in the Pentagon.
   Synar said he was displeased because the director of staff has
been responsible for authorizing travel by corps spouses, who Army
regulations say must have an ``unquestionable official'' role in a
government-financed trip.
   ``Unless he does a better job than he has done with spouse
travel, this isn't going to be much of a safeguard,'' Synar said.
   Heiberg and other corps officials have defended their use of the
aircraft on grounds that they are more efficient than commercial
flights.
   Ambrose's action partially settled an in-Army fight between the
corps and the Army auditors, who said last year that tax dollars
could be saved by selling the planes and having corps officials use
commercial or charter flights.
   Ambrose said the Army would decide later this year whether to
sell the aircraft, including Castle I, the 14-passenger jet that
has been used to ferry key members of Congress on trips to visit
water projects around the nation.
   Before the aircraft can be sold, however, Congress will have to
repeal a law forbidding such a sale. The prohibition was quietly
enacted in December at the behest of one of those flyers, Rep. Tom
Bevill, D-Ala., chairman of the House Appropriations subcommittee
that handles corps funding.
   Bevill said he disagreed with the Army auditors and with similar
findings made over the years by the congressional General
Accounting Office.
   ``All three planes are needed,'' Bevill said. ``They do their
best work when there's floods and emergencies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
