<DOCNO> AP880301-0013 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0209EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Cox-Judgeship     03-01 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cox-Judgeship,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Judgeship Nominee Questioned About Racial Sensitivity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID PACE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. District Judge Emmett R. Cox's handling
of the 1985 vote fraud trial of three Alabama civil rights
activists has come under fire during a Senate Judiciary Committee
hearing on his nomination to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   Morton Stavis, president of the Center for Constitutional Rights
in New York, told the panel Monday that Cox displayed ``an
intolerance toward and a failure to respect'' a black lawyer
involved in the trial and issued rulings that raised questions
about his sensitivity to racial issues.
   Stavis' testimony marked the second time that the vote fraud
trial has been used as the basis for opposing one of President
Reagan's judicial nominees.
   The trial, which civil rights groups charged was part of an
effort by the Reagan administration to intimidate black voters in
the South, ended in innocent verdicts for all three activists.
   It then became the focal point of a 1986 campaign by civil
rights groups against Reagan's nomination of U.S. Attorney
Jefferson B. Sessions III to a federal judgeship in south Alabama.
   Sessions, who was prosecutor at the vote fraud trial, was
rejected by the Judiciary Committee, marking the first time that
one of Reagan's judicial nominees has been voted down in committee.
   While the Sessions nomination drew opposition from a host of
civil rights groups, Stavis was the only witness Monday who
testified in opposition to Cox. The committee did not vote on the
nomination, but Sen. Howell Heflin, D-Ala., who presided at the
hearing, predicted that Cox would win Senate confirmation within a
month.
   Stavis criticized Cox's decision during the 1985 trial to bring
criminal contempt of court charges against Howard Moore, a
California lawyer who represented one of the activists. Cox had
ruled that Moore's questioning of a witness violated his order
barring defense attorneys from raising the issue of selective
prosecution.
   That contempt ruling later was reversed by the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta. Stavis, who represented Moore, told
the Judiciary Committee that ``there was absolutely no foundation''
for the contempt charge.
   Cox acknowledged Monday that the appeals court had ``fairly
concluded'' that he had been wrong to cite Moore for contempt.
``They educated me on the law of criminal contempt,'' he said.
   Stavis also charged that Cox had shown a lack of racial
sensivitity by refusing to delay the trial for two weeks so the
jury could be selected from a jury pool drawn from the Selma, Ala.,
area, which had a much larger percentage of blacks than did the
jury pool drawn from the Mobile, Ala., area.
   Cox declined during the hearing to respond specifically to
Stavis' testimony about the jury selection issue. But he told
reporters afterwards that racial considerations played no part in
his handling of the case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
