<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Brazil-Sanctions     03-01 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Brazil-Sanctions,420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Cites Progress, Puts Off Sanctions Against Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration says it won't go
forward with $105 million in retaliatory sanctions against Brazil
at this time, citing ``some progress'' in relaxing trade barriers
against U.S. computer software sales.
   The administration earlier this year announced that it would
slap the duties on a variety of Brazilian products to protest the
restrictions.
   However, since then there has been a thaw in U.S.-Brazilian
relations, both on the trade and Third World debt front.
   A new software law in Brazil, which calls for a new set of
regulations governing imports of foreign-made computer programs and
other software, helped prompt the administration decision to delay
its sanctions.
   U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter, citing ``recent
progress,'' in the dispute, said in a statement on Monday: ``The
United States will delay sanctions against Brazil pending review of
the implementing regulations for Brazil's new software law.
   ``Subsequent to that, we will review our options and consider
what actions, if any, to take.''
   The list of specific Brazilian exports to be targeted had never
been released, even though a preliminary list included
Brazilian-made shoes, aircraft, automobiles and electronics
equipment.
   The issue of access of U.S. computer software companies to
markets in Brazil ``will remain a high priority for the U.S.
government,'' Yeutter said.
   ``Recent Brazilian actions, and discussions with representatives
of the government of Brazil, demonstrate progress on this issue,''
Yeutter said. ``Some of our immediate concerns have now been met.''
   The new Brazilian law will regulate commercial sales of all
software, both domestic and foreign. It calls for new regulations
to be issued by April 19.
   ``As a result, we feel it would be inappropriate and
counterproductive to proceed with our previously announced plans to
retaliate,'' Yeutter said. ``That proposed action will be placed on
hold until we have a chance to evaluate Brazil's response on the
software regulations.''
   Adding to the atmosphere of eased relations between Brazil and
its key trading partners has been Brazil's participation in
negotiations on a loan restructuring package.
   Key portions of that pact were reached over the weekend as
Brazil, Latin America's largest debtor nation, agreed to make a
$700 million interest payment to make it current for all of 1988
and the last quarter of 1987.
   Brazil hasn't repaid any principal on its $114 billion foreign
debt since 1983. In February 1987, it decreed a moratorium on
interest payments but late last year agreed to resume them.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
