<DOCNO> AP880301-0017 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0215EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-CapitolMice Bjt   03-01 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Capitol Mice, Bjt,790</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON WIRE: Capitol Mice Foil Cat, Startle Ambassador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cat came to stay but the Capitol mice
played anyway _ around an ambassador's feet.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., has a mouse problem.
   He shares it with other members of the Democratic leadership who
occupy offices in the oldest part of the Capitol, the part that
survived after the British burned the building in 1814.
   The mice call it home but House leaders and their staffs call it
disturbing.
   So traps were set and baited with cheese.
   The mice ignored then.
   Then Foley called in reinforcements.
   He brought his cat to work, a feline with a proven reputation as
a champion mouser.
   The cat moved in with the Foleys a dozen years ago while they
were on vacation in the Caribbean.
   Since the cat had chosen them, and not they the cat, they gave
the animal an appropriate name _ ``Roger the Lodger.''
   Roger was brought in to lodge for awhile in Foley's office suite
on the first floor of the Capitol, sharing quarters not only with
the mice but with Foley's dog, Alice, who accompanies the majority
leader to work on a daily basis.
   Expectations ran high for Roger. But the results were poor.
   Roger the Lodger bagged no mice.
   The mouser's failure was underscored on Monday during a meeting
in an adjoining office used by Rep. David Bonior, D-Mich., the
chief deputy Democratic leader.
   Bonior was conferring over coffee with Jan Kinast, the Polish
ambassador to the United States.
   Suddenly a mouse darted out from behind a small chest.
   It ran across the carpet and disappeared under the conference
table, literally at the startled ambassador's feet.
   The House leadership is looking for a new weapon in its war
against mice.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The Senate's sergeant at arms _ Henry Giugni _ became an instant
celebrity last week when he followed orders and arrested Sen. Bob
Packwood, R-Ore.
   Giugni's posse had Packwood carried onto the Senate floor to
constitute a quorum so consideration could continue of a
controversial campaign financing act, then besieged by a filibuster.
   It was not the first time a senate sergeant of arms has been the
focus of attention by the Senate and the press.
   On Feb. 7, 1935, the Senate voted to fire Sergeant at Arms David
S. Barry.
   Barry's offense: The 72-year-old former journalist had written a
magazine article entitled ``Over the Hill to Demagoguery'' which he
had thought would be published after he left office.
   But the publication date was moved up and when the article
appeared it began with these words:
   ``Contrary, perhaps, to the popular belief, there are not many
crooks in Congress; that is out and out grafters, or those who are
willing to be such.
   ``There are not many senators or representatives who sell their
votes for money, and it is pretty well known who those few are.
   ``But there are many demagogues.''
   Senate Republican leader Bob Dole, who recounted the incident on
the Senate floor recently, said the article probably would have
been ignored had it been written by a journalist.
   ``But for the Senate's sergeant at arms it was an entirely
different matter,'' Dole said. ``So the Senate voted him out of
office, less than a month before his term would have ended.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   It doesn't take much time. And it doesn't cost much money. And
it makes somebody somewhere happy.
   So Congress over the decades has busily subdivided the calendar
into days, weeks, months and even years in honor of some historic
figure, event, cause, profession or industry or thing.
   It was in that spirit early last month that Rep. Robert W.
Kastenmeier, D-Wis., offered a resolution designating the week of
Oct. 30 through Nov. 5 as National Jukebox Week.
   ``As a rich chronicler of music, culture and technology, the
jukebox is without peer,'' Kastenmeier informed the House. ``It has
brought great joy and memories to generations of Americans. Its
popularity is unequaled in the eyes of young and old alike.''
   Besides, he said, the juke box is on the advent of its
centennial.
   The very first juke box, a wax cylinder Edison phonograph fitted
with a coin slot, was installed in San Francisco's Palais Royale
Saloon in 1889.
   Just the thing, the Kastenmeier resolution said, to be observed
``with appropriate programs, ceremonies and activities.''
   But if juke boxes bore, perhaps doll houses are the ticket.
   Rep. Robert C. Smith, R-N.H., wants to designate the week of
October 9 as National Dollhouse Week.
   After all, Smith contended, ``about 10 percent of our population
has some involvement with dollhouse and miniature collecting.''
   The source of that statistic, he disclosed, is the Miniatures
Industry Association of America.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
