<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Senate-Afghanistan     03-01 0398</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Senate-Afghanistan,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Resolution Says No Aid Cutoff Until Soviets Completely Out</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd is
hinting he may delay Senate consideration of the new U.S.-Soviet
nuclear arms reduction treaty if the White House ends U.S. military
aid to insurgents in Afghanistan before a complete and final Soviet
troop withdrawal.
   Byrd, D-W.Va., commented shortly before the Senate voted 77-0 on
Monday to adopt a resolution urging the White House not to cut off,
suspend or reduce military aid to the Afghan resistance ``until it
is absolutely clear that the Soviets have terminated their military
occupation.''
   The non-binding resolution also urged formation of an interim
government in Kabul acceptable to the Afghan resistance.
   Byrd said the resolution is intended to ``send a clear message''
to the administration that the Senate wants no part of any
U.S.-Soviet agreement in which U.S. aid to the Afghan resistance is
ended merely on Moscow's promise to withdraw its troops, not on
their actual removal.
   Byrd and Sens. Gordon Humphrey, R-N.H., and Steven Symms,
R-Idaho, took strong exception to congressional testimony last week
in which Robert A. Peck, an assistant deputy secretary of State,
said the United States would be prepared, ``if completely satisfied
with the overall agreement, to prohibit U.S. military assistance to
the Afghan resistance.''
   Peck also testified last week: ``We will continue our assistance
... until that support is no longer needed. But the question of
when to cut off aid is one that should be left to the president.''
   Symms said Peck's testimony leads many to fear a ``superpower
deal ... that will allow the Soviets to gain politically what they
could not gain on the battlefield.''
   Byrd said, ``I'd like to know what's in these agreements before
I call up the INF (Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces) treaty,''
Byrd said.
   ``I don't want the Senate kept in the dark,'' he added.
   The INF treaty, which calls for the elimination of medium-range
nuclear missiles from Europe, is under examination by the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee and two other Senate panels.
   It could reach the Senate floor for action by the end of March
or early April.
   Byrd supports Senate ratification of the treaty without
reservations that would force its renegotiation. He said last week
that includes a reservation linking implementation of the pact to
complete Soviet withdrawal from Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
