<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ScienceEducation     03-01 0589</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Science Education,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>International Study Shows American Students Far Behind</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Students in most other countries are far
better educated in science than are American students, according to
an international study that one U.S. official said emphasizes ``the
troubled state of science education in the United States.''
   In a report released Monday by the National Science Foundation,
U.S. students at three different grade levels all scored well
behind those from most other nations, with some American
14-year-olds scoring at the level of the ``scientifically
illiterate.''
   ``For a technologically advanced country, it would appear that
(in the United States) a re-examination of how science is presented
and studied is required,'' said the study, which was conducted by
the International Association for Evaluation of Educational
Achievement, an association of research centers.
   Erich Bloch, director of the National Science Foundation, said
of the study: ``These findings emphasize again the troubled state
of science education in the United States. ... America's future as
a world technological and economic leader and the quality of life
we enjoy depend on confronting the real problems in science
education with vigor, determination and a sense of urgency.''
   The study was conducted by the International Association for
Evaluation of Educational Achievement, an association of research
centers. Early findings, which compared the United States only with
Japan and England, and with partial findings from Israel and
Sweden, were reported by The Associated Press in September.
   The comparative study was based on tests administered to 204,308
students at 7,581 schools in 24 countries between 1983 and 1986.
The tests were given at three academic levels: near the end of
primary grades, at about age 10; at grades eight and nine, about
age 14; and in the final year of high school.
   Among 10-year-olds, students in Japan, Korea and Finland scored
around 15.4 out of 24 possible correct answers. U.S. students
scored just below the middle of the scale at 13.2.
   Among 14-year-olds, Hungary, Japan and the Netherlands scored at
the top, while Americans ranked third from last with a mean score
of 16.5 out of 30 possible correct answers. The lowest-scoring
quarter of this age group, the report said, ``were scientifically
illiterate'' with their test scores ``at chance level.''
   Tests for the high school seniors were given only to those
specializing in science subjects. Hong Kong, England and Singapore
scored highest, with the United States students receiving among the
lowest marks.
   In an analysis of the U.S. results, the report said: ``The
achievement of advanced science students in biology, chemistry and
physics is low. The biology results are especially low.''
   The study said that the United States, along with Australia,
Canada, Finland, Italy and Sweden, has ``many poor scoring schools
and it would seem likely that the school authorities would have
grounds for concern.''
   Secretary of Education William J. Bennett, responding to a
report of the study, said it supports an assessment on U.S.
education that his department released last week.
   ``Now comes this international report card showing that compared
to students in other countries, American elementary and high school
students are not just in a `dead stall,' they're doing even
worse,'' Bennett said. ``They're in reverse and going downhill.''
   The international study also compared the difference in science
achievement based on gender. In grades five and nine, boys scored
higher than girls in all countries. For grade 12, boys outperformed
girls in biology, chemistry and physics, except in Australia, Hong
Kong and Sweden, where girls had top marks in biology.
</TEXT>
