<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0224EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-GlassMerger     03-01 0392</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Glass Merger,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Owens-Illinois Acquires Most Of Brockway At $60 A Share</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Owens-Illinois Inc. has acquired virtually all
outstanding shares of Brockway Inc. stock to the tune of about $740
million and is on the verge of creating the nation's largest glass
container company, offcials say.
   Monday's move followed a decision by the government against
appealing a court decision in favor of the merger.
   Owens-Illinois spokesman Sam Allen said the company bought
12,337,630 shares of common Brockway stock, 98.7 percent of the
outstanding shares. Allen said the actual merger will likely occur
in a couple of weeks, at which time the remaining shares will be
purchased.
   Robert Lanigan, chairman of Owens-Illinois, said the merger will
make the combined operations and the glass container industry
``significantly more competitive with can, plastic and other
materials in the worldwide packaging business.''
   Susan Ticknor, spokeswoman for the Federal Trade Commission,
declined to specify why the agency decided against appealing a
decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals that, in effect, paving the
way for the merger.
   However, Ms. Ticknor said the FTC has scheduled administrative
hearings on potential anticompetitive effects of the merger. And
she said Owens-Illinois could be ordered to divest itself of
Brockway holdings if the agency determines that the merger violates
antitrust laws.
   The Toledo, Ohio, based Owens-Illinois proposed to buy Brockway,
of Jacksonville, Fla., last September for $60 a share.
   The merger will make the combined company the nation's largest
manufacturer of glass containers, which are used in packaging foods
and beverages. The largest producer of glass containers has been
Anchor Glass Container Corp., according to the FTC.
   Owens-Illinois officials have said the only weapon the glass
container industry has against plastics and metal packaging
producers is competitive pricing and the merger with Brockway is
designed to increase productivity and lower costs.
   The FTC had attempted in court to block the merger, saying it
might violate antitrust laws by substantially reducing competition
and creating the conditions for price discrimination.
   However, last month U.S. District Court Judge Joyce Hens Green
denied the FTC's request for a preliminary injunction on the basis
that the agency had failed to prove the deal would harm competition.
   And last Friday, the appeals court sided with Judge Green,
saying that the agency had failed to make its case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
