<DOCNO> AP880301-0022 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Jackson'sVotes     03-01 0708</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Jackson's Votes,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Showing in Maine Seen as Breakthrough</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson's surprise second-place finish
in the Maine Democraatic caucuses was a ``breakthrough,'' proving
conclusively that he has broadened his appeal, his backers say.
   Jackson reaped 28 percent of the vote in the Maine contest on
Sunday, on the heels of respectable showings in three other states
which, like Maine, all have voting age black populations of 1
percent or less.
   The Maine results came after he spent just $13,000 in the state
and campaigned there only two days. The well-funded winner, Michael
Dukakis, is well known to Maine voters as governor of nearby
Massachusetts, and he captured 42 percent.
   ``It shows that we can get votes in any part of the country,''
Jackson said Monday in Pembroke, N.C. ``It shows we have the
broadest base...and our campaign has the strongest appeal.''
   ``The Rainbow Coalition is coming alive,'' he added, invoking
the name he has given to his target constituency of all minority
groups and the economically oppressed.
   Political consultant Ann Lewis, an informal Jackson adviser,
called Maine ``the most significant breakthrough state for him so
far.''
   Bob Beckel, a top political strategist for Walter Mondale's 1984
presidential bid, said Jackson's performance is``a sign of a
growing movement among non-black supporters of Jackson, and for
people to try to ignore it, they're making a great mistake.''
   In Iowa and New Hampshire, Jackson finished fourth out of seven
contenders. In Minnesota he was second with 20 percent in last
week's caucuses.
   In Maine, Jackson's 28 percent contrasted to the 1 percent that
he got when he ran in 1984.
   Campaign manager Gerald Austin said he knew his candidate would
do well in Maine and the goal was to come in second. But Jackson's
margin, well above the single-digit results of the other Democrats,
was better than he had anticipated.
   He credited it to organizing by students and dedicated
volunteers _ the campaign had only two paid staff people in Maine.
   ``It was basically, totally indigenous and independent,'' he
said of the Maine organization. ``They did things on their own.''
   Jackson's core support came out of the university communities in
Orono and Portland, and striking paper workers in Jay, he said.
   He carried Portland and another of the state's largest cities,
Bangor.
   Jackson bought $10,000 worth of TV ads in the days before the
caucuses, and $2,000 on radio. The 10-second TV spots showed the
winning U.S. goal in the 1980 Olypic hockey game against the
Soviets, with an announcer saying as Jackson's picture appeared:
``Just like in the Olympics, one man can make a difference.''
   Beckel, who called Jackson ``one of the best hidden political
stories of the year,'' commented also, ``People don't want to buy
the notion that Jesse Jackson has got a message that people listen
to and that has begun to rise above his blackness ... Somebody in
this party has to to recognize that this is a significant guy in
the party.''
   Political analyst William Schneider, however, questioned whether
Jackson's white votes are really the downtrodden whom he has
targeted. He cited exit polls from Iowa and New Hampshire showing a
good portion of his votes came from upscale, well-educated
liberals, ``the radical chic.''
   But he also noted that Jackson has a strong message that appeals
to many Democrats.
   ``There is no other candidate in the race who really stands for
the old politics ... what I would call Democratic fundamentalism,''
as espoused by the late Sen. Hubert Humphrey, Sen. Edward Kennedy,
D-Mass., and New York Gov. Mario Cuomo, said Schneider.
   Beckel said people ``consistently underestimate'' Jackson.
   ``He's the most charismatic candidate in the field. He's got a
message that's concise, that does not change from place to place.''
   Maine Democratic chairman Rick Barton said timing was a key for
Jackson.
   Jackson's successful appearance at the University of Maine in
Orono on Feb. 11, just after Iowa's caucuses and just before the
New Hampshire primary, was ``just the right time ... when Maine
Democrats were starting to lock in,'' he said.
   Barton said Jackson probably also picked up about 5 percentage
points from people who defected from the flagging campaigns of Paul
Simon and Hart.
</TEXT>
