<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan-St.Patrick'sDay     03-01 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-St. Patrick's Day,0175</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Retransmits a0460 to fix cycle designation</NOTE>
<HEAD>President Takes Note of St. Patrick's Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan has issued an early St.
Patrick's Day message, saying he wanted to acknowledge ``the world
of debt we owe to the Irish people.''
   Although his message came two and a half weeks ahead of time,
Reagan on Monday took note of the March 17 commemoration, saying
the Irish people ``have created and perpetuated a unique heritage
of faith and freedom, of humor and hope, of scholarship and
sanctity and sacrifice.''
   Reagan, who is of Irish ancestry, went on to say:
   ``With faith and fearlessness, St. Patrick brought Christianity
to Ireland a millennium and a half ago. The annals reveals the
Irish people's eagerness to embrace the faith and to keep it; that
trait remains to this day, a tribute to the Apostle of Ireland and
to his flock in every generation.
   ``May America and Ireland always cherish each other and the
kinship in which we hold St. Patrick's Day.''
</TEXT>
