<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0238EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Mecham'sDay Bjt   03-01 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mecham's Day, Bjt,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meetings and Phone Calls, And Not Much Time For
Impeachment-Watching</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCOTT McCARTNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLENDALE, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a far cry from the Capitol, but it's
got most of the comforts of home.
   Impeached Gov. Evan Mecham still goes to work early and stays
late. But his office-in-exile is in a house he once lived in,
across an alley from a hay barn in the far reaches of this Phoenix
suburb.
   His days are filled with meetings and phone calls, he says,
leaving not much time to follow his televised impeachment trial,
which opened Monday in the state Senate.
   ``No, I didn't watch,'' Mecham said. ``I've been busy. I've got
a lot to do.''
   Mecham met with supporters and attended a meeting downtown. He
took time to hold a news conference in what used to be a sunken
living room. But he didn't hang on every vote in the Senate, which
on Monday decided the House's impeachment document was sufficient
for trial.
   ``Frankly, I haven't tracked the vote and I haven't tried to
interpret anything,'' he said.
   His paid staff of five worked on one side of the
7,000-square-foot ranch-style house while volunteers worked on the
other side to raise money for the governor's legal defense and
recall election campaign.
   Plans were being readied for a Wednesday night rally. Some 300
phone calls come in each day, spokesman Tanner Brown said.
   The house was converted into office space before Mecham was
impeached Feb. 5 and replaced by acting Gov. Rose Mofford, the
former secretary of state.
   Outside, a simple sign identifies the ``Governor Evan Mecham
Headquarters,'' and adds, ``Office Space Available. Inquire
Within.'' The building sits between a farm full of sheep, chickens
and roosters, and a Mormon church.
   Police sometimes guard the front door, and a security system is
in place. Monday's proceedings made the switchboard light up, a
receptionist said, including a series of obscene phone calls.
   Mecham said he won't venture downtown to the Senate unless it's
necessary.
   ``When my attorney tells me I should be there, I'll be there,''
he said.
   He said he was disappointed the Senate chose not to grant
requests for a delay in the trial since his new chief counsel has
been on the case less than a week, but was confident in his defense.
   ``We have no choice. We have a time to get ready by,'' he said.
   ``I feel confident we'll be able to get our case out and I think
we'll be successful,'' the governor said. ``If the decision is made
on the evidence, I expect to get 29 votes.''
   One member of the 30-member chamber is absent from the trial
because of illness. A two-thirds vote is needed to convict Mecham.
   Mecham was impeached on allegations of concealing a $350,000
campaign loan, misusing $80,000 from a special fund and attempting
to thwart an investigation of an alleged death threat involving a
state official.
   He also has been indicted in state district court on six felony
counts involving the $350,000 loan, which amounted to about a third
of his campaign funds, and faces a criminal trial March 22. Mecham
also faces a recall election May 17.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
