<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0239EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-NATO-Thatcher     03-01 0426</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NATO-Thatcher,0439</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher Turns Chilly Lest Gorbachev Woo The West Too Well</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-NATO Summit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher has
turned distinctly chilly toward Mikhail S. Gorbachev ahead of this
week's NATO summit here, apparently worried the Soviet leader may
be wooing the West too well.
   ``The Russian bear was easier to deal with when it looked more
like a bear than it does now,'' aides quoted Mrs. Thatcher as
telling a private meeting of NATO ambassadors on Feb. 17.
   ``The nicer the Russians get, the more dangerous they are.''
   Her remarks underlined the dilemma of the right-wing British
leader who has developed a warm personal relationship with
Gorbachev.
   She now appears in a bind over how to keep encouraging
Gorbachev's internal reforms without also encouraging sentiment for
a further erosion in nuclear weapons and military spending in
Western Europe on grounds the Soviet Union is no longer much of a
threat.
   Thatcher aides deny she has done a U-turn on the Soviet leader
she once hailed as someone ``I can do business with,'' and who gave
her a red carpet welcome on an official visit in Moscow last spring.
   But British officials acknowledge alarm over Gorbachev's
relatively benign image in the West.
   Lord Carrington, NATO secretary-general, indicated that
Gorbachev may succeed in dividing the 16-nation North Atlantic
Treaty Organization by generating complacency.
   ``It is rather a curious paradox that it's much easier to hold
the alliance together when they're frightened than when they're
not,'' Carrington said in a recent British Broadcasting Corp. radio
interview.
   ``But the fact still remains that there is an enormous military
potential on the other side of the Eastern border.''
   Polls indicate a more relaxed attitude among West Europeans to
the neighboring Communist giant under the urbane Gorbachev.
   A survey by Datagroep of The Netherlands among 6,064 people in
nine West European countries last spring indicated that nearly
two-thirds thought that public views of the Soviet Union had
recently grown warmer.
   Mrs. Thatcher, who has been among Gorbachev's most outspoken
admirers in the West, appears to have helped the shift in public
opinion.
   After her Moscow visit last spring a Gallup sounding reported
that 58 percent of Britons thought the Soviet Union ``really wanted
to be friendly with the West.'' Just 33 percent thought Soviet
advances should be treated ``with the greatest suspicion.''
   Britain's Economist weekly commented: ``Could that in part be a
result of the flattering attentions the prime minister has been
happy to receive from Mr. Gorbachev?''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0027 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0240EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-DemocratsDebate Bjt   03-01 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Democrats Debate, Bjt,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Is Main Target In One Of Campaign's Liveliest Debates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WILLIAMSBURG, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate-a-day Democratic
presidential field was scattered across the Super Tuesday landscape
today after a forum in which Rep. Richard Gephardt was singled out
for attacks on his trade policy, tax vote and the contributions he
has taken from special interests.
   In one of the liveliest debates of the campaign, the Democrats
spelled out differences on trade, taxes and foreign debt with
bare-knuckled zest, sparing not even the moderator who was chided
by Jesse Jackson for asking ``a race-based question.''
   After the third Democratic debate in as many days, the
contenders were campaigning in states that will hold primaries or
caucuses on March 8, the most delegate-rich day in the history of
presidential politics.
   Shortly after Monday's debate ended, Gephardt flew South to meet
with former President Jimmy Carter in Georgia and receive the
endorsement of two former governors of South Carolina.
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr. was campaigning in Virginia and Kentucky;
Jackson in Maryland and North Carolina; Gov. Michael Dukakis in
Maryland, former Colorado Sen. Gary Hart in North Carolina; and
Illinois Sen. Paul Simon in the state of Washington.
   Gephardt took heat for his acceptance of campaign contributions
from political action committees, for his vote for President
Reagan's 1981 tax cut and for his trade policy.
   When Dukakis criticized Gephardt for taking PAC contributions,
the Missouri congressman retorted that to suggest that members of
Congress would ``take direction on how to vote is an affront.''
   Then Gephardt said he was certain the Massachusetts governor
accepted contributions from people who did business with his state,
which prompted Dukakis to reply, ``I am not running around the
country beating up on the establishment.''
   Gephardt said he often got contributions from people even though
they opposed his position on individual issues.
   Jackson interjected that ``lobbyists would lose their jobs if
they gave money continuously against the interests of who they were
working for.''
   ``Do you think the Reagan-Gephardt tax bill of 1981 was fair?''
asked Gore.
   The senator from Tennessee kept repeating the question and
Gephardt kept saying, ``Are you finished?''
   Finally, Gephardt said he thought the bill was fair because it
cut taxes for middle-income families.
   When Gore asked his question once again, Gephardt snapped, ``Can
you hear, Al?''
   During an exchange on how to deal with Mexico's foreign debt,
Dukakis said the oil import fee supported by Gephardt would ruin
the Mexican economy.
   ``Are you running for president of Mexico or America?'' asked
the congressman.
   ``If I'm president of the United States, I'm going to pay
attention to that country,'' responded Dukakis.
   Twice, Hart interjected, ``Let the record show, Gov. Dukakis
didn't answer the question.''
   Simon passed up the debate, which was held on the campus of the
College of William and Mary and was sponsored by the Democratic
Leadership Council, an organization of Democratic officials who
banded together out of concern over what they saw as the party's
leftward drift and the failure of its presidential candidates to
appeal to voters in the South and West.
   One of the most dramatic exchanges took place when moderator
Judy Woodruff, chief Washington correspondent of the Public
Broadcasting Service MacNeil-Lehrer News Hour, asked Gore why he
hadn't been ``nearly as vocal talking about the differences between
yourself and Rev. Jackson. Would that be because you don't want to
offend his black supporters?''
   Gore replied that ``the reason is he doesn't have a record to
talk about in public life.''
   Gore went on to say he had disagreed with Jackson on issues such
as defense spending.
   Jackson was bristling and he turned to Woodruff and said: ``That
is a race-based question. ...
   ``I am a bona fide Democrat. I have registered more Democratic
voters than anyone on this stage. I am the reason why some
Democrats are on this stage, because of that work. ... My race is
self-evident and my leadership is obvious.''
</TEXT>
