<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0241EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NewspageStocks     03-01 0135</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Newspage Stocks,0137</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Reach Post-Crash High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market has jumped to its highest level
since the October market meltdown.
   Analysts said there was no major economic news to account for
the burst of stock-buying on Monday that sent the widely watched
Dow Jones industrial average up by 48.41 points to 2,071.62. But
they said the market continued to be buoyed by the brisk pace of
takeover bids in recent weeks.
   On the New York Stock Exchange, seven stocks rose for every two
that fell. Investors traded 236.05 million shares on the NYSE.
   The previous highest closing since the Oct. 19 crash was
2,051.89 on Jan. 7. The Dow industrials finished February some 333
points above the close on Black Monday, when the Dow plunged a
record 508 points.
