<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Violence,0184</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Near Bus Carrying Soldiers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb apparently detonated by
remote control exploded today near a bus carrying military
personnel, damaging the bus and nearby homes but causing no
injuries, police said.
   The blast occurred at 6:10 a.m. in Benoni, about 20 miles east
of Johannesburg. It sent shrapnel against the bus, collapsed the
ceilings of two nearby homes and shattered the windows of other
houses, police said.
   An air force spokesman, Commandant Koos Smit, said the bus was
en route to Pretoria, with 18 army, air force and medical personnel
on board.
   There was no claim of responsibility, and police made no
accusations.
   Authorities have blamed the outlawed African National Congress
guerrilla movement for many previous bomb attacks, including a
remote-control blast that killed four policemen in Johannesburg
last year.
   By law and custom, white-led South Africa's apartheid policy
establishes a racially segregated society in which the 26 million
blacks have no vote in national affairs. The 5 million whites
control the economy and maintain separate districts, schools and
health services.
</TEXT>
