<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtonInBrief     03-01 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington In Brief,730</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inflation Erodes the Impact of Fines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The penalties for violating government safety
laws has not kept up with inflation and has pulled the enforcement
teeth from many of the laws by reducing the impact of fines,
according to a coalition of consumer groups.
   Penalties for violating various health and safety laws have
remained essentially unchanged over the years, while inflation has
reduced the value of the amounts involved, the Consumer Federation
of America and the U.S. Public Interest Research Group said Monday
in a report.
   ``Letting civil penalties be eroded by inflation operates as if
there were a built-in depreciation schedule in our key health and
safety statutes,'' said Michael Waldman of the group Public
Citizen's Congress Watch, in a statement released with the study.
   As one example the study cited the Occupational Safety and
Health Act of 1970 retains its original penalties of $1,000 per
violation and $10,000 for failure to provide a safe workplace. To
keep place with inflation these would have to increase to $2,970
and $29,700, the report said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Reagan Hopes for Safe Olympics in Seoul, Praises President Roh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says he hopes the Summer
Olympics in Seoul, South Korea, will be incident-free and that he
has confidence in newly inaugurated President Roh Tae Woo.
   In responses to questions submitted by the South Korean
newspaper, Dong-A Ilbo, Reagan said a smoothly run Olympics
competition in September ``is in everyone's interests.''
   ``The prospect of North Korea, or anyone else's, attempts to
disrupt the games through violence is a danger that we and the
Soviets can agree to work against.''
   ``We hope that Moscow will use its close relations with
Pyongyang to urge moderation and to encourage the resumption of
direct North-South contacts on practical ways to reduce tension,''
the president said. ``It is time for the North to eschew violence
and get down to the serious business of resuming dialogue with
Seoul.''
