<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Markets     03-01 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar And Stocks Close Higher In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Late-afternoon dollar purchases by speculators
pushed the U.S. currency higher in uninspired Tokyo trading today,
while stock prices rose in unusually heavy trading on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange, dealers said.
   The dollar opened at 128.45 yen, up 0.33 yen from Monday's
close, following gains on overseas markets. It then edged up in
afternoon trading to close the day at 128.63 yen, up 0.51 yen. Spot
volume totaled a moderate $4.7 billion.
   Despite the large day-to-day rise in the dollar's value, traders
said there was little news that was influencing trading in the U.S.
currency.
   ``The actual range in trading during the day wasn't very great,
only about 0.2 yen,'' said a trader at a Tokyo commercial bank who
spoke on condition of anonymity. ``Most of the increase was due to
speculators trying to cover dollar-short positions in the late
afternoon.''
   The 225-share Nikkei Stock Average, which ended 13 consecutive
days of gains with a decline of 42.06 points Monday, rose 193.09
points, or 0.8 percent, to finish the day at 25,435.90.
   Stocks in many sectors rose, with trading in the market's first
section an exceptionally heavy 1.6 billion shares, the highest so
far this year.
   The second-section index also rose, gaining 1.56 points to hit
an all-time high of 2,927.31.
   Dealers said stocks were spurred upward by a surge on Wall
Street on Monday that pushed the Dow Jones industrial average up
48.41 points to 2,071.61, its highest level since last year's
market crash.
   But they said the market received additional impetus from
bullishness resulting from favorable Japanese economic trends.
   ``Lately, the Tokyo market has been acting more independently of
Wall Street,'' said Michio Katsumata of Nomura Securities, Japan's
largest brokerage. ``Stocks in Tokyo are being buoyed by
predictions of higher Japanese corporate profits in March. Also,
the large amount of capital in circulation is boosting the market,
resulting in an excess of buy orders over sell orders.''
   The announcement today that Japan's unemployment rate in January
rose 0.1 percent from December had little impact on the market,
traders said. January's 2.7 percent rate was down from 3.0 percent
for the same month last year.
</TEXT>
