<HEAD>`Good Morning, Vietnam' First in Sluggish Box Office Weekend</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Winter Olympics on television and a drop in
the number of new movies contributed to a sluggish weekend at the
box office. ``Good Morning, Vietnam'' was the No. 1 film for the
seventh week.
   ``The openings weren't strong and the Olympics did very well in
the ratings, particularly on Sunday. The box office was hurt on
Sunday,'' said John Krier of Exhibitor Relations Co., which
compiles the weekly turnstile figures.
   ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' which got Robin Williams an Oscar
nomination for his portrayal of a raucous Saigon disc jockey,
earned $5.2 million for a nine-week total of $78.5 million. In
second place was Roman Polanski's ``Frantic'' with $4.35 million in
ticket sales.
   It was another good week for Disney Studios, with three movies
remaining in the Top 5.
   In addition to ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney-Touchstone
films has the Sidney Poitier movie ``Shoot to Kill'' in third with
a $3.5 million take and ``Three Men and a Baby,'' fifth in its 13th
week of release.
   The offbeat romantic film ``Moonstruck'' was fourth with $3.3
million.
   The only other new entry in the Top 10 was ``Night in the Life
of Jimmy Reardon,'' a teen movie starring River Phoenix. It earned
$2.7 million in its first week, to place sixth.
   ``Action Jackson'' was seventh with $2.4 million, ``Broadcast
News'' was eighth with $1.349 million, ``She's Having a Baby'' was
ninth with $1.340 million and the creepy ``The Serpent and the
Rainbow'' was 10th with $1.32 million.
   Studios use the weekend box office to determine how well a movie
is doing.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations Co., with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs. Films where costs are not
available are maked n-a.
   1. ``Good Morning, Vietnam,'' Disney-Touchstone, $5.23 million,
1,598 screens, $3,275 per screen, $78.49 million, nine weeks, $21
million.
   2. ``Frantic,'' Warner Bros., $4.35 million, 1,101 screens,
$3,960 per screen, $4.35 million, one week, n-a.
   3. ``Shoot to Kill,'' Disney-Touchstone, $3.51 million, 1,482
screens, $2,371 per screen, $16.92 million, three weeks, n-a.
   4. ``Moonstruck,'' MGM-UA, $3.37 million, 1,178 screens, $2,867
per screen, $41.2 million, 10 weeks, $17 million.
   5. ``Three Men And A Baby,'' Disney-Touchstone, $2.86 million,
1,615 screens, $1,773 per screen, $140.34 million, 13 weeks, $18
million.
   6. ``Night in the Life of Jimmy Reardon,'' 20th Century-Fox,
$2.73 million, 881 screens, $3,107 per screen, $2.73 million, one
week, n-a.
   7. ``Action Jackson,'' Lorimar, $2.43 million, 1,243 screens,
$1,956 per screen, $13.51 million, three weeks, n-a.
   8. ``Broadcast News,'' 20th Century-Fox, $1.35 million, 826
screens, $1,634 per screen, $42.52 million, 10 weeks, $15 million.
