<1ST_LINE>r a PM-StudyAbroad     03-01 0433</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Study Abroad,0444</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Survey Finds Large Increase in U.S. Students Studying Abroad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A rapidly growing number of U.S. college
students are studying abroad, especially in Great Britain,
according to a new study.
   In 1985-86, 48,483 students took courses for academic credit in
foreign schools, according to latest figures released Monday by the
Institute for International Education, the nation's largest higher
education exchange agency.
   In 1982-83, the most recent previous study, 27,145 U.S. students
studied abroad, said Edrice Howard, IIE's senior publications
editor.
   The survey was conducted by mail last year to 2,896 accredited
U.S. colleges and universities, of which 1,898 reported students
earning academic credit for study abroad.
   The study did not explain the rise in popularity of foreign
study. But administrators on U.S. college campuses said that at
least som students may be finding that study overseas is economical
compared with the more expensive U.S. schools where tuitions have
been soaring throughout the 1980s.
   At Beaver College in Glenside, Pa., a school noted for
study-abroad programs that students from some 225 U.S. colleges
participate in, president Bette Landman said she believed the
increase stemmed from ``an increasing sensitivity among students to
foreign study, not only to help their careers, but especially in
the last year or two, to the kinds of understandings we as world
citizens must bring to our lives.''
   The school is sending over 1,700 students from U.S. campuses to
study in the British Isles and Vienna this year, Landman said,
compared with about 750 students in 1980-81.
   At Northern Illinois University, where the numbers of students
in overseas programs have risen at least 10 percent in that period,
Orville Jones, assistant dean of international programs said that
as more students have traveled during their high school years, the
thought of studying overseas is no longer as strange or frightening.
   The survey found that 76.8 percent of U.S. students abroad were
studying in Western European countries.
   The most popular single country, Great Britain, attracted 29.3
percent of all students studying abroad, followed by France with
13.7 percent, Spain with 8.8 percent, Italy 7.8 percent, and West
Germany 6.1 percent.
   Latin America attracted 7 percent, with smaller percentages
studying in Asia, the Middle East, Eastern Europe and Africa.
   Nearly 90 percent of the students were in programs sponsored by
U.S. colleges and universities, the survey found. The most popular
field of study was liberal arts, with 18.2 percent, followed by
foreign language with 16.7 percent.
   Almost two-thirds, or 63.8 percent, of U.S. students abroad were
female, according to the report.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
