<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DartmouthUnrest     03-01 0570</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dartmouth Unrest,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tensions Simmer Anew At Dartmouth Over Conservative Paper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Members of Dartmouth College's
Afro-American Society planned more protests this week after a black
professor came under renewed attack from a conservative student
newspaper.
   The dispute between The Dartmouth Review and music Professor
William Cole threatened to reignite tensions that shattered the Ivy
League campus after a January 1986 sledgehammer attack by Review
members on anti-apartheid shanties on the college green.
   The independent weekly's editor, Christopher Baldwin, who also
was involved in the shanty attack, faces college disciplinary
charges with three other Review members stemming from a
confrontation with Cole last week after the paper printed a cover
story questioning his competence.
   Cole had sued the newspaper for libel for a January 1983 article
that said he ``looks like a used Brillo pad'' and called his music
course ``the most outrageous'' on campus. Cole dropped the suit in
1985 and received no damages. He and the newspaper each claimed
vindication.
   A member of the Afro-American Society, sophomore Kimberly
Robinson, said Monday the newspaper's new attacks were ``obviously
racially motivated.''
   About 250 students held a rally Monday in front of the college
administration building, and Robinson said the Afro-American
Society planned to start a boycott today of Hanover businesses that
advertise in the Review.
   The group also planned a march down Dartmouth's ``Fraternity
Row'' Wednesday night and a rally with students from other area
colleges Thursday.
   Robinson said members of Afro-American Society also met twice
Monday with Dartmouth President James Freedman to detail
allegations of other recent racial incidents on campus.
   In its cover story two weeks ago, the Review revived charges
that Cole is incompetent and printed excerpts from a transcript of
one of his classes that week.
   The story also leveled criticisms at an English professor who is
white. Baldwin said both stories originated from complaints to the
newspaper by students in the classes.
   Baldwin denied the article was racially motivated and said the
Review is the victim of a ``witch hunt'' as it tries to root out
incompetence at Dartmouth.
   He said he and two Review colleagues, with a fourth as an
observer, approached Cole after his class Thursday to advise him
that he could publish an unedited response in the newspaper, but
also to seek his explanation for remarks about the Review he
allegedly made during a class.
   Baldwin said an ``altercation'' ensued. The next day, the Review
published on its cover a picture of Cole during the incident and a
story about it.
   Dartmouth spokesman Alex Huppe said Baldwin and the other three
students face college charges of disorderly conduct, harassment and
violation of the right to privacy because of the confrontation.
   ``To have four students exercise their will over the
institution, we're not going to let four students do that,'' said
Huppe. The four are scheduled to appear before a disciplinary board
next Tuesday.
   Cole could not be reached for comment. He did not return a
message left on his telephone answering machine Monday night.
   Baldwin was among a dozen students involved in a pre-dawn
sledgehammer attack on symbolic anti-apartheid shanties set up by
student protesters in January 1986. After a series of hearings and
appeals, he was sentenced to serve 180 hours of community service.
   The shanty attack sparked sit-ins and protests that continued
all semester and led to a one-day moratorium on classes for
discussions of racism.
</TEXT>
