<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DistrictAttorneys     03-01 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-District Attorneys,0460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>National Association Drug Committee Chief Says War on Drugs
Failing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration's war on drugs has
been little more than a skirmish that failed to stem the movement
of drugs across U.S. borders, says the head of a task force of
prosecutors.
   ``The federal government, despite all the talk, has failed to
stop the drug trafficking across the borders,'' State's Attorney
Richard Daley of Chicago told the National District Attorney's
Association's annual conference Monday. ``And it's increasing each
year. It's not going down.''
   Daley, head of the association's Drug Control Committee, said
Drug Enforcement Administration border patrols capture only 15
percent of the illegal drugs coming into the United States, while
marijuana and cocaine worth $130 billion a year is entering from
Latin American countries.
   Daley also said the federal government is not properly funding
local efforts to prosecute criminals as promised when the war on
drugs was declared.
   ``I don't think it's a war on drugs. I think it's only been
skirmishes,'' Daley said. ``They don't really have a national
policy. That's where it fails.''
   When the Reagan administration first attacked drug use in
America, it set aside $225 million to help local prosecutors, who
handle at least 95 percent of the drug cases in the U.S., Daley
said.
   But this year funding was cut to $70 million, although the drug
problem is getting worse and more violent, he said.
   ``The federal government should put its money where its mouth
is,'' said Daley, the son of the late Chicago Mayor Richard Daley.
``We local prosecutors are on the offensive and we need federal
help.
   ``The drug people are going to corrupt this country more and
more. And you're going to see more violence. You're just seeing the
beginning.''
   The association delegates approved four resolutions dealing with
drug enforcement, including one urging federal funding for local
anti-drug programs to be reinstated to ``adequate levels.''
   They called for combining state and federal efforts to block the
importation of illegal drugs into the United States.
   A third resolution asked the Internal Revenue Service to channel
its efforts toward helping ``prevent drug dealers from enjoying the
profits of their illegal activity.''
   The association also asked for a federal program to help fund
the construction of county and state prisons to house the increased
number of convicted drug offenders.
   Daley said the idea of educating the public to ``just say no''
has gone far enough and the concentration should be placed on
people who have said yes to drugs for years.
   ``I'm not a social worker and I'm not a teacher,'' Daley said.
``I'm a prosecutor.''
</TEXT>
