<1ST_LINE>r i PM-EEC-CentralAmerica     03-01 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-EEC-Central America,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>EEC Prepared To Back Central America Economic Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS WIEGOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HAMBURG, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The European Economic Community is
prepared to back a Central American plan to boost economic
development in the troubled region, West Germany's foreign minister
said.
   Foreign Minister Hans-Dietrich Genscher said Monday the
12-member European Community ``is prepared to take constructive
part in seeing this plan through.''
   Genscher, who was chairing the EEC session, did not say by how
much the community was prepared to raise its relatively small
amount of economic aid to Central America, but emphasized the group
was interested in helping the region achieve stability. EEC aid to
the region last year was about $96 million, community officials
said.
   The Central American states have worked out a $1.4 billion total
aid package they say is needed from foreign doners.
   Earlier, the EEC reaffirmed its support for a regional peace
plan and warned against outside interference in Central America.
   The peace plan calls for an end to outside support for
insurgencies, cease-fires, amnesties and democratic reforms.
   French Foreign Minister Claude Cheysson, who heads the EEC
commission for Latin American relations, also reassured Central
American countries of the EEC's economic support without providing
specific figures.
   The EEC ministers were in Hamburg for a one-day meeting that
centered on Central American issues. They met with representatives
of Costa Rica, Nicaragua, El Salvador, Guatemala, and Honduras _
the countries whose presidents signed the Arias peace plan in
August.
   They also met with representatives from Mexico, Panama,
Venezuela and Columbia, members of the Contadora group that is
trying to mediate an end to violence in the region.
</TEXT>
