<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kenya     03-01 0230</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kenya,0238</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Moi Uncontested, Wins Third Five-Year Term</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel arap Moi won a third
five-year term after no one contested his seat in Parliament and
his ruling party nominated him as the only presidential candidate.
   Moi in effect won the contest Monday after filing unopposed as a
member of Parliament for Baringo Central constituency.
   The filing was a formality since Moi was the sole presidential
candidate nominated Saturday by the ruling Kenya Africa National
Union, which he leads. By law, it is Kenya's only political party.
   Joseph Mwangovya, supervisor of elections, announced Moi's
election after the president presented his election papers during a
ceremony at the Kabarnet High School playground.
   Moi, 63, has been president of this East African nation since
1978, when as vice-president he succeeded the late Jomo Kenyatta,
the country's first leader.
   The constitution requires the president to be a member of
Parliament and for general elections to be held at least every five
years.
   Monday was the deadline for candidates to file papers for the
March 21 general election.
   The party approved 787 parliamentary candidates for the primary
election and 360 of them made it through to the general election,
which will be held by secret ballot for 188 seats.
   Besides Moi, 61 other members of the previous Parliament were
elected Monday because they have no general election opposition.
