<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Koreas 1stLd-Writethru a0502 03-01 0630</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Koreas, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0502,0647</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Roh Appeals To North Korea To Take Part In Olympics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 5th graf pvs ``Less than...'' with one graf to CORRECT
that press photographers hit, sted detained. Pickup 6th graf pvs
``Roh hinted...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SEL5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Roh Tae-woo appealed today
to communist North Korea to take part in the 1988 Olympic Games and
pledged not to impose any conditions on the north's participation.
   ``There is no condition. ... We will welcome you, the breathren
in the north, more than anyone else as the same countrymen and
brothers,'' Roh told an audience of 4,000 people at the Sejong
cultural center in Seoul.
   Roh made the strongest appeal in recent months to the north to
take part in the Games, speaking during celebrations of Samil Day,
a national holiday commemorating a 1919 uprising against Japanese
rule. He also appealed for national reconciliation in the south.
   ``Today, we recall our breathren ... who rose up with bare fists
against the Japanese imperialist colonial rule,'' Roh said.
   Less than one mile away, police today kicked and punched
dissidents and dragged away dozens of them after breaking up an
anti-government protest in Pagoda Park, where the 1919 uprising
took place. Prominent dissident leaders were among those detained.
   Roh hinted at his willingness to meet with North Korean leaders
by saying he was ready to deal with anybody. He repeated that the
south would seek to establish relations with North Korea's main
allies, the Soviet Union and China.
   ``I will meet with anyone, anytime and anywhere and will not
hesitate to open that road however rugged it might be,'' he said.
   The new president, formally sworn in Feb. 25, said the Olympic
Games could help speed reunification of the divided Korean
peninsula.
   North Korea is demanding to co-host the Olympic Games and says
it will boycott the Games if its request is denied.
   South Korea and the International Olympic Committee have
rejected the demand, but said the north could stage five events if
it takes part in the Seoul events.
   The two nations have existed since 1948 and fought the bloody
Korean War from 1950 to 1953. The bitter rivals have clashed
repeatedly over the years.
   Roh also appealed to the South Korean opposition to work with
his government in ending decades of authoritarian rule and
introducing full democracy. ``The curtain has been raised for the
era of national self-esteem in which democracy will blossom,'' he
said.
   Roh, a former general, won the first democratic presidential
elections in 16 years last December with 36.6 percent of the vote
after rival opposition candidates split the opposition vote. Roh
campaigned on the platform that he alone could ensure democracy and
stability.
   About 150 dissidents staged a demonstration today in Seoul's
Pagoda Park to denounce Roh and demand the immediate release of all
political prisoners.
   Protesters waved placards, shouted slogans and applauded
speeches as hundreds of onlookers watched.
   ``Down with the Roh government!'' and ``Release all the
political prisoners!,'' the protesters shouted.
   Scuffles began when plainclothes police tried to detain some
protesters and other dissidents protested.
   A column of about 100 police suddenly charged into the protest,
kicking and punching people to the ground and chasing others.
Police hauled away about 40 dissidents, some of whom were badly
beaten.
   Police also hit a number of press photographers covering the
demonstration.
   The Rev. Moon Ikhwan and several other prominent dissident
leaders were taken away by police. Some of those detained included
radicals released from prison Saturday as part of a government
amnesty.
   Opposition leaders rejected the amnesty as insufficient and have
demanded the release of all political prisoners. The government
says only dissidents guilty of violent crime or subversion remain
in jail.
</TEXT>
