<1ST_LINE>r a PM-KennedyMuseum     03-01 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kennedy Museum,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commissioners Approve $2.3 Million Contract For Construction of
Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   County commissioners have approved a $2.3 million
contract to construct an elevator tower and visitors center in the
former Texas Schoolbook Depository as part of an exhibit on the
assassination of President John F. Kennedy.
   The commissioners voted 3-2 Monday to award the contract to
Thomas J. Hayman Construction Co., which will begin work on the
project as early as this week.
   ``The eyes of the world will be on this project,'' said Lindalyn
Adams, president of the Dallas County Historical Foundation, which
has worked for 11 years to get the exhibit funded. ``As sad as it
is, it is the most important historical site in Dallas.''
   The foundation plans to raise $1.5 million from private sources
for additional renovations on the sixth floor of what is now known
as the Dallas County Administration Building.
   The Warren Commission determined that Lee Harvey Oswald fired a
high-powered rifle at Kennedy from the sixth floor of the building
where he worked on Nov. 22, 1963.
   The elevator tower is intended to carry up to 500,000 visitors a
year to the exhibit without disrupting work at county government
offices.
   Architect Tony Callaway said construction could be completed by
November, but foundation officials say they are unlikely to
schedule the exhibit's opening on Nov. 22, the 25th anniversary of
Kennedy's assassination.
   ``We think it would be inappropriate,'' Adams said.
</TEXT>
