<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Afghanistan     03-01 0438</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Afghanistan,0451</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghan Envoy Accuses Pakistan Of Undermining Peace Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pakistan is trying to undermine U.N.-sponsored
Afghanistan peace talks, Afghanistan's ambassador to the Soviet
Union charged today.
   The ambassador, Mohamadulah Subhani Safi, made the comment on
the eve of a new round of negotiations, telling a news conference
that Pakistan ``doesn't want peace'' for its Afghan neighbors.
   Pakistan, which represents the Afghan guerrillas in the talks
that resume in Geneva on Wednesday, is trying to ``raise issues
that have no relevance to Pakistan,'' he charged.
   Safi complained about Pakistan's demand that any accord signed
in Geneva that would facilitate a withdrawal of Soviet troops from
Afghanistan be linked to the formation of a transitional, coalition
government in Kabul.
   Without such an interim government, unending civil strife would
follow a Soviet pullout, Pakistani diplomats have argued.
   But Safi said the composition of the Afghan government cannot be
dictated by Pakistan or any outside power.
   His comments were echoed in an article in Pravda, the Soviet
Communist Party daily, which said Pakistani leaders have
``apparently forgotten their previous statements that the presence
of the Soviet troops in Afghanistan was the sole obstacle in the
way toward resolving the Afghan problem.''
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has pledged _ if peace talks
are successful _ to begin withdrawing an estimated 115,000 troops
from its embattled neighbor May 15 and complete the pullout in 10
months.
   Gorbachev has said the Kremlin has no intention of trying to
determine the composition of the government left behind when it
leaves the country it entered in December 1979 in support of a
Marxist regime.
   Pravda called it ``an open secret'' that the United States and
its NATO allies have a decisive influence over Pakistan and leaders
of the Afghan resistance.
   ``Their attitude to the Afghan settlement, which is now entering
its crucial stage,'' will be a touchstone for the world to judge
the real worth of their calls for a political settlement of
regional crises of every kind,'' the newspaper said.
   The United States has been ambivalent in its reaction to the
calls for an interim government. A senior American official
returning with Secretary of State George P. Shultz from Moscow
hinted last week that Washington does not back such demands.
   But the U.S. Senate, in a non-binding resolution Monday, urged
the formation of an interim government in Kabul that would be
acceptable to the Afghan resistance.
   There also has been a lack of clear signals on when Washington
would be prepared to cut off its aid to the guerrillas, which was
reported to have totaled about $700 million last year.
</TEXT>
