<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Poor     03-01 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Poor,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$50 Million In Funds For Poor Embezzled, Misappropriated</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local officials pocketed or misappropriated $48
million in state funds to poverty-stricken areas over two years,
using the money to build hotels, apartments and movie houses, an
official report said.
   The State Auditing Administration said the sum represents 6
percent of the $816 million it audited, but officials said they
believe much more was embezzled during 1985 and 1986, the official
People's Daily reported Monday.
   The state allocated more than $1.62 billion to poverty-stricken
areas in the two-year period, the paper said.
   Statistics at the end of 1986 showed that 60 million people in
about 200 counties live below China's poverty line of $40 annually
plus 440 pounds of grain.
   Auditors also found more than 110 people involved in graft cases
totaling more than $91,000, it said.
   The State Council is planning to change distribution of the
funds so that the money will go directly to enterprises that can
improve the area's financial situation.
   In Yanchi county, Ningxia Autonomous Region, more than $243,000
or 42.9 percent of the county's funds for the poor, were used to
build apartments, hotels and cinemas, the paper said.
   In seven cities and counties in Hunan, officials used $132,432
to buy 22 cars and other motor vehicles.
   In Feixian county, Shandong province, officials used $4,300,
collected illegally as administrative fees for the distribution of
the help-the-poor funds, to buy motorcycles, tape recorders and
cameras, the paper said.
</TEXT>
