<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SAfrica-HumanRights     03-01 0302</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-SAfrica-Human Rights,0314</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.N. Human Rights Commission Condemns South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Denouncing what it called South Africa's
``escalation of acts of terrorism'' against blacks, the U.N. Human
Rights Commission has renewed its call for mandatory sanctions
against the white-led nation.
   The 43-country panel, at its annual meeting Monday, urged that
South Africa be economically isolated.
   It said children were increasingly being targeted for repression.
   The United States, Britain and West Germany dissented in the
36-3 vote. Belgium, France, Japan and Portugal abstained.
   The resolution accuses South Africa of continuing ``gross and
cruel violations of human rights'' under apartheid.
   It calls for the immediate release of Nelson Mandela, imprisoned
leader of the outlawed African National Congress guerrilla movement
and freedom for all political prisoners in South Africa.
   ``Massacres and daily killings of defenseless men, women and
children have become the order of the day,'' the resolution says.
   It says human rights violations have risen under a
government-imposed state of emergency that went into effect in June
1986, and urges the U.N. Security Council to impose mandatory
sanctions on South Africa.
   Separately, the commission asked all governments to immediately
cut trade, manufacturing and financial ties with South Africa and
Namibia, or South-West Africa, the territory ruled by South Africa
in defiance of U.N. resolutions.
   The vote was 32-7. The United States, Britain, Belgium, France,
West Germany, Italy and Portugal opposed the draft. Spain, Ireland,
Japan and Norway abstained.
   On Namibia, 34 delegations voted without dissent to accuse South
Africa of wide-ranging oppression there and to call anew for
Namibian independence. Nine Western countries abstained.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
