<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Play     03-01 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Play,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historical Play Under Fire In Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KAREN GILMOUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's new policy of glasnost will
suffer if theaters are barred from performing a play criticized for
its portrayal of Soviet history, eight leading theater figures said.
   The Soviet people have gotten glasnost through suffering and
``that's why any attempts to turn the process backwards ... arouse
deepest concern,'' said the three actors, three producers and two
playwrights in a letter published Monday in the Communist Party
newspaper Pravda.
   Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's policy of glasnost, or more
openness on some issues, has led to greater artistic freedom.
Lately, Soviet artists have produced plays on subjects they would
not have touched before.
   The eight accused several critics of trying to block the staging
of Mikhail Shatrov's play ``Onward _ Onward _ Onward'' by ``pinning
political labels'' on its author.
   Earlier this month, three historians told Pravda the play
compared Soviet founder Vladimir I. Lenin to Josef V. Stalin _
denounced after his death as a dictator _ and portrayed Soviet
history in a negative way.
   The eight said the timing of the criticism indicated it was
aimed at dissuading theaters from booking the play.
   ``It is not by chance that in the provinces they manage to hear
this voice. We have information at the Union of Theater Workers
that this new play, devoted to Lenin, already was banned in some
towns,'' the eight wrote.
   Shatrov's new work takes the form of a debate among Bolsheviks
and their opponents as they look back on Soviet history since the
1917 revolution that brought the Communists to power.
   The historians accused Shatrov of using Lenin as a conduit for
his own ideas and treating the Bolshevik revolution as an accident.
   In their letter, the eight said Shatrov has written about Lenin
for 30 years and his plays have been well received.
   Shatrov's new play was published in January in the literary
magazine Znamya and is scheduled to be performed in Moscow this
spring.
   In the play, Shatrov makes Stalin answer for his purges in which
millions of people perished, but in one scene Lenin accepts blame
for not making certain Stalin could not gain power after Lenin's
death in 1924.
   In the closing scene, Stalin and Lenin are on stage. The desire
is expressed for Stalin to leave, but he will not.
   ``Yes, we do want Stalin to leave, not only the stage, but our
lives,'' the eight said in the letter. ``We want his methods to
vanish, his `morality,' his ways to solve disputes, in particular
in art. But unfortunately, the heritage of the past cannot be
overcome by pronouncements.''
   ``We are not going to defend the play or attack it,'' they
added. ``It hasn't been staged yet and a play without being staged
is a soul without a body. We are concerned with other things.''
   In a seven-paragraph comment on the letter, Pravda said it would
not take sides. ``Pravda's point of view is well known,'' it said.
``It has always been against anybody's monopoly for truth and
against the position `There is my opinion and there is a wrong
opinion'.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
