<DOCNO> AP880301-0058 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0745EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-AmericanStudent     03-01 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-American Student,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Student Petitions Queen In University Exam Dispute</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRISTOL, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An American denied a first-class honors
degree from Bristol University after he was accused of cheating
petitioned Queen Elizabeth II, saying he's honest and is not
getting a fair appeal hearing.
   Francis Foecke, 30, a native of South Bend, Ind., has spent the
last 21 months trying to clear his name after writing his final
exams in mathematics and computer science at the school in the
western city of Bristol in June 1986.
   The London Times said today that he and his English wife,
Priscilla, have spent $53,100 trying to disprove allegations that
he illicitly gained access to examination papers before the
examination.
   ``I do not think I am ever going to get an objective hearing or
an objective decision from the (university's) appeal committee
because they are so close to the people who say I am guilty,'' said
Foecke.
   ``I do not think they realize what a devastating effect this has
had on my wife and me,'' he said. The couple lives in the Bristol
suburb of Clifton.
   When Foecke went to pick up his results after the final exams,
the university registrar told him he was suspected of cheating and
would not receive the degree, the highest the university offers.
   He was told his examination answers too closely mirrored the
lecturers' model answers and that he even had repeated their
mistakes in working out some of the mathematical equations.
   Foecke has maintained he worked up to 18 hours a day for more
than a year preparing for the exams and that he used the methods
taught by his lecturers.
   The Times said the university authorities did not prove Foecke
cheated but stated they believe he may have stolen a key to get
into an office where the papers were stored.
   Foecke's lawyer Guy Dorman said Monday: ``We are petitioning
(the queen) on the grounds of a breach of natural justice.''
   A legal concept enforced by the senior courts, natural justice
says any group making an official ruling, such as the university
authorities, must give a fair hearing to the person involved before
announcing its decision.
   The queen holds the post of visitor at the university. The
visitor is appointed to look after student interests among other
matters but petitions to her in this capacity are rare.
   Because she is a constitutional monarch, the queen would not
make a ruling in her own right in Foecke's case and there was no
comment on the case from Buckingham Palace.
   The petition was sent through Lord Belstead, who holds the post
of Lord President of the Privy Council and is the Cabinet member
responsible for supervising the government's legislative program.
</TEXT>
