<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-IkeTurner     03-01 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Ike Turner,0274</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Musician Ike Turner Surrenders On Warrant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rhythm-and-blues musician Ike Turner,
former husband of pop superstar Tina Turner, surrendered Monday on
a week-old warrant that sought his arrest because he failed to
appear in court to face cocaine charges.
   Turner, 55, was charged with possession of cocaine, conspiracy
to sell cocaine and maintaining a residence for the purpose of
selling cocaine.
   He appeared before Superior Court Judge Gilbert Alston and was
released after posting $15,000 bail.
   Pre-trial motions for Turner and co-defendant Richard Lee
Griffin are set March 18. Two other co-defendants return March 18
for sentencing on conspiracy charges.
   Turner was arrested in June 1985, after he allegedly tried to
sell $16,000 worth of cocaine to an undercover officer in Hollywood.
   A trial is sheduled on another charge March 14 in Santa Monica
Superior Court on separate felony drug-trafficking charges that
include alleged transport of cocaine and possession of rock cocaine
for sale.
   Those charges stem from an August 1987, incident in which Los
Angeles County sheriff's deputies stopped Turner after the car he
was in allegedly was seen moving erratically.
   In October 1986, Turner admitted he had used cocaine every day
for at least 15 years and said he was undergoing rehabilitation.
   Turner formed the Ike and Tina Turner Revue with his wife, and
they produced hits such as ``Proud Mary'' before splitting up in
1976.
   Miss Turner went on to record the 1985 Grammy-Award winning
record and song of the year, ``What's Love Got to Do With It.'' Her
``Private Dancer'' album garnered two other Grammys.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
