<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthSubpoenaed     03-01 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-North Subpoenaed,0422</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-National Security Council Aide Told to Testify at Detroit Drug
Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lt. Col. Oliver North and two other figures in
the Iran-Contra affair were ordered to testify at a federal trial
about an alleged scheme to smuggle marijuana and cocaine into
Michigan from South America.
   The defense lawyer who obtained the subpoenas said North might
be able to provide information about a pilot who flew supplies to
Nicaraguan rebels under contract with the CIA and also was accused
of transporting the drugs.
   North, the former National Security Council aide fired in
November 1986 as the Iran-Contra affair transpired, last week was
ordered to appear March 15 before U.S. District Judge Anna Diggs
Taylor in Detroit.
   Defense attorney Ronald C. Dresnick of Miami said he wanted to
determine North's relationship with Michael B. Palmer. According to
the indictment of Dresnick's client and seven other defendants,
Palmer was aboard a DC-6 aircraft allegedly used to ship drugs into
Michigan last summer.
   Dresnick represents Frank Ivan Turek Correa of Colombia, one of
eight defendants indicted Sept. 24 on charges of conspiring to
import tons of cocaine and marijuana into Michigan between July and
Sept. 6, 1987.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Robert Donaldson, referring to
Dresnick's claim that Palmer was a contract employee of the CIA,
said the defense was a diversion and ``a red herring.''
   Palmer was a vice president of Southern Air Transport, a
CIA-backed operation, Dresnick said. According to court documents,
Palmer contracted with the State Department to fly food and
clothing to the Contra rebels trying to topple the government of
Nicaragua.
   Palmer never was charged in the Detroit case despite his
apparent role in the alleged trafficking.
   Dresnick, in his court filing seeking North's testimony,
provided a page from North's desk calendar dated Aug. 9, 1985, with
a hand-written notation reading: ``DC-6, which is being used (for
Contra supply) runs out of New Orleans, is probably being used for
drug runs into the U.S.''
   The same calendar page also noted a ``meeting with Rob,'' who
Dresnick said he believed was Robert Owen, North's liaison with the
Contras. Both Owen and Palmer also have been subpoenaed to testify
in Detroit, although Palmer's whereabouts are unknown.
   Barry Simon, a Washington attorney representing North, refused
to say Monday night whether North had received the subpoena or to
answer any other questions.
   Witnesses who refuse to answer a subpoena can be subject to a
bench warrant for their arrest.
</TEXT>
