<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OilSpill     03-01 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Spill,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Barge Rolled Upright, More Oil Leaks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATIA BLACKBURN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANACORTES, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a month of preparation, it took
only 17 minutes to roll over an upside-down oil barge that had been
raised from the bottom of Guemes Channel and partially unloaded.
   A floating sheen of oil reached the shore of Shannon Point
before and during the rollover Monday in a release estimated at 300
gallons to 500 gallons of a light grade of oil. Much of it was
sopped up with absorbent materials.
   ``I'm relieved, because it eliminates an ecological time bomb,''
said Coast Guard Lt. Eldo DeLong.
   The 176-foot barge sank Jan. 31 in 130 feet of water four miles
west of Anacortes. It was raised from the bottom Sunday by two
giant derricks.
   The site is about 75 miles north of Seattle on Washington's
inner coast in an area of Dungeness crabs, salmon farms, bottom
fish and other saltwater life.
   Officials had said that 70,000 gallons of oil escaped from the
barge when it sank, and another 344,000 gallons was still on the
barge when the lifting operation began Sunday. Roughly 92,610
gallons of oil was pumped out Sunday night and Monday.
   More oil was to be pumped out of the barge until it was stable
enough to be towed to port.
   Some oil has been detected in kelp beds and in bottom-dwelling
sea cucumbers, and at least one bird has died.
   The barge, operated by Olympic Tug and Barge Co. of Seattle, was
being towed from an oil refinery at Anacortes to Seattle when it
sank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
