<2ND_LINE>PM-Cop Funeral, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0514,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>10,000 Police Say Goodbye To One Of Their Own</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to recast, deleting reference to
`execution-sytle,' picking up at the 3rd graf previous, and adds 2
grafs with Texas memorial service</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAT MILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEAFORD, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A police officer who was shot to death
while he guarded a witness in a drug case was given a farewell by
10,000 police officers amid vows to find his killer and hopes that
his death helps the fight against drug dealers.
   The throng of officers, some from as far away as Texas and Ohio,
lined eight blocks approaching St. James Church on Monday for the
funeral of Edward Byrne, a 22-year-old rookie officer.
   ``If drug trafficking has become so bold that they can engage in
the assassination of a police officer, then our whole society is at
risk,'' Mayor Edward I. Koch said at the funeral service. ``That is
why his death is so important.''
   In his homily, the Rev. Thomas DeVita said, ``Eddie's murderers
need to be pitied and also prayed for. They do not know about the
sanctity of life. They cannot really know or understand what they
have done, even though this is such a terrible sin.''
   Eight officers served as pallbearers as a bagpiper played ``When
the Battle is Over.''
   Police have been rounding up suspected crack dealers since the
murder early Friday in hopes of finding someone who will shed light
on the killing. Officer Peter O'Donnell, a police spokesman, said
that as of Monday night, 108 had been arrested in the South Jamaica
section of Queens, where the killing took place.
   Byrne was guarding the house of a man who had complained to
police about crack dealers in that neighborhood. The officer, who
had been on the force just eight months, was hit by three shotgun
blasts as he sat in a radio car.
   Others attending the funeral included Police Commissioner
Benjamin Ward, Cardinal John J. O'Connor and Officer Steven
McDonald, who was paralyzed below the neck by a gunman's bullet in
1986.
   Koch had taken out a full page in The New York Times on Monday.
It bore Byrne's picture, and called upon the federal government to
take tough measures with foreign governments that allow drug
trafficking.
   Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y., echoed Koch's sentiments outside
the church.
   ``Our nation's leaders appear to be isolated from our people in
the streets who are being killed and from our youngsters who are
becoming addicts,'' said D'Amato. ``Our nation's leaders don't have
the guts to cut off aid to countries run by narcotics dealers such
as Panama.''
   In Texas, more than 2,000 people attended a memorial service
Monday for Officer Gary D. McCarthy, the third Dallas policeman
killed in six weeks.
   He was off duty and moonlighting as a part-time security guard
at a grocery store when he was gunned down Friday during an
attempted robbery. Three men have been arrested, one of them a
parolee who served less than a year of a five-year sentence for
aggravated assault on a police officer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
