<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0910EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LiveCannonballs     03-01 0342</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Live Cannonballs,0353</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Authorities Fear 25 Live Civil-War Cannonballs On The Loose</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Civil War cannonball still capable of
exploding has been turned over to bomb squad investigators by a man
who believes as many as 25 others may have been taken as souvenirs.
   Thomas L. Combs Sr., 64, of Clements, Md., gave a rusted,
six-inch, 120-year-old cannonball to the Maryland Fire Marshal's
bomb squad Monday.
   He became concerned after hearing news reports 10 days earlier
that an identical cannonball that was given to the St. Clements
Island Museum had been found to be live, said fire marshal's
spokesman Bob Thomas.
   The bomb squad determined Combs' cannonball also was live and
took it to a bomb laboratory in Harford County, where investigators
are trying to defuse and salvage the museum's cannonball, which a
Potomac River clammer found in his net.
   Thomas said both cannonballs have a fuse and contain black
powder.
   ``If it detonates, it would send shrapnel from inside in all
directions. (It was) meant to inflict numerous casualties,'' Thomas
said.
   Combs said his cannonball had been collecting dust in a tool
shed behind his home since 1961, when he found it while deer
hunting near Chantilly, Va., Thomas said.
   Combs told officials he took the cannonball from a pyramid of
about 20 to 25 others in a heavily wooded area, and that the stack
appeared to have been left there since the Civil War, Thomas said.
   Combs noticed the pyramid of cannonballs becoming smaller during
his hunting excursions over the next 20 years, until none were
left, Thomas said.
   ``That means that at least 25 citizens might have a (live bomb)
in their house or on their property,'' Thomas said.
   Investigators suspect it was a cache of Confederate munitions,
he said.
   Thomas said the bomb squad would pick up any suspect cannonballs
for free and return them if they can be defused without damage.
   Maryland officials plan to notify state and county authorities
in Virginia about the discovery, Thomas said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
