<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HurricaneCarter     03-01 0578</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hurricane Carter,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carter: Bitterness Would Only Give Prosecution Another Victory</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY28</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former boxer Rubin ``Hurricane'' Carter,
breaking a 12-year silence after finally winning his long battle
for freedom, says he was sentenced to ``a life of living death''
but is not bitter.
   ``For 20 years, I was considered a danger to society, a scourge
upon humanity. I was locked away in an iron cage for not one, but
three lifetimes,'' the former middleweight title contender said
Monday in a news conference.
   Carter was convicted in the 1966 murder of three white men in a
Paterson bar and served 19 years in prison before the indictment
was finally dismissed last week.
   But Carter, 50, dressed in a tan suede jacket, dark tie and navy
blue pants, said during the 90-minute news conference that he
harbors no bitterness over the system that jailed him.
   ``If I have learned anything in my life, it's that bitterness
consumes the vessel that contains it,'' he said.
   The 1966 verdict against Carter and John Artis was overturned,
but the two black men were again convicted in 1976.
   Carter, who was serving a life term, was freed in 1985 by U.S.
District Judge H. Lee Sarokin in Newark, N.J., who found the
conviction was tainted by racism and the witholding of information
by prosecutors.
   The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the judge's 1985 decision, and a
Passaic County judge last Friday signed the papers dismissing the
indictment, as requested by county prosecutors.
   Carter had remained in seclusion, declining to discuss the case
publicly. But on Monday he condemned over-zealous prosecutors, the
horrors of the state prison system, the jailing of innocent people
and racism.
   ``They sentenced me to a life of living death,'' he said. ``And
there is no other way to describe the nature of a prison. Prison
destroys everything valuable in the life of a human being.''
   Artis, paroled in 1981, is serving a six-year prison term on an
unrelated drug charge. His lawyer, Lewis Steel, issued a plea for
Artis' freedom, saying the judge who sentenced him in the drug case
improperly took the voided murder convictions into account in the
sentencing. The drug sentence is on appeal.
   Carter's cause was taken up in the 1970s by celebrities, who
championed him as a symbol of racial injustice. Bob Dylan wrote a
ballad about the case, which played repeatedly in the background
before the news conference.
   Carter refused to blame the trial's prosecutors directly for his
fate, but said ``racism is sleazy'' and referred to Sarokin's
finding that the prosecution made ``an appeal to racism rather than
reason.''
   Since being freed, he said he has worked on his case nearly
every day and his third book, ``No Holds Barred, No Bars To Hold,''
while living in southern New Jersey.
   Carter said he had difficulty understanding how he came to serve
nearly two decades in prison.
   ``One moment I'm a championship prize fighter, the next moment
and 20 years after I'm reviled as a triple murderer,'' he said.
   ``The fact that the most productive years of my life, the ages
of 29 and 50, have been stolen, the fact that I was deprived of
seeing my children grow up, wouldn't you think I would have a right
to be bitter?'' he said.
   But being bitter would give the state another victory, he
said.``That would make me an accomplice to their crime.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
