<HEAD>Newspaper Says Police Quizzed AIDS-Afflicted Porn Star In 1981
Murder Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police recently questioned pornographic film
star John Holmes, hospitalized and gravely ill bed with AIDS, about
a 1981 mass murder for which he was tried and acquitted, a
newspaper reported today.
   The appearance of a new witness and reports Holmes may soon die
from acquired immune deficiency syndrome prompted the bedside
questioning, the Los Angeles Times reported.
   Holmes, 43, a premier male sex film star of the 1970s and early
1980s, made hundreds of sexually explicit films and thousands of
peep shows in his career.
   Citing unnamed sources, the newspaper reported a new witness has
surfaced with information about the grisly beating deaths of four
people in a house in the affluent hillside neighborhood of Laurel
Canyon.
   Mitchell Egers, one of two lawyers who successfully defended
Holmes in 1982, refused to disclose what, if anything, Holmes told
homicide detectives.
   Egers confirmed that Holmes is hospitalized with a serious
illness but would not say if he suffers from AIDS.
   However, the newspaper quoted unidentified sources as saying
Holmes' illness has been positively diagnosed as AIDS, the
incurable disease transmitted through sex, shared hypodermic
needles and transfers of infected blood products.
   Holmes was cleared of killing four people who were found beaten
to death in a Laurel Canyon home. Detective Tom Lange, supervisor
of the investigation, declined to discuss the case Monday except to
say it remains active.
   Prosecutors said the four were part of a theft ring for which
Holmes acted as a middleman to Los Angeles nightclub owner Adel
Nasrallah, also known as Eddie Nash. Holmes allegedly fenced stolen
property for the group to Nash, who allegedly paid for the loot
with drugs.
   Nash's business had been robbed two days before the murder.
Prosecutors alleged Holmes staged the robbery and, when discovered,
led killers to the Laurel Canyon home. Prosecutors claimed he
committed one of the murders with his own hands.
   Jurors cited a lack of corroborating evidence for their vote for
acquittal.
   Nash was sentenced in a separate case to eight years in prison
for possession of two pounds of cocaine worth an estimated $1
million. He was released after serving less than two years.
   Lange said Nash remains a suspect in the Laurel Canyon killings,
as does his one-time bodyguard, and that police have other suspects.
</TEXT>
