<2ND_LINE>PM-Inmate Freed,0261</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Who Once Confessed To Killing Is Cleared</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who spent almost two years in prison
after he confessed to a murder he didn't commit was freed four days
after another man confessed to the crime.
   Steven Ferndo, 20, of south St. Louis, said he confessed to
stabbing Charles Oxenhandler in January 1986 because he was a drug
addict and ``sick of life.''
   Ferndo was freed by St. Louis Circuit Judge Robert Dowd Jr.
after Douglas Weems of Jefferson County confessed last Thursday to
the killing.
   ``Drugs had ruined my life,'' Ferndo said of his decision to
confess. ``I was down. I was a drug addict. I gave up on life.
   ``Now I don't even remember that life. Now I just want to go up
in the world and put my life together.''
   Ferndo was sentenced to 20 years in prison in 1986 after he
entered an ``Alford plea,'' which makes no attempt to counter the
evidence while offering no admission of guilt.
   The case was reopened in October after a young woman who had
been punched by Weems told authorities that Weems had killed
Oxenhandler.
   Weems, 23, was charged with second-degree murder in the killing
of Oxenhander, a radio consultant who used the stage name of Robert
Hattrick. Weems told police that a fight had broken out after
Oxenhandler made homosexual advances.
   Ferndo's mother, Janie Gillian, wept at the hearing Monday and
said, ``My baby's out ... I knew he was not a killer.''
</TEXT>
