<1ST_LINE>r w PM-PostmasterGeneral     03-01 0241</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Postmaster General,250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Postmaster General Takes Office</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation has a new postmaster general today,
the fourth in as many years.
   Anthony M. Frank, a San Francisco banker, took office as head of
the U.S. Postal Service without formal ceremony. He started his
service with a meeting of top postal executives.
   Frank takes over the troubled agency with a rate increase
pending at the same time cuts in services have been forced by
congressionally required spending reductions. The cuts include
reduced sorting time, collections and window hours.
   He brings to the job a reputation as an innovator who encourages
initiative in his managers and is willing to try new ideas.
   A decision by the independent Postal Rate Commission is expected
within a week on a rate increase proposed by the agency last year.
The complex series of rate changes would include a 25-cent first
class rate, if approved, and could take effect by mid-April.
   The service cuts are not likely to change, even with higher
rates, since the new stamp prices were proposed to cope with other
cost pressures and are not related to the budget changes imposed by
Congress.
   Frank succeeds New York businessman Preston R. Tisch, who had
held the post since Aug. 6, 1986. Tisch followed Albert V. Casey,
who held the job for only seven months. Casey replaced Paul N.
Carlin, who served for just a year from January 1985 to 1986.
</TEXT>
