<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WaterbedCare     03-01 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Waterbed Care,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug-Addicted Infants Seem To Improve On Waterbeds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Waterbeds work wonders for babies born addicted
to narcotics used by their mothers, a new study indicates, but
researchers say they aren't sure why.
   Such infants have easier withdrawal, are more comfortable and
are more likely to thrive if they lie on waterbeds instead of
traditional bassinets, the study found.
   Infants going through drug withdrawal suffer many of the same
symptoms that afflict adult addicts, including irritability,
tremors, vomiting, abnormal sleeping and poor feeding.
   But a waterbed provides improved care that is ``safe,
noninvasive, inexpensive and effective,'' said the researchers,
whose findings were published in the February issue of the American
Journal of Diseases of Children.
   One of the researchers, Dr. Suzanne D. Dixon, cautioned that
this is essentially an improved nursing technique and not even a
partial solution to the problem posed by addicted infants.
   ``This study was to evaluate a simple nursing change to see if
it could make life just a little better for children who have a lot
of things stacked against them,'' said Dixon, with the pediatrics
department at the Univerity of California in San Diego.
   Waterbed use makes the early days of newborn addicts more
comfortable, helps in some traditional treatments and hopefully
gives youngsters a better chance for normal development, she said.
   She said researchers aren't sure why the waterbeds seem to help.
   More expensive oscillating waterbeds have been used successfully
with premature non-addicted babies to provide movement stimulation.
But the researchers found that newborn addicts can benefit from
non-oscillating beds that are less expensive than traditional
bassinets.
   ``Over half of the narcotic-exposed neonates required medication
to control withdrawal symptoms,'' the researchers said.
   ``Those on waterbeds required a significantly lower maximum
phenobarbital dose and had a lower incidence of hospital discharge
with medication, thereby reducing the newborn's exposure to
additional drugs.''
   When discharged from the hospital, 63 percent of the waterbed
babies had been weened from withdrawal medication, as opposed to 38
percent of infants in bassinets.
   The research was conducted on 30 infants born with an addiction
to narcotics, mostly heroin or methadone. Half were put on
waterbeds, half in bassinets.
   By the fifth day, researchers said, it was clear the waterbeds
were having an impact.
   Withdrawal symptoms such as vomiting, tremors and congestion
were less severe among the waterbed babies, the study found. They
also went to sleep more easily and had improved weight gain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
