<2ND_LINE>PM-Car Kids,0324</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Says Husband To Blame For Children's Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman charged with involuntary
manslaughter says it was her husband who locked their two young
children in a sun-baked car last summer, leading to the youngsters'
deaths, her lawyer says.
   Lisa Shields, 19, of White Township, relied on her husband, John
Shields, 24, to take care of their children, Kristle, 3, and
Calvin, 1, on Aug. 22, said lawyer Thomas Johnson.
   Shields will ``testify his wife told him to watch the children
while she went inside the house because she was ill,'' Thomas said
during opening remarks Monday in the first day of Mrs. Shield's
trial.
   Prosecutors called 11 witnesses Monday and were expected to call
several more today before the defense began its case.
   The couple left a party early on Aug. 22 and drove to a
relative's farmhouse, according to an affidavit by state police.
Mrs. Shields slept in the car with the children from about 5 a.m.
to 9 a.m., and Shields went into the house, police said.
   Then Mrs. Shields went into the house and asked her husband to
take care of the children, Johnson said. Shields moved the car to a
sunnier location and rolled up the windows, police said.
   When Mrs. Shields checked the children several hours later, she
found Calvin unconscious and Kristle gasping for breath, according
to police. Calvin was pronounced dead at the scene and his sister
died the next day in Pittsburgh's Mercy Hospital. Autopsies showed
both died of high temperatures.
   Mrs. Shields also is charged with endangering the welfare of
children. Her husband faces identical charges and is scheduled to
go on trial later this month in Mifflin County.
   Each defendant won a change of venue from Indiana County after
defense attorneys argued pre-trial publicity made seating an
impartial jury impossible there. They have been jailed since their
arrests.
