<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Soviet-Violence     03-01 0591</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Violence,0612</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Curfew Imposed In Sumgait, Site Of Rioting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL PUTZEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet government spokesman said today a curfew
was imposed in Sumgait, the city in Azerbaidzhan where rioting
broke out two days ago. He said ``some mistakes'' had been made
concerning a disputed territory that is home to tens of thousands
of Armenians.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said the
situation was calm but tense in Azerbaidzhan and neighboring Soviet
Armenia, where ethnic hatred triggered demonstrations, violence and
at least two deaths in recent days.
   He suggested the unrest resulted from a ``mistake'' made 65
years ago when a territory composed largely of ethnic Armenians was
made part of neighboring Azerbaidzhan.
   ``There were certain injuries'' in Sumgait, an industrial city
where hooligans were blamed for touching off a riot Sunday,
Gerasimov said.
   At his regular briefing today, the Soviet spokesman was peppered
with questions about the unrest in the southern republics of
Armenia and Azerbaidzhan. However, he said he had few details.
   Foreign journalists have been barred from the region, and only
sporadic reports from witnesses, activists and the official media
have reached Moscow.
   Gerasimov was asked about reports that Soviet tanks are
patrolling Sumgait, that ethnic Azeris are attacking Armenians
there and that there have been at least two deaths in the city.
   He responded that ``there is a curfew'' in Sumgait, but that he
had not heard anything about tanks being sent into the city. ``The
situation is calm there today, but it is tense,'' Gerasimov said.
   Asked if troops remained in the city today, he said, ``I don't
know, but I guess so. Presumably.''
   The violence in Sumgait, reported Monday by the official Soviet
news agency Tass, followed outbreaks 150 miles away in
Nagorno-Karabakh, the contested region in Azerbaidzhan, and mass
demonstrations in Yerevan, the capital of Soviet Armenia.
   The demonstrators demanded that Nagorno-Karabakh, which has been
part of Azerbaidzhan since 1923, be made part of Armenia.
Three-quarters of the area's 157,000 residents are Armenian.
   Gerasimov said he did not have detailed reports from the entire
region but that what information he had indicated ``everything is
calm'' in Yerevan and surrounding areas.
   ``The events that took place caused great concern to us,'' he
said. ``We think it is not a proper way to settle the problems that
have accumulated.''
   Gerasimov acknowledged, however, that the unrest apparently
stemmed from ``some mistakes made in the national relations, and
these mistakes should be rectified.''
   Soviet authorities have pledged to reconsider the issue of
Nagorno-Karabakh's parent republic, and Gerasimov's statement
seemed to indicate the region might be turned over to Armenia. He
did not, however, say when that might occur.
   Asked if he meant to say that Nagorno-Karabakh should be made
part of Armenia, Gerasimov said: ``I meant there were some mistakes
in Nagorno-Karabakh.''
   He described the region as ``a kind of enclave'' in Azerbaidzhan
with 49 nationalities represented among the population that is
nonetheless mostly Armenian.
   ``That is why we should be very tactful in handling this
question in order not to cause differences between brothers and
nationalities. The previous policy had some mistakes in this
area,'' he said.
   On Friday, Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev appealed for
``civil maturity and restraint'' and promised the Communist Party
Central Committee would review relations among the Soviet Union's
more than 100 nationalities.
   Azerbaidzhan is the largest of three Soviet republics in the
Caucasus. It is bordered on the west by largely Christian Armenia
and Georgia and on the north by the Russian Republic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
