<2ND_LINE>PM-Bible Speaks,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heiress Among Top Bidders For Estate She Brought To Bankruptcy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An heiress whose lawsuit pushed a
church into bankruptcy was among four bidders for the church's
property in a recent auction.
   Elizabeth Dovydenas' $2.56 million bid for property of The Bible
Speaks church in Lenox was the third highest bid, Charles
Normandin, attorney for the court-appointed trustee managing the
church estate, said Monday.
   He said the high bid of $2.81 million came from a group called
Lenox Associates. Its lawyer, Richard Howard, declined to reveal
the partners' identities.
   Second was Kaslin Properties of New York with a bid of $2.61
million, Normandin said.
   Mrs. Dovydenas had argued in U.S. Bankruptcy Court last April
that she was duped out of a third of her chain-store fortune by the
founder and leader of the fundamentalist sect, Rev. Carl H. Stevens
Jr., while she was a parishioner from 1983 to 1986.
   The Bible Speaks campus closed last year after Mrs. Dovydenas
prevailed in her $6.6 million claim. Lawyers for the church plan to
appeal a federal judge's recent decision upholding the claim.
   Her claim is by far the largest of hundreds of creditors, who
claim they are owed more than $7 million by the church.
   Monday was the deadline for bids on the 65-acre estate with its
28 buildings. Normandin said the final round of bidding could come
at a hearing Monday at U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Worcester.
   Mrs. Dovydenas had been the high bidder at a November auction of
the church headquarters, but the Bankruptcy Court rejected her $1.8
million bid as too low. The campus has been appraised at $6 million.
</TEXT>
