<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CampusTakeover     03-01 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Campus Takeover,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dorm Takeover Ends at Hampshire College</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Forty minority students at Hampshire
College have reached an agreement with the administration to end
their week-long takeover of a dormitory, a college spokeswoman said
today.
   The students had complained of racism at the private liberal
arts school.
   ``By the end of the day we expect the agreement to be fully
signed,'' said administration spokeswoman Melissa Stephen.
   Spokesmen for the protesters holding the Dakin House office were
out of the building and could not be reached for comment.
   College President Adele Simmons met Monday with representatives
of the blacks, Hispanics, Indians and other minorities who have
held the small brick building since Feb. 23.
   Their 16 demands included the creation of the post of dean of
multicultural affairs and for a full-time coordinator for the
minority student group.
   Simmons last week offered the students $25,000 to spend as they
please on their programs, but the negotiators rejected the offer.
   ``That's really an absurd amount for what is needed,'' protest
spokeswoman Anita Fearman said Monday.
   College spokeswoman Lee Wicks said the students evidently did
not understand the college's budget.
   ``When you see our high tuition, you think there must be lots of
extra money on campus,'' she said. ``We're ending this year on a
deficit and they're asking us to come up with bucks in March. Yes,
we want to be supportive, but in fact we don't have the money.''
   Tuition at the private liberal arts school was nearly $16,000
this year, she said. Minorities represent about 10 percent of the
school's 1,100 students.
</TEXT>
