<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1047EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-MediaWomen     03-01 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Media Women,0499</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Glass Ceiling' Seen Blocking Women's Entry To Top Media Jobs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FELIX GUTIERREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More women are working in entertainment and
the news media, but they bump into a ``glass ceiling'' that
prevents them from rising into top management jobs, experts told a
conference on Women, Men and Media.
   ``While more women are hired, that doesn't always translate
up,'' said University of Missouri journalism professor Jean Gaddy
Wilson, citing data gathered during a five-year study of women in
media.
   ``I do see that glass ceiling,'' Ms. Wilson told the conference
Monday at the University of Southern California. She described the
``glass ceiling'' as ``a transparent barrier'' that allows women to
see top echelon jobs but blocks access to them.
   Women account for 66 percent of the nation's journalism
graduates, but less than 2 percent of newspaper corporate
management, 5 percent of publishers and general managers, and 13
percent of directing editors, she said.
   ``The employment of women in news media lags behind employment
in the society overall,'' Ms. Wilson said. ``If current trends
continue, women won't attain directing editorships on par with
their level of the population until 2055.''
   Despite gains in front of the television camera, Ms. Wilson
reported similar patterns in broadcast management. She said no
networks had a woman heading their news division, and only nine of
51 network news vice presidents are women.
   Local television stations also have few women in management, Ms.
Wilson said. But she said radio stations employ women in proportion
to the workforce.
   Linda Alvarez, anchor on Los Angeles television station KNBC,
said some women in television are treated as ``shadow anchors'' to
a male co-anchor, are assigned to ``soft stories'' and are not
allowed to age.
   ``You don't see very many female Charles Kuralts on television,
or women who look like Irving R. Levine,'' said Ms. Alvarez, naming
two veteran male newscasters.
   The three-day conference, which started Sunday, was organized by
Betty Friedan, author of the best-selling ``The Feminine Mystique''
and a visiting journalism professor at USC.
   An analysis of credits on 1986-87 network entertainment series
found women employed more often as writers than as producers or
directors, said Sally Steenland of Wider Opportunities for Women.
Seventeen of the top 20 shows had women writers. half had women
producers and six had directors.
   Futurist Alvin Toffler said women have a chance to manage new
media as communication becomes diversified by cable television and
other outlets targeting ``micro markets'' within the mass audience.
   ``We're going to see two-tiered media,'' said Toffler. Mass
media will cover major events, but customized media will provide
information and entertainment to audiences defined by such
characteristics as race, sex, interest or geographic area, he said.
   The conference was co-sponsored by the Gannett Foundation, USC's
School of Journalism, the Institute for the Study of Women and Men,
Women in Film, and the Times Mirror Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
