<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1109EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dole 1stLd-Writethru a0453 03-01 0870</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dole, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede FORT LAUDERDALE</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top grafs new with Durham events, new TV spot on Iran-Contra;
pick up 5th graf pvs bgng ``Dole the...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DURHAM, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Bob Dole, playing catch-up in the
Southern presidential primaries, attacked George Bush in public and
in new television commercials today as a vice president without
record or accomplishment and a supporter of the arms-for-hostages
deal with Iran.
   Dole's campaign began airing tough ads striking at Bush in
Florida and North Carolina, as Dole escalated criticism of the vice
president at appearances at Duke University.
   ``That's precisely what he did _ he supported the sale of arms
to Iran,'' Dole said when asked about the new television attack.
   Dole, the Senate minority leader, accused Bush of offering
``nine different answers'' on the Iran-Contra affair. ``But it's a
fact he did support it,'' Dole said.
   ``Now we're talking about credibility,'' Dole said at a news
conference. ``When somebody gives you nine different answers on the
same question, I think it's an issue.''
   Trailing Bush in the polls in most of the states voting next
week, Dole began a test-run of strong television ads in Miami and
other selected Florida cities, Dole campaign manager Bill Brock
said.
   The ads, which the Dole campaign produced but did not run during
the New Hampshire campaign, depict Bush as walking through snow but
leaving no footprints, Brock said. He said the message was that
Bush ``has held all these big jobs'' yet left no mark.
   In North Carolina, Dole began airing a different ad that
injected the Iran-Contra affair into the campaign, saying that Bush
``supported arms for hostages.''
   It also says Bush ``waffles on taxes'' and opposes legislation
limiting textile imports, a bill that Dole supports and that is
popular in the textile-producing Carolinas. Bush said in South
Carolina last week that he opposes the textile bill as
protectionist.
   Dole spoke to students on the campus of Duke University, where
his wife Elizabeth attended college. While there he lashed at Bush
for saying repeatedly that he wants to be ``the education
president.''
   ``Well he's certainly been quiet the last seven years when the
administration's been whacking billions and billions of dollars out
of the education budget,'' Dole said. ``Haven't heard one word.''
   A day earlier in Fort Lauderdale, Dole told a downtown crowd to
question Bush on his record. ``Ask him what's he done in the last
seven years,'' Dole said. ``What's he done anywhere in America or
the world to make a difference?''
   Dole, the Kansas senator and Senate minority leader, cited his
own record in Congress and raised anew his claim that Bush had
distorted Dole's stand on tax increases in television commercials
that helped Bush win the New Hampshire primary.
   Dole said voters want to elect ``someone who is not out trying
to distort somebody else's record when they don't have a record of
their own.''
   ``Bob Dole is not going to raise your taxes,'' he said. ``We
don't know what George Bush is going to do.''
   ``Tough'' was a word Dole brandished as he flew around the South
drawing comparisons with Bush in advance of the big round of
primaries across the region and elsewhere on Super Tuesday, a week
away.
   ``I have a quality that some may be lacking. I am tough,'' Dole
said in Atlanta and echoed in Mississippi and Florida. And for
anyone missing his comparison with the vice president, Dole said:
``I'm tougher.''
   Reacting to the crisis in Panama, Dole called for a full trade
embargo against that country if its military strongman Manuel
Noriega stays in power, and he urged the use of force if necessary
to protect U.S. interests there, including the Panama Canal.
   Dole said the Reagan administration has sent mixed signals on
Noriega, who is accused of drug trafficking. And Dole suggested the
United States reconsider transferring the Panama Canal to that
country if Noriega appears able to retain power.
   ``You just ought to say no to drugs, no to Noriega, and no,
maybe, to giving them the canal,'' Dole said.
   He said some U.S. officials have made conciliatory statements
about Noriega and ignored old evidence of drug involvement in the
Panamanian military.
   ``It seems to me we have one signal indicating Noriega ought to
stay or Noriega isn't such a bad guy,'' Dole said. He singled out
Daniel Murphy, former chief of staff to Vice President George Bush,
who he said described Noriega as cooperative, and cited ``other
indications they didn't know about Noriega and drugs until a few
weeks ago.''
   ``Strange thing,'' Dole said. ``We knew about it when we were
debating the Panama Canal treaty 10 years ago. In fact many of us
talked about it on the Senate floor.''
   Dole frequently mentioned his vote against the treaty,
tranferring eventual ownership of the Panama Canal to Panama, that
was narrowly ratified 10 years ago. He said that if it appears
Panama's situation will go unchanged, ``we may want to go back and
take another look at that canal.''
   `` We may not want to turn it over to Panama, if they're going
to be in this state,'' Dole said.
</TEXT>
