<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Robertson     03-01 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Robertson,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Renews Contention There Are Missiles in Cuba</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate
Pat Robertson said today a transcript of 1967 Senate subcommittee
testimony supports his belief there are nuclear missiles in Cuba.
   The former religious broadcaster quoted testimony from two
people:
   _Paul Bethel, a State Department official who said Cuban
refugees had told him about seeing missiles.
   _One of the refugees, identified only as Mr. Apud, who said
members of the Cuban military had told him about missiles aimed at
Washington before he left in 1966.
   In the 1967 Judiciary subcommittee transcript, Apud said he was
told by Cuban soldiers he had known for many years that the
missiles were nicknamed ``Washington Left,'' ``Washington Right''
and ``Washington Central.''
   The transcript also showed that Bethel said in response to
questioning by Sen. Strom Thurmond, R-S.C., that numerous refugees
had told him they had seen missiles left in Cuba after the Cuban
Missile Crisis and new ones put in in 1964.
   Bethel testified he could not say for sure that intermediate or
intercontinental ballistic missiles were in Cuba, but that the
State Department also couldn't be certain they weren't there.
   ``This is documented evidence,'' Robertson said today at a
breakfast attended by about 600 supporters.
   He first brought the subject up in a debate in New Hampshire
last month, contending there are missiles in Cuba aimed at the
United States.
   The Reagan administration immediately denied it.
   At a news conference on Monday, Robertson produced a Cuban
refugee who he said had seen the weapons. The Cuban, who spoke
through an interpreter and identified himself only as E. Rodriguez,
said he had seen missile sites, but did not know whether the
weapons had nuclear warheads.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
