<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CommuterChaos     03-01 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Commuter Chaos,0495</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Day of Expressway Reconstruction Not So Bad</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first morning of reconstruction on the city's
major highway link to the south passed without major traffic jams,
police said today.
   ``So far, so good,'' state police Sgt. Dolores Enright said of
the traffic on the Dan Ryan Expressway, one of the nation's busiest
highways.
   Most commuters apparently heeded warnings about potential
traffic problems and took other routes or public transportation.
   The project will widen the Dan Ryan from four lanes each way to
five.
   During 6{ months of construction on southbound lanes this year,
all traffic will share four lanes. The northbound lanes will be out
of commission next year during the project's second phase.
   Some motorists had planned novel ways to cope with massive
traffic jams they had expected.
   Julie Coenen said bought tape-recorded ``talking books,'' such
as James Michener's ``Texas,'' to listen to while she sits in
traffic.
   ``I think it's going to be like a huge, huge parking lot,'' says
Ms. Coenen, who lives in northwest suburban Elk Grove Village and
uses the Dan Ryan Expressway to commute to her job as a health
educator at Michael Reese Medical Center on the city's South Side.
   ``I have visions of people taking folding chairs and tables and
playing cards.''
   ``I think it's going to be a real bad nightmare,'' says Norma
Hill, 35, a hospital secretary who commutes from her home in south
suburban Evergreen Park to her job in south Chicago.
   The Dan Ryan Expressway, an 11-mile stretch of concrete and
asphalt, is the main link between Chicago and points south. Traffic
from at least six other expressways feeds the Dan Ryan just south
of downtown Chicago.
   State officials say the $210 million rebuilding job will be the
largest highway project in Illinois history.
   ``The road is simply wearing out from old age and the pounding
it has taken from traffic, particularly trucks,'' says Dick
Adorjan, a spokesman for the Illinois Department of Transportation.
   The state plans to close all four southbound lanes from March 13
to October 31, rerouting southbound traffic onto two of the four
northbound lanes. The process will be reversed in the spring of
1989.
   The work began today with the closing of several lanes on each
side of the freeway for a week to build traffic crossovers and
patch the northbound side.
   As the project began, a psychiatrist recommended deep breaths,
exercise or conversation as tension easers for stalled commuters.
   ``Drivers who are mentally prepared to face these difficulties
can reduce the stress,'' says Dr. Richard Glass, associate
psychiatry professor and director of adult outpatient services at
the University of Chicago Medical Center.
   He said drivers could also use their stall time to learn a
foreign language from taped lessons or dictate letters into a tape
recorder.
</TEXT>
