<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Deport     03-01 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Deport,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Makes It Easier to Deport Some Aliens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court, making it easier to deport
some aliens, today blocked further hearings for a California man
seeking to avoid return to his native Ghana.
   The court ruled 8-0 that immigration officials, having decided
an alien should be deported, generally are under no duty to
reconsider the case when the alien says he has new evidence to
support a bid for asylum.
   The decision is a defeat for Dr. Assibi L. Abudu, a native and
citizen of Ghana who graduated from the University of Southern
California medical school and married a U.S. citizen.
   Immigration officials moved to deport him in 1981 after he was
convicted in California of illegally attempting to obtain the
narcotic drug demerol by fraud. He was given a one-year suspended
prison sentence and was placed on probation for three years.
   The Immigration and Naturalization Service found him deportable
and the Board of Immigration Appeals upheld that decision.
   Abudu sought to reopen his case in 1985 and seek asylum in the
United States from the military dictatorship of Flight Lieutenant
Jerry Rawlings, who regained power in Ghana in a Dec. 31, 1981,
military coup.
   Abudu said he had new evidence that his life might be in danger
if he was forced to return to Ghana based on a 1984 visit to him by
Abukari Alhassan, secretary of housing and construction in the
Rawlings regime.
   Abudu said he believed Alhassan was trying to lure him back to
Ghana so officials there could torture him to extract information
about opponents of the Rawlings regime.
   Abudu said his brother escaped capture by the regime and fled
into hiding and also said his lifelong friend, Lt. Col. Joshua
Hamidu, is regarded as the number one enemy of the Rawlings
government.
   The Board of Immigration Appeals refused to reopen Abudu's case,
noting that Abudu did not initially seek asylum when he contested
his deportation.
   But the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in 1986 ordered the
board to reconsider granting Abudu asylum.
   The Supreme Court today agreed with the Reagan administration
that the appeals court should have deferred to the decision of the
immigration board.
   Justice John Paul Stevens, writing for the court, said aliens
seeking to reopen their deportation cases have the difficult task
of proving that immigration officials abused their discretion in
refusing to do so.
   ``There is a strong public interest in bringing litigation to a
close as promptly as is consistent with the interest in giving the
adversaries a fair opportunity to develop and present their
respective cases,'' Stevens said.
   ``We have no hesitation in concluding that the Board of
Immigration Appeals did not abuse its discretion when it held that
Abudu had not reasonably explained his failure to apply for asylum
prior to the completion of the initial deportation proceeding,'' he
said.
   Justice Anthony M. Kennedy, who only recently joined the court,
did not take part in the decision.
   The case is INS vs. Abudu, 86-1128.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
