<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ObstetricSurvey 1stLdWritethru a0563 03-01 0455</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obstetric Survey, 1st Ld Writethru, a0563,420</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS figure in 8th graf pvs, The survey, for New York
obstetricians. Officials, who released incorrect figure, said 55
percent were sued at least twice, sted at least three times.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A survey released today says that the threat
of malpractice suits caused 12 percent of obstetricians to close
their practices last year and that two-thirds leave the field
before age 55.
   The survey, conducted in October and November for the American
College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, showed that the
national rate for physicians dropping obstetrics has remained at 12
percent for the last two years, but that the age of those quitting
is getting younger.
   ``If this trend continues, we are going to see more and more
physicians leaving obstetrics at the height of their professional
ability,'' said Dr. Jimmie Gleason, chairman of the doctors'
committee on professional liability. ``We are looking at a
situation where obstetrics is being concentrated more and more in
large urban and suburban areas.''
   In Florida, the number of doctors no longer delivering babies
has reached 25 percent, about twice the national average, and 75
percent of those quitting in Florida are doing so before the age
55, also far above the national average.
   Malpractice insurance premiums for obstetricians in Florida and
New York now average about $52,000 a year, the survey shows. The
national average has risen from $10,946 in 1982 to $37,015 in 1987,
according to the report.
   Gleason said the survey revealed ``several disturbing trends''
in the care of high-risk pregnancies.
   Twenty-seven of the surveyed doctors said they were limiting the
number of high-risk cases they will take, compared to 23 percent in
1985, and 18 percent in 1982.
   The survey showed that seven out of 10
obstetrician-gynecologists nationally have been sued at some point
in their career. In New York, 55 percent of the practicioners have
been sued two or more times.
   Fifty-two percent of the suits involved obstetric cases, with 31
percent of these cases for claims of neurologically-impaired
infants, and 15 percent for claims of stillbirths or infant deaths,
the survey showed.
   Of the claims resolved, 36 percent were dropped without payment.
Of those not dropped, 79 percent were settled with payment.
   The survey showed that obstetrician-gynecologists had a mean
gross income in 1986 of $296,133, with the highest gross in New
York, with $387,022, and in Florida, with $323,252. The mean gross
income increased by $81,122 from 1984 to 1986, the survey showed.
   The average medical practice overhead reported was $147,029,
with the average for Florida at $190,882.
   Opinion Research Corp. of Princeton, N.J. conducted the survey
for the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
