<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Scotus-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0580 03-01 0374</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Scotus-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Declines to Decide if Mississippi or Federal Government
Controls Gulf Area</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts penultimate graf, Justices Thurgood, to say who did
not participate.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court today declined to decide yet
whether the state or the federal government should control a Gulf
of Mexico area off Mississippi's southwestern coastline.
   Rejecting arguments by the state's lawyers, the court ruled 7-0
that more information is needed before such a determination is made.
   Mississippi had sought a ruling that its southwestern coastline
extends beyond several barrier islands and into Chandeleur Sound,
south of the Mississippi Sound.
   Control of an area of about 150 square miles of the gulf, along
with control of the natural resources there, remains in dispute.
   The case acted on today has, in varying forms, been before the
high court since 1956, when the justices first invoked their
``original jurisdiction'' to hear the controversy before it had
been aired in any lower court.
   In such cases, the Supreme Court functions as a trial court and
acts on the recommendations of a court-appointed ``special
master.'' In this case, retired Judge Walter P. Armstrong Jr. is
serving as the special master.
   He recommended that Mississippi's pressing for a ruling that
gives it control of the disputed gulf area should be ruled
premature.
   Writing for the court today, Justice Harry A. Blackmun agreed.
   He said Mississippi's arguments ``are overruled but without
prejudice to the advancement of such claims as any party might have
with respect to the area south of Mississippi Sound in the vicinity
of Chandeleur Sound in an appropriate separate chapter of these
proceedings.''
   The Mississippi Sound is a body of water between the state's
mainland and a line of barrier islands several miles offshore.
   In 1985, the justices ruled that Alabama and Mississippi _ and
not the federal government _ own their respective portions of the
sound's bed and therefore control the natural resources there.
   Blackmun said the high court would retain jurisdiction in the
case, raising the likelihood that still another ruling on the issue
is in the court's future.
   Justices Thurgood Marshall and Anthony M. Kennedy did not
participate in the decision.
   The case is Alabama and Mississippi Boundardy Case, 9 Original.

</TEXT>
