<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1118EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-TritiumRelease     03-01 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tritium Release,0305</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Tritium Escape Reported At SRP</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AIKEN, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ``puff'' of tritium escaped from the
Department of Energy's Savannah River Plant today, but posed no
hazard to the public, officials said.
   Spokesman Jim Felder said about 20,000 curies of tritium, a
radioactive isotope of hydrogen, were released at 6:18 a.m. this
morning during routine operations.
   Felder characterized the release as ``a puff'' and said it
lasted less than a minute.
   The weapons production facility at the plant makes material used
in the production of nuclear weapons, and Felder said details on
the process under way when the release occurred are classified.
   The exposure at the plant boundary, about six miles from the H
Chemical Separations Area where the release occurred, was about
0.04 millirems, Felder said. By comparison, he said a normal chest
X-ray is 20 millirems.
   Two employees in the work area at the time of the release were
undergoing tests to see if they suffered any ill effects. They were
wearing full protective gear at the time, he said.
   All plant operations have returned to normal, he said.
   Felder said an initial assessment of the cause of the release
indicates equipmment malfunction. However, an investigation will be
conducted.
   The last such release at the plant occurred July 31, 1987, when
a dosage of .2 millirems was measured at the plant's boundary.
   The plant's reactors were reduced to half power last year amid
concerns over the cooling system, and Department of Energy
officials told a U.S. Senate subcommittee in Washington on Monday
that the reactors could be running at full capacity by 1990.
   Felder said this morning the process in which the tritium was
released is separate from that involving the reactors and would not
affect the reactor plans.
</TEXT>
