<1ST_LINE>u p PM-SuperTuesday-Media 1stLd-Writethru a0432 03-01 0873</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Super Tuesday-Media, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0432,850</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 4-7 with new Dole, Gephardt ads; picks up 7th graf
pvs ``At the outset...; DELETE final 3 grafs to tighten</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   How does a presidential candidate campaign for
20 far-flung contests held on the same day? The answer is
television.
   The primaries and caucuses of March 8, Super Tuesday, are being
held in states and territories from Florida to Washington, an
unprecedented sweep across more than 150 media markets with more
than 500 television stations.
   Television is as critical on the vast Super Tuesday battleground
as grass-roots organizing was in Iowa and New Hampshire.
   Kansas Sen. Bob Dole fired an opening salvo, starting a test-run
of tough television ads in Florida and North Carolina.
   The Florida ad, which the Dole campaign produced but did not run
during the New Hampshire campaign, depicts Vice President George
Bush walking through snow but leaving no footprints. The message,
said Dole campaign manager Bill Brock, was that Bush ``has held all
these big jobs'' yet left no mark.
   The other Dole ad, running in North Carolina, injects the
Iran-Contra affair into the campaign. It says Bush ``supported arms
for hostages,'' ``waffles on taxes'' and opposes legislation
limiting textile imports, a bill Dole supports and that is popular
in the textile-producing Carolinas. Bush said in South Carolina
last week that he opposes the textile bill as protectionist.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt also was taking the offensive with two
critical ads. One featured Rep. Marvin Leath of Texas criticizing
Gephardt rivals Michael Dukakis and Albert Gore Jr. The other was a
retooled version of an ad that was considered a key factor in
Gephardt's victory over Dukakis last week in South Dakota.
   At the outset of his campaign, Dukakis mentioned Belgian endive,
a kind of yuppie lettuce, as an example of how Iowa farmers could
diversify their crops. The Gephardt ad criticizes the Massachusetts
governor's positions on trade and farm issues, and ends with a
voice saying sarcastically: ``Belgian endive?''
   Many observers said Dukakis made a major error in not responding
with an ad of his own _ a situation that won't be repeated. Dukakis
aide Leslie Dach said the Dukakis campaign had prepared a negative
ad about Gephardt and would use it soon, possibly starting today,
in Super Tuesday states.
   Gephardt has also revived an ad that was seen as having a big
impact in Iowa _ in which he criticizes South Korea for stifling
U.S. auto sales in that nation with stiff tariffs, and threatens to
respond in kind. See how many Hyundais the Koreans can sell here at
$48,000 apiece, he tells viewers.
   And Gephardt has a commercial featuring the popular Rep. Claude
Pepper, a Democrat who has ample clout with senior citizens. Pepper
is from Florida, the second-biggest Super Tuesday state.
   Dukakis has ads featuring fellow Massachusetts politician Tip
O'Neill, the former House speaker, and has been running a
biographical spot in which he stresses his economic accomplishments
as governor.
   Dukakis has mounted particularly strong efforts in four states
with pockets of ethnic or liberal voters: Florida, Texas, North
Carolina and Georgia.
   Gephardt and Dole have focused on the border states that lie
near their respective homes of Missouri and Kansas.
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., who bypassed early contests to
stress the Super Tuesday states, took out a loan Monday to pay for
a media blitz, a campaign spokesman said.
   ``We're going to saturate Super Tuesday. ... We want to pour it
on,'' said press spokesman Mike Kopp.
   Gore's state campaign treasurer in Tennessee, Johnny Hayes, said
Gore had taken a $1 million line of credit against which money
would be borrowed for a 20-state advertising campaign. Kopp said
new Gore commercials would go on the air today.
   Gore has already made national cable television buys and
purchases of time on individual stations in most of the Super
Tuesday states.
   Bush was first on the air in Texas, where he once lived. He has
been running a biographical ad. Republican rival Rep. Jack Kemp has
concentrated his advertising money in seven Super Tuesday states,
said his political director, Charles Black.
   Rarely are the candidates engaging in the small-scale,
``retail'' campaigning of the early contests _ visiting diners,
plant gates and firehouses, taking door-to-door strolls down
residential streets. When they do, it's mostly for the benefit of
television cameras.
   ``It's too vast a primary to even bother, other than for media
events,'' said Larry Sabato, a political media expert at the
University of Virginia. ``It's a wholesale day. The candidates have
to rely heavily on their strategic consultants and media
consultants.''
   A well-heeled candidate could spend upwards of $2 million
blanketing the territory with TV commercials, radio spots and
satellite feeds. The trick is to spend shrewdly as well as heavily.
   ``It's a matter of consultants sitting down with polling data
and Census data and deciding where you have your best bet,'' said
Bob Lichter, a media analyst and co-director of the Center for
Media and Public Affairs. ``It's applied science meets gut
political instinct.''
   The typical Super Tuesday technique calls for finding targets
within states, such as individual congressional districts, and
keeping mum about where they are.
</TEXT>
