<2ND_LINE>PM-Puerto Rico-Search, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0575,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strong Waves Hamper Search, Police Say</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: CORRECTS dateline to AGUADA</NOTE>
<DATELINE>AGUADA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strong waves off Puerto Rico's west
coast hampered a search today for possible survivors of a small
craft carrying illegal aliens from the Dominican Republic to this
U.S. Commonwealth, police said.
   Police Maj. Cesar Gracia said two bodies were found Monday and a
third has been spotted floating at sea. One survivor was
hospitalized Monday.
   Authorities and a survivor said the majority of the 45 people
aboard the craft made it to shore safely.
   The boat, estimated at 20 to 30 feet long, sank Sunday night
near the small fishing village of Aguada, about 85 miles west of
the capital San Juan, the landing site for many boats bringing
illegal aliens to the United States in recent years. The exact
number of illegals making the trip during that period is unknown.
   According to Gracia, the Dominican residents boarded the craft
on the east coast of Dominican Republic on Saturday night, when the
weather was clear. As they neared Puero Rico, the boat was
overturned by large waves about 180 feet from shore.
</TEXT>
