<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NorthwestAirlines     03-01 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Northwest Airlines,0457</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Flight Attendants Still Prepared To Strike; No Talks In Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAGAN, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Only one major issue still separates
Northwest Airlines and its flight attendants, who continued working
as usual today even though their strike deadline passed last week,
company and union officials say.
   Another union official said there was a possibility that
Northwest could be faced with simultaneous strikes by the flight
attendants and ground workers.
   A federal mediator is scheduled to hold talks between the
company and District Lodge 143 of the International Association of
Machinists a week from today, said Guy Cook, president of that
union.
   If those talks break down and the mechanics declare a strike
deadline, the flight attendants, represented by the Teamsters,
could invoke their own walkout, Cook said.
   But Cook said he does not know how long the flight attendants
can maintain their right to strike or how long it will take for the
mechanics to set a strike deadline in accordance with labor laws.
   ``I think that's the game that is going on right now,'' said
Chuck Davis, a labor expert at the University of Minnesota. ``If
the machinists are going to begin negotiations, it may be to (the
flight attendants') advantage to work without a new contract until
the machinists take a position.
   ``The more coordination that goes on, the larger the numbers,
the more strength they have in dealing with Northwest.''
   There are about 6,700 union flight attendants and about 20,000
mechanics, baggage handlers and other ground workers at Northwest.
   Talks between Northwest and Teamsters officials broke off at
dawn Saturday after an all-night negotiating session. A strike
deadline of 11:01 p.m. Friday passed without a strike and no job
actions have been taken against the company, said company spokesman
William Wren.
   Wren and Teamsters spokesman Jeff Musto said Monday that there
is only one major sticking point in the talks: A company proposal
to delay the promotion of workers on a lower B-scale pay schedule
to the higher-paid A-scale bracket.
   All new employees hired since a 1982 contract have started as
B-scale employees at pay rates lower than the previous system,
Musto said.
   The 1982 contract called for B-scale employees to jump to
A-scale levels in their sixth year of employment, but the company
has proposed extending that wait until the ninth year, Musto said.
   Wren said a large number of senior flight attendants make more
than $40,000 a year, plus meal payments when they're working. Most
entry-level flight attendants are making about $15,000 a year, he
said.
   About a third of the company's flight attendants are at the
B-scale level, Musto said.
</TEXT>
