<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Gephardt 1stLd-Writethru a0470 03-01 0635</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gephardt, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0470,640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Meets Carter; No Endorsement</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates in top 8 grafs with Carter visit, picking up in 4th
graf pvs, From Georgia</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A week before Southern voters assert
themselves in the 1988 presidential campaign, Rep. Richard Gephardt
paid a call today on former President Carter and said, ``I come
here today not to enhance my prospects but to greet an old friend.''
   Carter made it clear that with fellow Georgian Sam Nunn not in
the race he had no plans to endorse any of the Democratic
presidential candidates before the nominating convention next July.
   On one of Gephardt's major issues, the former president also
said that he could accept the congressman's trade legislation ``if
the president has the authority to moderate any sort of
protectionist trends.''
   Asked about Carter's less than ringing endorsement of a proposal
that has been a centerpiece of his presidential campaign, the
Gephardt said that he and Carter ``shared the view we've got to
create a better more open world trade.''
   Standing on the front walk in front of his brick home in this
small town that he put on the map, Carter said he thought there was
a 50-50 chance that no one will have clinched the presidential
nomination before the convention.
   ``My hope is that out of the primary and caucus season will come
a clear winner,'' he said. ``I'm not sure that's a likelihood now.''
   The former president said he would attend the convention as a
delegate and that if there was a deadlock ``I would not personally
favor turning to someone outside the active candidate group for the
nomination.''
   Carter said he has met with all of the active candidates.
   From Georgia, Gephardt was flying to Columbia, S.C., to pick up
the endorsement of former Govs. Richard Riley and Robert McNair.
   As the campaign entered the final week before Super Tuesday on
March 8, the day 20 states, most of them in the South, hold
primaries and caucuses, Gephardt started running a new television
commercial throughout the region.
   The ad takes on Sen. Albert Gore Jr. of Tennessee and Gov.
Michael Dukakis of Massachusetts.
   In it, Rep. Marvin Leath of Texas says Gephardt ``stood with us
for lower taxes, for an oil import fee to make America strong, for
a tough trade bill to stand up for American workers.''
   ``On all these issues, Gore and Dukakis were opposed to us. Gore
and Dukakis even think the Gephardt trade bill is too tough on the
Japanese, Europeans and Koreans. We're tired of hearing that you
can't fight for America anymore. That's why 35 Southern congressman
are fighting for Dick Gephardt for president.''
   Gephardt won favorable comment from several fellow Democrats
attending a meeting of the Democratic Leadership Council the past
two days in Williamsburg, Va.
   ``Gephardt is the only candidate who is running a message
campaign,'' said Sen. Bob Graham of Florida. ``So he has the
benefit of operating almost in a vacuum.''
   Graham said he thought Super Tuesday would play a major role in
determining whether Gephardt or Gore survives in the presidential
race.
   Bill Carrick, Gephardt's campaign manager, said,``I don't think
it's going to be that definitive.''
   Carrick said the Gephardt campaign would spend $1 million on
television advertising during the week before Super Tuesday, most
of it in Florida and Texas, the two biggest states voting on March
8.
   Carrick described Riley, who was governor of South Carolina from
1977 to 1985, as a leader of the progressive wing of the Democratic
Party in the state.
   He said McNair, who was governor from 1965 to 1971, was a leader
of the ore conservative wing of the party.
   He said their dual backing was ``a nice little bookend
endorsement.''
</TEXT>
