<1ST_LINE>u a PM-TurtleExcluders     03-01 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turtle Excluders,0409</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Upholds Fishing Regulation Aimed At Saving Endangered
Turtles</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AUSTIN WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge today cleared the way for
enforcement of a federal regulation intended to save endangered sea
turtles by throwing out a suit filed by shrimpers who say the rule
will ruin their business.
   Shrimpers said they would defy the regulation, which goes into
effect today.
   U.S. District Judge Patrick Carr brushed aside vehement
arguments from shrimpers battling the requirement that they use
bulky traps called turtle excluder devices, commonly called TEDs,
which are intended to eject trapped turtles from nets.
   ``I don't care if he upheld it. It's a bad law, and the
shrimpers ain't going to live by it,'' said Tee John Mialjevich of
Concerned Shrimpers of Louisiana, which filed suit against the law.
   Critics say the devices don't always work and that they allow
shrimp to escape. Mialjevich said shrimpers in Florida, where the
law has been in effect since Jan. 1, experienced reductions of 35
percent to 50 percent of their catches.
   The law was also scheduled to go into effect off the coast of
Texas today.
   Shrimpers had argued that there was not enough evidence to show
that the TEDs would be effective in protecting the endangered
turtles.
   ``A review of the administrative record demonstrates that
(shrimpers') arguments are unfounded in most aspects,'' Carr wrote.
``From the outset, the Secretary (of Commerce) through the National
Marine Fisheries Service collected scientific information from sea
turtle experts from states, universities and the private sector.''
   Carr had said in advance that his ruling would not determine the
usefulness or effectiveness of the controversial devices, but would
address only whether the government had followed proper procedures
when it imposed the legislation.
   The outcry against the TEDs spread even to the state
Legislature, where a law was passed forbidding state officials from
enforcing the new regulations.
   The state attorney general's office had joined the shrimpers'
suit, but Carr dismissed the state from the case, saying the
shrimpers were capable of speaking for themselves.
   State officials were not sure how they would act.
   Corky Perret, assistant secretary of Wildlife and Fisheries,
said his department is caught in a ``Catch-22'' situation between
state and federal law.
   ``Until I get some legal, firm position to sit on, I guess I'm
up in the air,'' Perret said.
</TEXT>
