<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Congress-Drugs     03-01 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Congress-Drugs,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Panama</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senators Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., and Pete
Wilson, R-Calif., called on President Reagan today to strictly
penalize Latin American countries that fail to cooperate with the
United States in its effort to combat drug trafficking.
   Chiles, Wilson and Rep. Charles B. Rangel, D-N.Y., told the
White House Conference for a Drug Free America the Reagan
administration must decide the national security interest of the
United States before being concerned about Latin America,
particularly Panama, Mexico and Columbia.
   Reagan was to officially announce that Panama has failed to
cooperate with the United States, but will not impose forceful
sanctions in an effort to force the ouster of Central American
country's military strongman, Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega.
   The president also was to reject calls to decertify Mexico and
Colombia, which have been criticized heavily for failing to cut the
flow of drugs to this country.
   Chiles said many members of Congress believe the certification
process has not been used properly by the Reagan administration.
   Under the 1986 law, the U.S. is to decertify and cut off aid to
countries ``not fully cooperating'' with the United States to
combat drug traffic..
   ``This year, the good news is that Panama is on the list,'' said
Chiles. ``On the other hand, Mexico and Colombia aren't. We'll have
to examine why Mexico is certified. Colombia is a country under
siege and we will have to examine that. We have to ask ourselves
what is the national interest. I think we have to continue to apply
pressure against these countries.''
   He said the law will be changed next year to require a bilateral
agreement between the United States and Latin American nations ``so
that there will be a country-by-country certification, rather than
one list including all of them. We will tell them in advance what
we expect of them and we will be able to grade them on how they do.
That will be more helpful to this country.''
   Wilson was particularly upset that the administration did not
decertify Mexico, a country that borders on his state of California.
   ``How can we delude ourselves into thinking that Mexico should
be certified,'' he said. ``They should not. They have not
cooperated fully with the United States. If we are going to send
young drug agents into Mexico, we should demand full cooperation
and not wink at it. The 1986 act spelled out what is to be
expected, and it has not been done.''
   Chiles and Wilson both said the president relies too heavily on
the State Department for the basis of his certification of a
country. ``State is willing to be too tolerant in this area,'' said
Wilson.
   Rangel, chairman of the House Select Committee on Narcotics
Abuse and Control, said the U.S. felt for years that Colombia was
the primary cause of concern for the nation's drug problem but now
``it seems that we have an entire hemisphere to worry about. The
so-called spread of Communist influence is the least of our worries
in this region at this point in time.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
