<1ST_LINE>r p PM-VermontPrimary 1stLd-Writethru a0435 03-01 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Vermont Primary, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0435,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Vermont Primary Overshadowed By Super Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with turnout, inserting new 3rd graf</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MEG DENNISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vermont's ``beauty contest'' primary
today has been largely overshadowed by preparations for next week's
delegate-heavy Super Tuesday primaries, political observers say.
   Republican George Bush and Democrat Michael Dukakis _ who won
the Maine caucuses over the weekend _ were considered the
front-runners here, continuing to play on their ties to the region.
Bush, a Connecticut native, has a summer home in Maine; Dukakis is
the governor of Massachusetts.
   Vermont Secretary of State James Douglas predicted a record
turnout of 125,000 voters. Several communities reported strong
voting today under sunny skies, but turnout in the state's largest
city, Burlington, was running behind four years ago.
   Some had predicted that the Vermont primary _ falling between
the New Hampshire primary and Super Tuesday, March 8 _ would take
on more importance this year. But the primary has attracted little
attention.
   ``I think what we're seeing is we're getting jumped by Super
Tuesday,'' said Craig Fuller, executive director of the Vermont
Democratic Party.
   ``Vermont just got lost in the shuffle,'' said Garrison Nelson,
a political science professor at the University of Vermont. ``Those
timing factors when combined with the fact the Vermont primary is a
beauty contest ... led to an incredible loss of interest.''
   Tuesday's voting does not choose delegates; Vermonters merely
state their preferences in the non-binding primary. Delegates to
the national conventions will be elected at state conventions, a
process that begins in April with local caucuses to elect delegates
to the state convention.
   The candidates sent a lot of surrogates to stump for them, but
made few personal appearances.
   ``We got to see very little of the candidates. We saw their
mothers, their wives, their children, but we didn't see much of
them,'' Nelson said.
   Spokesmen for the candidates say attention now is on winning
delegates in local caucuses.
   ``That's our focus, that's where our energy is going even now,''
said Chris Wood, a campaign coordinator for Jesse Jackson, who
scored a surprisingly strong second in the weekend Maine Democratic
caucuses.
   ``I think there's a recognition that the (Vermont) primary is
the beginning of building for the caucus,'' said Marilyn Yager of
the Dukakis campaign.
   But Yager maintains Vermont probably gets more attention from
candidates than some of the 20 individual Super Tuesday states.
   ``No single state gets a lot of one-on-one attention,'' she said.
   Although non-binding, the Vermont primary has served an
important purpose in past years.
   In 1980, former President Jimmy Carter used a win in Vermont to
embarrass Sen. Ted Kennedy, D-Mass., in his own back yard. The same
year, a strong second-place finish in Vermont gave Republican John
Anderson's campaign a major boost.
   In 1984, Gary Hart's overwhelming defeat of Walter Mondale in
Vermont helped him shed his image as a dark horse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1225EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RuralPoor Bjt-1stAdd   03-01 0855</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rural Poor, Bjt - 1st Add,0875</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>TCHULA, Miss.: long-term decline.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Apparel manufacturing is Mississippi's leader in employment.
Besides that, furniture building is centered in the Tupelo area,
and catfish processing employs people in the Delta.
   Since the 1960s, manufacturing has employed more people than
farming in this state where 70 percent of the people live outside
urban areas _ and yet in some recent years the leading source of
income in Mississippi was neither. It was government ``transfer
payments'' _ Aid to Families with Dependent Children, Social
Security, food stamps.
   ``As the economy becomes more automated, more geared toward
people with skills,'' Pepper said, ``you're going to see more
people left out.''
   Asked the solution, he quoted Mississippi's new governor, Ray
Mabus: ``Education, education, education.''
   Without that, high-technology companies will continue to stay
away, agreed Jane Jackson, a lawyer working for the Mississippi
House of Representatives. ``You've got to get them (students)
enough math and English so that the Vo-Tech can teach them to work
for a Sony.''
   In rural areas nationally, 18 percent of people fall below the
poverty level, about $11,200 for a family of four, according to
1986 Census Bureau figures. That's the same rate as in inner-cities.
   ``I don't think the people who are masterminding this economy
are paying attention to this,'' said John Zippert of the Federation
of Southern Cooperatives, a group based in Alabama that helps
family farmers hold onto their land.
   ``It's a little like the underclass question of the urban ghetto
_ that there's going to be a permanent class that's going to be
left behind.''
   Left behind is a fitting description.
   ``In one year, rural areas across the country lost 632,000
people to metro areas due to migration,'' Leahy, D-Vt., has said.
``That's like saying that all of North Dakota migrated in one
year.'' Those who leave tend to be the best educated, say
officials, lamenting the rural ``brain drain.''
   It's not that nothing is being done to address the rural-urban
economic restructuring that Jesse White of the Southern Growth
Policies Board has termed ``just as profound as what was happening
in the Rustbelt.'' But many observers of the rural poor say the
efforts of government are piecemeal and inadequate.
   Federal funding for a variety of rural development programs
added up to about $1.6 billion last year, according to a study just
completed by the Center for Community Change, a research and
advocacy group in Washington, D.C. Those programs included grant
and loan programs of the Department of Housing and Urban
Development _ from which Tchula received its grant _ and the
Agriculture, Commerce and other departments.
   ``The funding levels have shrunk radically from what they were
at the end of the Carter administration,'' said Norm DeWeaver, who
led the study.
   The Reagan administration's policy has been to decentralize
efforts to aid rural development, noted the economic research
organization MDC Inc., of Chapel Hill, N.C., in a report last month.
   ``The federal government now dictates fewer rules and provides
fewer dollars. As a result,'' said MDC, ``... there is a surge of
economic and social initiatives in state governments throughout the
country.''
   Besides a new emphasis on improving education in virtually all
Southern states, initiatives cited by MDC included: a bank in
Arkansas that focuses mainly on rural economic development;
innovative literacy projects in Kentucky; and a biracial group in
struggling Noxubee County, Miss., that promotes home-grown
businesses.
   Nonetheless, the study cited ``many more dark rural places still
lacking the resources, the information, and the encouragement'' to
make significant economic progress, and it called for more
carefully targeted federal and private-sector help in giving
isolated places access to capital and management assistance,
education and training.
   Just outside of Tchula, the members of the Mileston Co-op know
what a little outside help can mean.
   Sitting in the spare country store that the co-op of black
farmers has owned for 40 years, Willie Lacy, the acting president,
talked about the donation they received from FarmAid, the charity
fund created by country musicians.
   Some of the members, whose cotton farms average about 50 acres,
used the money to pay delinquent taxes or overdue rent on land or
old fertilizer bills.
   ``I can remember one fella,'' Lacy said, ``he had everything,
but he couldn't get diesel _ so that helped him.''
   In the store, the afternoon gathering place now a month before
planting time, the co-op members say they could use a different
kind of outside help.
   They'd like to restart their cotton gin, which closed a few
years ago because of drought-stricken crops and lack of money _ and
they'd like to diversify, maybe open a plant that would process,
package and freeze vegetables grown in their fields.
   A plant like that would employ some of the workers displaced by
planting and picking machines. First, though, they'd need the
expertise to help ensure profitability, and second, the start-up
investment.
   The idea is not to get rich, the men said, but to employ people
and give the next generation a chance to stay here.
   ``I realize it wouldn't cure the problem,'' Lacy said, ``but
that would help some.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
