<DOCNO> AP880301-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1229EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FarmScene     03-01 0967</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farm Scene,0998</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drop in Lettuce, Other Vegetables Leads to Index Decline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lower prices for lettuce, tomatoes, cotton and
milk helped pushed down the Agriculture Department's index of
farm-level commodity prices in February.
   The price index declined 0.8 percent from January but still
averaged 6.6 percent above a year earlier, the department's
Agricultural Statistics Board said Monday.
   Higher prices for cattle, hogs, corn and soybeans helped soften
the declines for the other commodities, however.
   ``Most commercial vegetable prices dropped sharply from a month
earlier as supplies became plentiful,'' the report said. ``Warm
weather in the Southwest pushed vegetable crops to maturity.''
   But cattle and calf prices ``were the highest since May 1979''
and hog prices rose for the second month in a row, the report said.
Corn prices at the farm were the highest since July 1986, while
soybeans were the highest in more than three years.
   Department economists say net cash income of farmers set a
record in 1987 of about $57 billion. This year's net _ the
difference between cash receipts and cash expenses _ may be in the
range of $50 billion to $55 billion.
   Consumer food prices are expected to rise 2 percent to 4 percent
this year, compared with a 4.2 percent average increase in 1987.
   According to the preliminary February figures, based mostly on
mid-month averages, the index for crop prices was down 4.3 percent
from January but averaged 11 percent more than a year ago.
   Commercial vegetable prices dropped 33 percent from January and
were down 2.2 percent from February 1987. Sweet-corn prices rose
from January, while all other vegetables declined. Lettuce prices
dropped to $11.90 per 100 pounds from $35.60 in January.
   Feed grains and hay, collectively, showed a 3.2 percent price
gain from January, averaging 23 percent more than a year earlier.
Corn, sorghum, oats and hay were up, while barley prices declined
from January levels. Cotton prices were down 6 percent from January
but averaged 22 percent more than a year earlier.
   The index for livestock and livestock products was up 2 percent
from January and 4.2 percent above Februrary 1987. Prices were
higher for beef cattle, calves and hogs, which more than offset
declines in milk, poultry and egg prices.
   Prices of beef cattle averaged $67.90 per hundredweight, up
$2.50 from January. Calf prices, at $93.10, were up $4.90 per
hundredweight. Market hog prices rose $3.60 from January to $47.50
in February but were still below a year earlier.
   February farm commodity prices averaged 130 percent of a 1977
base used for comparison, according to the preliminary figures,
down from a revised January reading of 131 percent. A year ago, the
February index was 122 percent.
   No new figures for farm production costs were included in the
report. Those have been confined to quarterly averages because of
budget cutbacks.
   In January, however, farm expenses were up 0.6 percent from last
fall but averaged 1.4 percent below a year earlier. The next
quarterly figures will be reported in April.
   The report said:
   _ Cattle averaged $67.90 per 100 pounds of live weight
nationally, up from $65.40 in January and the $58.80 reported for
February 1987. Those are averages for all types of cattle sold as
beef.
   _ Hogs averaged $46.70 per 100 pounds, compared with $43 in
January and $48.20 a year earlier.
   _ Corn, at $1.83 a bushel, was up from $1.77 in January and the
average of $1.42 per bushel a year earlier.
   _ Wheat prices at the farm, according to preliminary figures,
averaged $2.83 per bushel, compared with $2.75 in January and $2.58
a year earlier.
   _ Rice averaged $7.85 per 100 pounds, compared with $7.70 in
January and $3.83 a year earlier.
   _ Soybeans were $5.90 per bushel, compared with $5.73 in January
and $4.69 a year earlier.
   _ Upland cotton was reported at 57.1 cents per pound, compared
with 60.6 in January and 46.4 cents in February 1987.
   _ Milk was $12.30 per 100 pounds, compared with $12.50 in
January and $12.90 a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department is making some
progress but still lags in expanding jobs and services to black
Americans, according to a panel's report.
   In 1986, Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng directed all
agencies in the department to carry out new guidelines to improve
USDA compliance with civil rights and equal opportunity standards.
   As part of the department's February observance of Black History
Month, five study groups looked at how USDA has performed since
then.
   ``Black employees continue a modest but upward movement in all
occupational categories,'' the report said Monday. ``Some increases
have been realized both in absolute numbers and as a percentage of
total USDA employment. This is especially important because the
increases have occurred at a time when overall employment in USDA
was declining.''
   The USDA employs the equivalent of approximately 102,000
full-time employees, according to recent budget documents. The task
force report said blacks comprise 8.4 percent of the department's
employees, up from 8.1 percent in 1986. But that ``is low compared
with other federal agencies,'' it added.
   ``To continue to improve its equal opportunity posture, USDA
must realize larger increases in the number of blacks hired,
promoted and trained,'' the report said. ``And such increases must
be realized at a faster pace. Additionally the department must
place emphasis on retention strategies once black employees are
recruited and hired.''
   The task force report said there are ``encouraging signs'' that
USDA agencies are beginning to address the complex problems of
black farmers and their declining numbers.
   ``Coordinated efforts between the Soil Conservation Service,
Farmers Home Administration and Extension Service are just
beginning to show limited success at eliminating the historical
factors militating against small and economically disadvantaged
farmers,'' the report said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
