<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-VOA 1stLd-Writethru a0509 03-01 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-VOA, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0509,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Protest VOA Broadcasts to Baltics</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New grafs 3-4, beginning ``In Washington,...'' to update with
comment from VOA director. Picks up 3rd graf pvs ``There have
been..''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Foreign Ministry has lodged a protest with the
U.S. Embassy over the ``subversive thrust'' of Voice of America
broadcasts on nationalist unrest in the Baltic republics, Tass
reported.
   The official news agency charged Monday that VOA reports beamed
into the Soviet Union ``have been crudely distorting historical
facts, making provocative insinuations about the growth of
nationalist sentiment in the Baltic republics of the Soviet Union
and expressing U.S. support for forces that do not accept the
social system in this country.''
   In Washington, VOA director Richard W. Carlson said today:
   ``The Soviet charges are false. We are covering stories about
nationality problems in the Baltics and elsewhere in the USSR
fairly and honestly. We have tens of millions of listeners in the
USSR and the Soviet authorities don't want them to hear the message
so they attack the messenger. The complaints are unfounded and
we'll just keep doing our job.''
   There have been a number of nationalist demonstrations in recent
months in the once-independent republics of Latvia, Lithuania and
Estonia on the Baltic Sea.
   Tass said the U.S. government-operated radio has taken a
``dramatically increased subversive thrust'' in reporting on the
situation in the Baltic region.
   The news agency said the protest was made to the U.S. Embassy in
Moscow.
   The Soviets last May stopped routine jamming of VOA
Russian-language broadcasts, but there have been occasional
complaints in the official media about information broadcast by the
service.
</TEXT>
