<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 2ndLd-Writethru a0602 03-01 0951</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0602,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dole Attacks Bush With Iran-Contra Ads</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with Gephardt-Carter meeting, inserting new grafs
3-4, and subbing 1 graf for grafs 8-9 pvs, One Southern ...
Democratic caucuses.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURA KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   GOP presidential contender Bob Dole struck at George Bush in new
TV ads today, including one declaring Bush supported arms deals
with Iran, as Pat Robertson sought Cuban-Americans' support with
new talk about missiles in Cuba.
   The biggest delegate day of the primary season is a week from
today, and the presidential candidates were swarming across the
South, where most of the 20 Super Tuesday states are located. Jesse
Jackson started his day in New York, but then he, too, headed
South, to Baltimore for more campaigning.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt paid a call today on former President
Carter, who made it clear that with fellow Georgian Sam Nunn not in
the race he had no plans to endorse anyone before the Democratic
convention next July.
   Carter also said he thought there was a 50-50 chance that no one
will have clinched the party's nomination before the convention.
   Dole, in Durham, N.C., trails Vice President Bush in Southern
polls, and he began the final week before Super Tuesday with public
and televised attacks.
   The Senate minority leader accused Bush of offering ``nine
different answers'' on the Iran-Contra affair. ``But it's a fact he
did support it,'' Dole said.
   In Fort Lauderdale, meanwhile, Robertson said today a transcript
of 1967 Senate subcommittee testimony supports his belief there are
nuclear missiles in Cuba.
   The former television evangelist quoted testimony from a State
Department official who said Cuban refugees had told him about
seeing missiles.
   ``This is documented evidence,'' Robertson said today at a
breakfast attended by about 600 supporters. The Reagan
administration has denied his contention about missiles in Cuba,
which he first made in a debate in New Hampshire last month.
   Vermont began its non-binding ``beauty contest'' primary today
under sunny skies with a record turnout predicted and Michael
Dukakis, the governor of neighboring Massachusetts, the Demcratic
favorite.
   On the GOP side, Bush, who won Maine's GOP caucuses, has a
strong organization in Vermont, but Dole has won endorsements from
some top Republicans.
   Bush was campaigning in another pre-Super Tuesday state _ South
Carolina, which holds its primary Saturday. As he did in New
Hampshire, the vice president brought in former Arizona Sen. Barry
Goldwater, a hero to conservatives, to stump for him.
   Polls have given Bush a comfortable lead in South Carolina, but
he said he was taking nothing for granted.
   ``Two days before New Hampshire, some of the most respected
pollsters showed me down and almost out,'' he said Monday in
Charleston. Bush won the Feb. 16 New Hampshire primary by a solid
margin, after polls suggested rival Bob Dole was breathing down his
neck.
   Dole, on a Southern swing that took him to Mississippi, Georgia
and Florida, heaped scorn on the vice president, characterizing him
as a passive figure.
   ``Ask him what's he done in the last seven years,'' Dole said at
a Fort Lauderdale rally. ``What's he done anywhere in America or
the world to make a difference?''
   Continuing that theme, Dole unleashed a television ad which
depicts the vice president walking through the snow without leaving
any footprints. Dole's campaign said the commercial was having a
test run in Miami and other selected cities.
   Robertson, in Miami on Monday, produced a Cuban refugee who he
said had seen missiles in Cuba. The Cuban, who spoke through an
interpreter and identified himself only as E. Rodriguez, said he
had seen missile sites, but did not know whether the weapons had
nuclear warheads.
   Robertson also told Cuban-American senior citizens he would work
with them for an independent and democratic Cuba. ``Viva Cuba
Libre!'' he said. At a mostly Hispanic high school, he called
Castro a ``butcher and a tyrant.''
   Meanwhile, Democratic rivals Dukakis and Gephardt, who have been
trading victories in the early caucuses and primaries, traded jabs
at a Democratic debate in Williamsburg, Va.
   Dukakis ridiculed the Missouri congressman for ``running around
the country beating up on the establishment'' while accepting
political contributions from special interest groups. Gary Hart was
also critical of the practice.
   Gephardt called it ``an affront'' to suggest that such
contributions would influence the way he votes in Congress.
   During the debate, Jackson said he has sometimes been singled
out for different treatment during the campaign because of his
race. He cited an exit poll in which voters were asked if they
would support a black candidate for president.
   ``I said, did you ask how many would vote for a Greek?'' said
Jackson, referring to Dukakis, who is of Greek descent. ``My race
is self-evident and my leadership is obvious.''
   Earlier in the day, Jackson visited racially troubled Robeson
County in North Carolina and drew a comparison with white-ruled
South Africa.
   ``In South Africa people have been abandoned by the law. No law
protects them,'' he said. ``What is happening right here ... is a
whole body of people has been abandoned by the law.''
   He made the same comparison in Houston, where he walked through
a trash-strewn neighborhood. Jackson suggested city officials want
to force poor residents out and redevelop the property, likening it
to the South African government relocating blacks.
   He told college students at Pembroke State University that his
strong second-place showing in the Maine caucuses proves he has
broadened his appeal. ``Talk about mainstream; try the state of
Maine!'' he said.
   At Monday night's Democratic debate, at Jackson's suggestion,
the candidates wore yellow ribbons on their jackets in protest of
the arrest of Anglican Archbishop Desmond Tutu in South Africa.
</TEXT>
