<1ST_LINE>r i AM-TreasureHunt     03-01 0388</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Treasure Hunt,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Defends Controverisal Treasure Hunt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MLA2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Tuesday defended a
treasure hunt at a historic Spanish fort and extended the U.S.
contractor's digging permit for another month.
   On Monday, the Senate approved a resolution calling for a halt
to the search for Japanese treasure believed buried at Fort
Santiago, which was active during the Spanish occupation that ended
in 1898 and later was used by the Japanese as a garrison during
World War II.
   The Senate action followed a speech by opposition Sen. Juan
Ponce Enrile, who said the search was being conducted ``by
foreigners whose only reason for being here is perhaps their greed
for gold.'' Enrile charged it was an insult to national honor.
   International Precious Metals Inc., a U.S. concern, began
excavating this month at a chamber in Fort Santiago for gold
believed buried there by Japanese soldiers at the end of World War
II. The company has agreed to give the government 75 percent of
whatever is recovered.
   National Security Adviser Emmanuel Soriano, who is monitoring
the project for the government, told reporters Tuesday the
government approved the company's request to extend the dig for 30
days. The contract would have expired this week.
   ``Nothing is going on right there in Fort Santiago that would
desecrate the national shrine,'' Soriano said in response to
Enrile's speech. He said Enrile had known of digging at the same
site when he was defense minister under President Ferdinand Marcos
in 1975 but had not moved to block it.
   Soriano said the dig was an ``authorized and legitimate project
of which the beneficiary would be the Filipino people,'' and that
the contractors would restore the excavated portions of the fort.
   Soriano said Charles MacDougald, an official of the U.S.
company, had reported they expect to recover gold bullion believed
hidden in the fort within 10 to 15 days.
   The treasure hunt was widely publicized after two Filipino
workers were killed last week when a tunnel they were digging
collapsed.
   Soriano said his company would give the equivalent of $5,000 to
each to the families of the two workers. Work has since resumed,
with troops now guarding the site around the clock.
   Manila Mayor Gemiliano Lopez, who inspected the site Tuesday,
said the dig was about 17 feet deep.
</TEXT>
