<2ND_LINE>AM-Family Killed,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Family of Five Found Dead; Police Suspect Murder-Suicide</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH PICHT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GROVELAND, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators say a marriage in trouble
may have prompted a man to kill his wife and their three children
before setting the family's home on fire and fatally shooting
himself.
   Firefighters discovered the bodies of Lawrence Delabarto, 32,
his wife and their children, all in bed, late Sunday night after
responding to the fire.
   ``I am told by family and friends that there were some marital
difficulties,'' Livingston County Sheriff Richard Kane said Monday.
``His (Delabarto's) wounds are consistent with suicide, plus we
found that all the doors were locked and the phone was off the hook
which would indicate that this was planned.''
   Delabarto's body was found in bed next to his wife, 32-year-old
Linda, and a .16-gauge shotgun, Kane said.
   A preliminary examination indicated that Mrs. Delabarto had been
strangled, and that Delabarto and the children _ 12-year-old
Anthony, 10-year-old Danielle, and 6-year-old Dominic _ had been
shot, Kane aid.
   Investigators said the fire was started with fuel oil that had
been poured in several rooms.
   Kane said the family had gone to church on Sunday and had
breakfast with Delabarto's parents, who live in Geneseo.
   ``The father had no indication of any problems,'' Kane said.
   There also didn't seem to be anything unusual at Riverside Wine
and Liquor Co. in Mount Morris where Delabarto had worked as a
truckdriver for 2{ years.
   Richard Radesi, the company's owner, said Delabarto was
dependable, well-liked, proud of his family and ``just as congenial
as he could be.''
</TEXT>
