<HEAD>Convicted `Onion Field' Murderer To Serve 180 Days</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Convicted ``Onion Field'' murderer Jimmie
Lee Smith was ordered jailed for 180 days after he pleaded guilty
to misdemeanor possession of a hypodermic needle.
   Municipal Court Commissioner Alan S. Kalkin sentenced Smith on
Monday.
   Smith, 57, was arrested in November for allegedly driving under
the influence of an opiate after he was stopped for a traffic
violation.
   Smith has been on parole since March 1987 after serving three
years for a 1984 conviction on possession of heroin for sale. If
probation authorities deem he violated parole, Smith could go
immediately to state prison to serve the term.
   Convicted with Gregory Ulas Powell for shooting an officer in an
onion field in 1963, Smith served 19 years and was released on
parole in 1982. Powell is serving a life term.
   The case was made famous by Joseph Wambaugh's 1973 novel ``The
Onion Field,'' which later was made into a movie.
