<1ST_LINE>r w AM-EducationSpending     03-01 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Education Spending,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bennett Gets Friendly Capitol Hill Reception With New Spending
Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary William J. Bennett visited
Capitol Hill on Tuesday to promote his education spending proposal
for 1989 and found a friendlier reception than in past years, when
he was seeking cuts.
   The Reagan administration is asking for $21.2 billion in
education spending authority _ about $850 million or 4 percent
above the current level.
   ``This is a bill that should go through the House in one hour,''
Rep. William Natcher, D-Ky., chairman of the Appropriations
subcommittee on labor, health and education, told Bennett.
   ``I would imagine the seat that you're sitting in is quite a bit
cooler than it has been in the last few years,'' added Rep. Silvio
Conte, R-Mass.
   Bennett laughed and denied Conte's assertion that he had
undergone a conversion and become a ``born-again education
spender.''
   ``I'm the same old mad Catholic I always was,'' Bennett said.
   Bennett said the education request was as high as possible under
the outlines of the deficit reduction agreement reached last year
between Congress and the administration.
   That agreement limited overall domestic spending increases to 2
percent. The proposed 4 percent education hike is ``way above
average,'' Bennett said. ``This is pretty much to the limit of what
we could in good conscience ask for.''
   Natcher questioned Bennett closely on proposed cuts in certain
types of student loans, a public libraries program and grants meant
to offset tax losses in areas with federal installations.
   He hinted the House might not go along with those cuts but
promised Bennett, ``We're going to bring you out a good bill. We're
going to bring out a bill that both you and I will like.''
   The administration has proposed expansions in a number of
programs, including Pell grants to needy college students, aid to
disadvantaged children, magnet schools and a college loan program
under which repayments are pegged to future income.
   Congress has consistently appropriated more for education than
the Reagan administration has sought. The fiscal 1989 education
increase is only the second one requested by the Reagan
administration. The first came in 1984, another election year.
   Rep. David Obey, D-Wis., pointed that out in a statement and
noted that ``our kids go to school every year, not just election
years. ... Local school boards need help that isn't turned on and
off with election cycles.''
</TEXT>
