<HEAD>Two Fargo Police Officers Reprimanded For Bar Shooting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FARGO, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two police officers have been reprimanded for
persuading a deputy U.S. marshal to shoot out a light fixture in a
crowded bar, the police chief said Tuesday.
   The bullet richocheted behind the bar after striking the light,
but no one was injured.
   Officers David Sanders and Robert Kind were told they ``acted in
a way that brought unfavorable criticism upon the department,''
Chief Doug Franks said Tuesday.
   Sanders and Kind were sitting at a table with deputy U.S.
Marshal Garry Carroll at a Feb. 18 party attended by as many as 20
off-duty lawmen when they challenged Carroll to shoot out the
light, Franks said.
   Carroll was charged with reckless endangerment and is to appear
at a preliminary hearing March 7.
   Sanders and Kind will be suspended for a minimum of three days
if they are involved in a similar incident within the next 18
months, Franks said. Letters of reprimand will remain in their
personnel files, he said.
   No action has been taken against any other officers.
