<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1335EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DOE-ReactorSafety     03-01 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-DOE-Reactor Safety,300</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dicks Urges Creation of New Safety Agency To Oversee DOE Reactors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It would be counterproductive to create a new,
independent agency to oversee safety at federal nuclear weapons
materials facilities, a top Department of Energy official to
Congress on Tuesday.
   But Rep. Norm Dicks, D-Wash., urged the subcommittee to approve
legislation creating such a watchdog agency, calling the
department's plan to establish an advisory committee ``an
inadequate response.''
   DOE operates 40 major facilities in 34 states, including
reactors that produce plutonium and tritium and plants that refine
it for use in nuclear weapons.
   Joseph Salgado, a DOE undersecretary, told the House Armed
Services procurement and military nuclear systems subcommittee it
would be ``premature'' to create an outside agency.
   ``The advisory committee needs time to work, to prove its
credibility,'' Salgado said.
   The DOE official said a new agency would be ``regulatory,
counterproductive and adversarial'' and could ``severely hamper the
department's ability to perform its national security and energy
research missions.
   Dicks has introduced legislation that would create a Defense
Nuclear Facilities Safety Agency. It would have the authority to
shut down any reactor or plant that was found unsafe.
   A new agency would cost between $6 million and $10 million a
year to operate and funds could be taken from current DOE safety
oversight programs to pay for it, Dicks said.
   The administrator of the agency would be appointed by the
president and confirmed by the Senate.
   Dicks said that DOE was caught between the Department of
Defense's demands for nuclear materials and the need to operate the
facilities safely.
   ``Studies conducted in recent years have revealed disturbing
evidence that DOE's defense facilities are not only operating with
deteriorating and unpredictable equipment, but receive oversight
through a poorly managed and ineffcient safety assurance process,''
Dicks said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
