<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AlligatorDies     03-01 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alligator Dies,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hobbs Says Goodbye to John Roger The Alligator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOBBS, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Roger, the alligator who was flushed
into the Hobbs sewer system as a baby and lived a pampered life in
his own solar home at the city water treatment plant, was buried
Tuesday.
   The alligator was buried 16 years after sewer workers named John
and Roger found the 24-inch reptile swimming in an effluent pond.
   John Roger was 7 feet, 9 inches long at the time of his death
Monday. He lived in a fenced compound that included a solar-heated
home, diving pond and grass knoll for sunbathing.
   The alligator's body was found at the compound at the bottom of
his pool. He apparently had gone for a post-hibernation swim. No
necropsy was scheduled but officials suspected the alligator died
of pneumonia.
   State Sen. Joe Harvey, who was city manager at the time John
Roger was adopted, recalled the alligator was fond of frogs.
   ``There were months where there wasn't a live frog in this
town,'' Harvey said. ``Kids found out that John Roger liked frogs _
live frogs _ and they'd go out and find them, then throw them over
the fence of his compound.''
</TEXT>
