<HEAD>Plane Crash Kills 17 In South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A small passenger plane
exploded in flight Tuesday and crashed in an industrial area east
of Johannesburg, killing all 17 people on board, the South African
Broadcasting Corp. reported.
   The radio said the plane was operated by Comair, a private
commercial airline that flies between Johannesburg and towns in
north and central South Africa.
   The twin-engine plane, a Brazilian-made Bandeirante turboprop,
was en route to Johannesburg from the northern border town of
Phalaborwa when it crashed, state-run South African Broadcasting
reported. It said all 15 passengers and two crew members aboard
were killed.
   There was no immediate indication what caused the crash.
Witnesses told reporters they heard an explosion and saw what
appeared to be two pieces of the plane plunge to the ground.
   The plane went down in an area called Wadeville, about six miles
east of downtown Johannesburg.
   The identities of the victims were not immediately known.
   The Bandeirante can accommodate up to 18 passengers.
