<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Subways,0166</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Subway Ridership Up for 3rd Straight Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ridership on New York subways increased for the
third straight year in 1987 to its highest level in 13 years, the
Transit Authority reported Tuesday.
   TA President David Gunn attributed much of the increase to new
and overhauled cars on some lines and a boost in the number of
clean cars.
   Officials also said subway crime was down 8.1 percent for
serious felonies from 1986. TA spokesman Albert O'Leary said there
were 12,888 felonies on the subways last year compared with 14,030
in the previous 12 months.
   Gunn said 3,626,000 people rode the subways on an average
weekday last year, up by 216,000 from 1984 and 103,000 from 1986.
In all, 1.059 billion passengers rode the subways last year, up 29
million from 1986 and 62 million from 1984.
   Gunn said that 94 percent of the subway fleet should be
graffiti-free by the end of this year.
