<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Asbestos-Court     03-01 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asbestos-Court,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Asbestos Sends Trials to Motel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TITUSVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge presided in the banquet room
at the Quality Inn. Tourists by the pool did a double-take when a
prisoner went by in handcuffs, while lawyers consulted under beach
umbrellas.
   ``The court reporter said she wasn't sure she got a good
transcript because of the noise from the kitchen,'' said Circuit
Judge Gil Goshorn.
   Such incongruous scenes have been taking place in Titusville
this week as judges, prosecutors, clerical workers and other county
employees moved out of the Brevard County Courthouse, which was
closed because of asbestos contamination.
   County officials quarantined the courthouse Saturday when air
tests showed asbestos levels far above federal standards in several
rooms. Some levels were considered dangerously high, and most
employees were urged to get medical tests.
   Asbestos was widely used for insulation and fireproofing until
the federal government banned its use in 1979.
   The county clerk's office set up shop in modular buildings in
the courthouse parking lot. Workers wearing breathing masks hurried
to build a plywood and plastic ``cocoon'' to provide safe access to
the clerk's computers inside the courthouse.
   All documents were locked inside when the courthouse was
evacuated. Experts said all paperwork and even many computer
terminals were contaminated and would have to be carefully dusted
and cleaned as they are removed piece-by-piece from the building.
   The closing of the court house also affects real estate
transactions, court-ordered child support payments and other
operations.
</TEXT>
