<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Bosch     03-01 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bosch,0578</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bosch Release Order Stayed Pending Government Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ordered the U.S. Parole Commission
on Tuesday to free an anti-Castro activist who has been in a
Venezuelan prison for 11 years on bond, but he stayed his order to
allow the agency to appeal.
   Even if Orlando Bosch won his freedom, U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service officials were waiting in the wings to take
custody of him, they said Tuesday.
   Bosch, a hero in Miami's Cuban community, has been in jail since
he arrived last month from Venezuela, where he spent 11 years in
prison despite being acquitted three times of bombing a Cuban
airliner.
   U.S. authorities said Bosch had violated parole by fleeing this
country in 1974 while on probation for planning a bazooka attack on
a Polish ship in the port of Miami in 1968, and conspiring to plant
bombs on other ships.
   Bosch's daughter, Lourdes, said outside court that she was
pleased with U.S. District Judge Kenneth L. Ryskamp's order. But,
she added, ``I am just confused and upset that now this is going to
be appealed and they can stall another week or more. To me, it's
just a farce, a political farce.''
   Ryskamp called Bosch's imprisonment until a scheduled March 21
parole hearing ``totally arbitrary and capricious.''
   Ryskamp said Parole Commissioner G. Mackenzie Rast used ``tunnel
vision in picking out those facts he wants to rely upon'' when he
ordered Bosch to remain jailed.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Chuck Senatore said he would appeal
Ryskamp's decision to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
Atlanta, and the judge granted a temporary stay of his release
order.
   Even if the appeals court upholds Ryskamp, Bosch also cannot be
released until his lawyers convince the INS.
   ``We of course have a detainer on him and would be holding him
on an immigration violation,'' said INS district director Perry
Rivkind.
   The INS has targeted Bosch for exclusion hearings and possible
deportation because he entered the United States without legal
immigration documents last month after his release from a
Venezuelan prison.
   INS officials have said they will not permit Bosch's release and
have labeled him a terrorist because of his conviction for
conspiring to bomb the Polish ship. Parole officials also accused
him of consorting with known criminals.
   On the probation commission order, Ryskamp said Rast went beyond
the facts on record to conclude that Bosch should be held. The
judge said Rast apparently considered Bosch's acquittals in
Venezuela as a strike against him and wrongly considered
``reported'' past associations of Bosch with known criminals.
   ``If that's going to be the basis of denying somebody their
liberty rights, then it's a sad day for the Constitution,'' said
Ryskamp. The judge also noted that Rast evidently reviewed
information in Bosch's parole file which was never disclosed to
Bosch.
   The judge also noted that Rast ignored the recommendation of a
probation officer who interviewed Bosch and concluded there was no
risk that he would flee.
   Ryskamp set bond at $250,000 and said that if Bosch is freed he
cannot make public appearances or statements or identify himself
with any militant groups opposing the Cuban government of Fidel
Castro. He also could not receive more than five visitors in his
home at any one time and would be required to report in three times
a day by telephone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
