<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BeachBoys     03-01 0459</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Beach Boys,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer Brian Wilson's Psychologist Accused Of Drug, Sex Misconduct</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State medical authorities want to revoke the
license of a psychologist who has been Beach Boy Brian Wilson's
therapist, alleging the man financially exploited the eccentric
songwriter.
   In documents released Monday, the Board of Medical Quality
Assurance accused psychologist Eugene Landy of drug violations,
patient sexual abuse and ``grossly negligent'' conduct.
   Seven causes of action were filed against Landy, Wilson's
near-constant companion for the last five years.
   The accusations largely concern Landy's relationship with
Wilson, saying multiple business relationships with Wilson caused
the singer ``severe emotional damage, psychological dependence and
financial exploitation.''
   A request for comment was left at the office of a spokesman for
Wilson and Landy on Tuesday but there was no immediate response.
   Attorney John Mason, representing Wilson, said the accusations
were false.
   ``Brian Wilson has made a miraculous recovery with the help of
Dr. Landy, psychologically, physically and financially. He's in the
best shape he's ever been in his life,'' Mason said.
   Landy has said he became a virtual 24-hour guardian of Wilson to
save him from obesity and a dependence on drugs and alcohol that
left him cloistered in a sand box in his house for a year.
   In a 1983 interview in People magazine, Landy said his staff
controlled Wilson's every moment, monitored everything he ate and
drank and recorded everything he said.
   The medical board said Landy abused his privileges as a
psychologist by serving as Wilson's business manager, business
adviser, executive producer and co-songwriter while also as a
therapist.
   Last year, the Beach Boys formed a management advisory committee
to make business decisions. The state board said Landy used his
influence over Wilson to be picked as the singer's representative,
and was paid $140,000 for serving on the committee for 11 months.
   Also questioned was Landy's control of Wilson's prescription
drugs for a five-year period. Psychologists are not permitted to
prescribe drugs.
   The board said Landy would have Wilson examined by a physician
who would prescribe medications that were kept in Wilson's home in
a locked cabinet. Wilson didn't have a key, but Landy's unlicensed
assistants did.
   Landy was also accused by the board of using cocaine and amyl
nitrate with an unidentified female patient to induce her to have
sex with him.
   Linda McCready, a spokeswoman for the board's Sacramento office,
said the next step in Landy's case is for the state attorney
general to schedule a hearing before an administrative law judge,
which usually takes six months.
   The judge would make a recommendation to the board's psychology
examining committee, which will determine what action to take. Ms.
McCready said if Landy disagrees with the committee's decision he
can appeal to Superior Court.
</TEXT>
