<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionPetitions     03-01 0356</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Petitions,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pro-Choice Groups Submit Signatures to Put Abortion Issue On
Ballot</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHERINE RIZZO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pro-choice groups filed 229,128 signatures
Tuesday in support of a statewide vote on whether Michigan should
continue to pay for poor women's abortions.
   That gave the People's Campaign for Choice coalition more than
100,000 names above the minimum needed to put the issue on the Nov.
8 ballot and suspend a new law that will halt welfare abortion
funding beginning March 29.
   However, the petitions may have been filed too late to avoid a
temporary funding cutoff.
   ``We have every reason to believe that 29 days is enough time''
to confirm the required 119,829 valid signatures and put the law on
hold, said Judith Frey, speaking for the coalition.
   ``I would find that very unlikely,'' responded Elections
Director Christopher Thomas. He said election-year petition
certification normally takes 45 days to 60 days.
   Both Frey and Right to Life of Michigan President Barbara
Listing said they were confident the signatures will be certified.
   ``It's a large pad. It's certainly enough to, I think, place it
on the ballot,'' Listing said.
   Both sides have estimated the statewide campaign to sway
referendum votes will cost $2 million to $3 million.
   The petition drive that ended Tuesday was the second in as many
years dealing with welfare abortion funding.
   Since 1978, Gov. James Blanchard, a Democrat, and his Republican
predecessor, William Milliken, have used their veto power 17 times
to preserve state-paid abortions for the poor.
   Right to Life initiated the no-funding law last year with a
petition drive intended to avoid the veto.
   In Michigan, anyone who can gather 191,726 valid signatures can
place before the Legislature a measure that, if approved by both
houses, becomes law without the governor's signature.
   After gathering about 400,000 signatures, the Right to
Life-written proposal breezed through the Legislature and became
law.
   Michigan is one of 14 states that uses taxpayer money to finance
abortions for the poor. In 1986, the most recent year for which a
final tally is available, Michigan paid about $5.8 million for
18,600 abortions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
