<DOCNO> AP880301-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1527EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-KennedyMuseum     03-01 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kennedy Museum,0254</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Commissioners Approve $2.3 Million Contract For Construction of
Museum</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After a struggle to fund an exhibit on the
assassination of President John F. Kennedy, the Dallas County
Commission approved a $2.3 million contract to build an elevator to
what was believed to have been the killer's perch.
   ``The eyes of the world will be on this project,'' said Lindalyn
Adams, president of Dallas County Historical Foundation. ``As sad
as it is, it is the most important historical site in Dallas.''
   The foundation has worked 11 years to get the exhibit funded,
and plans to raise $1.5 million more from private sources for
additional renovations on the sixth floor of the former Texas
Schoolbook Depository.
   The Warren Commission determined that Lee Harvey Oswald fired at
Kennedy from the sixth floor of what is now the Dallas County
Administration Building on Nov. 22, 1963.
   The contract award was approved by a 3-2 vote Monday to Thomas
J. Hayman Construction Co., which could begin work as early as this
week.
   The exhibit, ``The Sixth Floor,'' will be reached via an outside
elevator that will carry an estimated 300,000 to 500,000 visitors
annually to the exhibit without disrupting work inside.
   Tony Callaway, a partner in the architectural firm of Hendrick
Callaway, said construction could be completed by November.
Foundation officials say they are unlikely to schedule the
exhibit's opening Nov. 22, the 25th anniversary of Kennedy's
assassination.
   ``We think it would be inappropriate,'' Adams said.
</TEXT>
