<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1545EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-AfghanistanTalks Bjt   03-01 0693</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan Talks, Bjt,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Peace Talks Poised For Crucial Stage</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks on Afghanistan open their most crucial
and fragile phase on Wednesday, one that is widely hoped to produce
a settlement to end a conflict that has claimed more than a million
lives.
   But complex and potentially disruptive issues remain to be
resolved during the United Nations-sponsored talks before a package
of agreements, drawn up during almost six years of bargaining,
finally can be completed.
   U.N. mediator Diego Cordovez has said the new round of talks
will focus on closing the gap between the varying timetables for
withdrawing an estimated 115,000 Soviet troops.
   But likely to dominate the talks is a question that is formally
outside their scope: Who will be in charge in Kabul until all
Soviet troops have moved out?
   Delegates from Afghanistan and from Pakistan both said Tuesday
that they have come to Geneva to finalize a settlement to end the
9-year-old conflict.
   But Pakistan Foreign Minister Zain Noorani said his country
would decide next week whether it was prepared to sign the peace
package with the present Marxist government of President Najib,
which it does not recognize.
   Noorani said Pakistan is continuing to press for the formation
of a transitional government to coincide with the withdrawal of
Soviet troops. Without it, he said, there can be no peace.
   But he said ``we have come to Geneva with a constructive
attitude to finalize the text'' of the four-agreement package.
   Meanwhile, the head of the Afghan delegation, foreign minister
Abdul Wakil, told a news conference that he was looking forward to
the new round with a ``sense of full optimism.''
   The present leadership, he said, were ``not ambitious'' about
retaining power. He said the timetable for the withdrawal was
``within negotiable range.''
   The negotiations have come under mounting pressure since Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev announced Feb. 8 that Moscow will
withdraw its troops beginning on May 15 if a final deal is sealed
in Geneva by March 15.
   He said the withdrawal could be completed in 10 months. Pakistan
originally demanded that the troops quit in three months but has
gradually widened that span to eight months.
   Pakistan wants the settlement to include the transitional
government because it could oversee the safe return of more than 5
million anti-Soviet Afghan refugees, one-third of Afghanistan's
pre-war population.
   Moscow has accused Pakistan of creating last-minute obstacles to
an accord and said the makeup of the government should be left to
the Afghans.
   The alliance of Pakistan-based Afghan resistance groups,
claiming to represent 200,000 Moslem guerrillas, responded last
week by revealing its own plan for a government.
   It has ruled out any power-sharing with Najib but offered a
minor role to ``Moslems presently living in Kabul,'' a formula that
could refer to moderates in the present government.
   Yunis Khalis, chairman of the seven-group alliance, vowed the
guerrillas won't lay down their arms until the ``Islamic
government'' is set up.
   Predictably, that concept has been rejected by Najib and Wakil,
who heads the Afghan delegation in Geneva. Wakil says he represents
the ``only legal government in Afghanistan which has been
recognized by 80 countries.''
   Pakistan so far has not given its formal support to the
guerrilla proposal and has hinted it prefers a more broad-based
approach.
   The United States, which along with the Soviet Union is to
guarantee implementation of the peace package, has been ambivalent
in its reaction to the calls for an interim government.
   But the U.S. Senate, in a non-binding resolution Monday, urged
formation of an interim government in Kabul that is acceptable to
the Afghan resistance.
   U.S. Undersecretary of State Michael Armacost, visiting Pakistan
last week, said the guerrilla plan was a ``very welcome step
towards the resolution of the Afghan problem.''
   There has also been a lack of clear signals on when Washington
would be prepared to cut off its aid to the guerrillas, reported to
have been about $700 million last year.
   The Afghan monarchy was overthrown in 1978 and a communist
government was installed. The Soviets intervened at the request of
the embattled new Marxist government.
</TEXT>
