<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congress-Drugs     03-01 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congress-Drugs,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Criticize Administration's Anti-Drug Efforts</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Drug Wars Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration has failed to stop
the heavy influx of illicit drugs into the United States, a group
of congressmen told a White House conference on drugs Tuesday.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., said the administration has earned
nothing more than a ``C'' grade for its efforts in the so-called
war on drugs. Rep. Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chided administration
officials, including President Reagan, for claiming the battle
against drugs was being won.
   ``If we are winning the war on drugs, I wish the commanders
would go out and tell it to the troops in the field,'' Rangel said,
drawing a standing ovation from a cheering crowd of about 2,000 at
the White House Conference on a Drug-Free America.
   ``It's tragic to believe we are winning this battle against
drugs when we haven't even fired the first shot,'' said Rangel, who
is chairman of the House Narcotics Committee.
   He and six other members of Congress criticized the
administration, as well as their own colleagues, for not taking
such actions as sanctions toward Latin America countries who do not
cooperate with the U.S. in trying to combat drug trafficking.
   They urged the creation of a drug czar to oversee the U.S.
anti-drug efforts, the use of military forces for the interdiction
of drugs from Latin America countries and the mandatory, random
testing of railroad employees.
   Rangel and Chiles were joined at the Congressional Forum of the
five-day White House drug conference by Sens. Pete Wilson,
R-Calif., and John C. Danforth, R-Mo., and Reps. Glenn English,
D-Okla., Benjamin A. Gilman, R-N.Y., and E. Clay Shaw, R-Fla.
   The conference, which was required by a 1986 anti-drug law, is
bringing together drug abuse experts who will submit a final report
and recommend solutions to the president and Congress this summer.
   Shaw told the enthusiastic crowd: ``We need to get away from a
policy of containment. We want you to come up with a plan for
victory. Let's fight it like we fought World War II, not like
Vietnam. Let's fight to win.''
   Rangel and several others praised the role first lady Nancy
Reagan has played during the past seven years in her anti-drug
campaign, ``Say No to Drugs.''
   ``Thank God, we have Nancy Reagan,'' Rangel said. ``She is the
only voice we have in this administration. We have no domestic or
foreign policy on drugs. If you want to fight this war, you have to
put up the resources for the boys in the front lines.''
   Chiles and Wilson also said there has been a lack of resources
assigned to the the battle against drugs.
   ``Nothing is a bigger threat internally or externally than the
use of drugs,'' Wilson said. ``We have to focus on the problem and
set priorities before it engulfs us completely.''
   Chiles, Wilson and Rangel also urged Reagan to impose severe
sanctions against Latin American countries, particularly Panama,
Mexico and Colombia, if they refuse to cooperate with the United
States in combatting drug trafficking.
   Under the 1986 law, the United States is to decertify and cut
off aid to countries ``not fully cooperating'' with the United
States to combat drug traffic.
   Reagan decided Tuesday that Panama, Afghanistan, Iran and Syria
have not cooperated with U.S. efforts to stop the drug smuggling to
American markets. But Ann Wrobleski, a State Department official
responsible for narcotics matters, said Reagan planned no steps to
penalize Panama economically beyond measures already taken.
   Reagan certified that Mexico and Colombia are cooperating with
U.S. drug enforcement efforts, but Ms. Wrobleski said the president
indicated that ``these countries should do more.''
   Reagan will ``wait and see'' if Panama's military-dominated
government improves its cooperation before deciding on additional
sanctions, she said.
   The decisions concerning Afghanistan, Iran and Syria will have
no economic impact on them, partly because none is a U.S. aid
recipient.
   Chiles said many members of Congress believe the administration
has not used the certification process properly.
   ``This year, the good news is that Panama is on the list,''
Chiles said. ``On the other hand, Mexico and Colombia aren't. ... I
think we have to continue to apply pressure against these
countries.''
</TEXT>
