<1ST_LINE>u w AM-ConstructionSpending     03-01 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Construction Spending,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Construction Spending Down 2.9 Percent in January</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Construction spending fell 2.9 percent in
January, the biggest decline in 10 months, reflecting widespread
weakness in all sectors of the building industry, the government
reported Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said construction spending fell to a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of $395.2 billion in January
following a revised 0.4 percent advance in December.
   Economists said the decline was bigger than expected and will
likely mean that construction will be a drag on overall economic
growth in the first quarter of 1988.
   ``What was surprising about the figures was how widespread and
pervasive the weakness was. Virtually every category from housing
to industrial to hotels and motels did poorly in January,'' said
Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co.
   Michael Sumichrast, an economist and publisher of a construction
industry newsletter, said he expects housing starts to fall by
about 15 percent this year and non-residential construction to drop
by 10 percent.
   ``I haven't found any area in the United States with strong
housing activity. The only strong area is public construction,
which I think will rise by about 4 percent,'' Sumichrast said.
   The January decline was the largest since a 3.3 percent drop in
March 1987, but some analysts said unusually severe weather in
January may have contributed to the decline.
   Residential contruction fell 2.6 percent to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $191.3 billion as construction of
single-family homes fell 2.2 percent and multi-family construction
dropped 6.4 percent.
   Analysts said single-family construction will strengthen in
coming months because of recent mortgage-rate declines, but they
forecast further declines in apartment building because of
continued high vacancy rates.
   Non-residential construction fell 2.2 percent to a seasonally
adjusted annual rate of $90.9 billion, reflecting declines in
office construction, hotels, factories and shopping centers.
   Government construction spending was off 4.9 percent in January
to a rate of $74.3 billion. The weakness in the public sector was
led by a 3.9 percent fall in the largest government construction
area, highway building, which declined to $24.8 billion.
</TEXT>
