<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1653EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-US-Vietnam     03-01 0571</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Vietnam,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Specialists Say U.S. Missing Chances in Southeast Asia</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's preoccupation with the Vietnam War and
with the POW-MIA issue is hurting U.S. interests in Southeast Asia,
three American China specialists said Tuesday after returning from
two weeks in Vietnam.
   They described a Vietnam that is changing from a closed society
dependent on the Soviet Union to a country more open to the West.
   The specialists said that if the United States does not take
advantage of Vietnam's new openness, it could cede influence in the
region to the Soviet Union, China and Japan.
   ``The United States must reassert itself in Southeast Asia,''
said Helen Chauncey, a professor of history at Georgetown
University. ``If it doesn't we will be left behind in what will be
a realignment of political and economic forces.''
   ``We have to stop letting the past determine our actions in the
region,'' said Brantly Womack, professor of political science at
Northern Illinois University. ``Emotional topics like POW-MIA issue
are just red herrings.''
   Chauncey and Womack were joined by Frederic Wakeman Jr., a
professor of history from the University of California, Berkeley,
in their call for a more open policy toward Vietnam.
   Wakeman urged increasing educational and business contacts with
Vietnam.
   ``In the long run our stakes in Asia are enlarged by our
training of the technocracy,'' he said, noting that China now has
20,000 students studying in the United States.
   The three specialists along with a fourth ``China hand,''
Jonathan Pollack, of the Rand Corporation, spoke at a briefing
sponsored by The Henry Luce Foundation, which supported their trip
from Dec. 29 to Jan. 11.
   Seven American China specialists took part in the voyage, which
included stays in Hanoi and Ho Chi Minh City, once known as Saigon,
and talks with high-ranking Vietnamese officials.
   For the first time, Womack said, Vietnamese officials, including
Foreign Minister and Vice Premier Nguyen Co Thach, are talking
about Vietnam's foreign policy in a ``post-Cambodian future.''
   Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978, kicked out the
Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge and installed a puppet government in
Phnom Penh.
   A stalemate ensued in Indochina, with the Soviet Union and
Vietnam on one side and a resistance coalition, lead by Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, China, the United States and the free-market
countries of Southeast Asia on the other.
   Last year Sihanouk split with the coalition and began direct
negotiations with Hun Sen, prime minister of the Vietnamese-backed
government.
   Nguyen van Linh, Vietnamese Communist Party chief, is pushing
for economic change in Vietnam, where the average annual income
hovers around $125. He has recognized the need for foreign exchange
and investment from the West.
   Wakeman said South Korean officials told him that both they and
Japan want to invest in Vietnam because of its disciplined,
inexpensive labor force.
   Ever since the U.S. withdrawal from Vietnam, American policy in
Indochina has been ``reactive,'' following the lead of China or the
capitalist countries of Southeast Asia, such as Thailand or
Indonesia, Chauncey said.
   ``American officials who I've talked to express a deep-seated
bitterness against the Vietnamese,'' Chauncey said. ``It's like,
`They beat us so we'll let them stew in their own juice.'''
   Other American officials, Womack said, think too much of the
issue of American prisoners of war and soldiers missing in action.
   ``This issue is important to Americans at home,'' he said. ``But
it's hurting American interests abroad.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
