<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DigitalAudio     03-01 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Digital Audio,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Study Says DAT Anti-Copying System Is Flawed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH MESCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposed electronic encoding system designed
to prevent music from being copied by new digital audio tape
recorders is flawed, the government said Tuesday in a report that
boosted efforts to introduce the new machines in the United States.
   ``There is no reason at this point why manufacturers should not
be selling'' digital recorders in this country, said Gary Shapiro
of the Home Recording Rights Coalition.
   But recording industry officials promised to sue any
manufacturer that tries to sell the machines in the United States
before the copying issue is resolved, either legislatively or
through industry negotiations.
   Digital audio tape, or DAT, recorders can make copies of compact
disc recordings without discernible loss of quality. The recording
industry fears that such high-quality copying would cut into their
compact disc profits.
   DAT recorders costing about $2,000 were introduced last year in
Japan, West Germany and France. But manufacturers have held off
bringing them to the United States, where pending legislation in
Congress would require DAT recorders to contain an anti-taping chip
that would prevent home recordings.
   A spokesman for Sony Corp. of America, a DAT manufacturer, said
the study's results would not effect the company's decisions on
when to introduce the recorders in United States.
   ``We're not rushing to market,'' Sony spokesman Stephen Burke
said. He said Sony would have to evaluate the availability of
software and other factors before deciding when to sell the
recorders in this country.
   Congress asked the National Bureau of Standards to study an
encoding system proposed by CBS Records in which a narrow band in
the upper mid-range frequencies is removed from a recording. A DAT
recorder equipped with the anti-taping chip detects the ``notch''
and disables the machine's recording circuitry for a short period.
   The study found that the system is flawed because it doesn't
always work, the ``notch'' can sometimes be heard by listeners, and
the system can be bypassed ``for about $100 by a competent
electronics technician.''
   ``It's like selling you a camera that won't take certain
pictures,'' said John Lyons, director of the bureau's National
Engineering Laboratory, describing the encoding system.
   Lyons said the effect of the notch on the recordings ``is
subtle. Sometimes you can hear it and sometimes you can't.'' When
the notch is discerned, it is often recognized as a missing note,
he said.
   The bureau's testing team didn't study other anti-taping
methods, he said. He added that while ``there are any number of
ways'' of altering a recording to prevent copying, ``none of them
is going to be fool proof.''
   The Home Recording Rights Coalition said the results of the
study were a victory for the consumer and signals the end of the
legislation before Congress.
   The coalition has been fighting all anti-taping efforts as
infringment on the rights of consumers to make recordings at home,
for their private use, of records, tapes and compact discs.
   Jay Berman, president of the Recording Industry Association of
America, questioned aspects of the study but said it virtually
kills the CBS copy-code system ``as a viable political solution.''
   But he said the recording industry remains committed to finding
a solution through ``negotiation, legislation or litigation.''
   Berman said his is a $5 billion a year industry that is losing
$1.5 billion a year to home copying.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
