<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0678,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He Won't Get Down in Gutter to Respond to Attacks</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT new 4th graf with later Bush quote bgng ``I
support...; ADD 2 final grafs of Bush color bgng ``Later in...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT LAUDERDALE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said
Tuesday he wouldn't ``get into the gutter'' and respond to attacks
by his Republican presidential opponents.
   As the Super Tuesday collection of 20 primaries and caucuses
draws near, Bush toured the South and acted the part of
front-runner.
   ``I have tried to wage an honorable campaign and I'm not going
to get into this gutter answering every single attack,'' Bush told
supporters outside his Broward County campaign headquarters
downtown here. ``I want this nomination to be worth something after
I win it and, believe me, I'm going to win it.''
   ``I support the president. I have nothing to say about Dole's
charges, nothing at all,'' Bush said later when asked by reporters
to respond to Dole criticism that Bush has changed his version of
the Iran-Contra affair repeatedly.
   Bush began his day-long swing through south Florida, scheduled
to end in Tampa with a foreign-policy lecture to political science
students at Florida International University in Miami. He also
briefly addressed a rally at the state university.
   ``Things are going well but I am taking absolutely nothing for
granted. I am convinced that whoever wins Super Tuesday will be the
next president,'' Bush said at the campus, where one of the
introductory speakers was ``Miami Vice'' co-star Michael Talbott.
   Bush also was joined for his trip by former Arizona Sen. Barry
Goldwater, the 1964 Republican presidential nominee, and Florida
Gov. Bob Martinez.
   Sen. Bob Dole stepped up criticism of Bush in commercials and
speeches that say Bush has accomplished nothing of significance and
questioning Bush's role in the Iran-Contra affair.
   Bush told the students that he was in charge of two meetings in
which the 1983 Grenada invasion was planned and he said he had
helped form and head the South Florida Task Force on Drugs that
began seven years ago.
   He expressed pride in the Grenada invasion, saying: ``Kicking
Castro out of Grenada was a very good thing.''
   Bush said although there have been some slight improvements in
relations with Cuba and Fidel Castro's regime, he said there was no
reason to expect a change in policy toward Castro because he
continues to ``support and export revolution.''
   At the campus rally, Bush took note of placards denouncing the
new U.S.-Cuban immigration accord that calls for normalized
immigration of Cubans in return for the return of Mariel boatlift
Cubans. Many in Miami's large Cuban exile community, which numbers
more than 600,000, have said they strongly oppose sending any
Cubans back to Cuba.
   Bush pledged that Cubans would not be treated in the same way as
immigrants from other countries because they are fleeing oppression.
   Later in the afternoon, Bush drove a paving machine at the
construction site of a development called Mystic Pointe, which will
have 1,600 units for sale at an average $100,000 price.
   The project is adjacent to the prestigious Turnberry Isle
development, which was mentioned in the national news last year
when Miami model Donna Rice disclosed she took a chartered trip to
Bimini with Democratic candidate Gary Hart from the marina there in
a yacht called the ``Monkey Business.''
</TEXT>
