<1ST_LINE>u w AM-BeltMisuse Bjt   03-01 0668</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Belt Misuse, Bjt,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Misuse of Auto Seat Belts Said Cutting Their Effectiveness</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   While the increasingly widespread use of
automobile lap-shoulder belts is saving hundreds of lives, the
belts often are misused in ways that reduce their effectiveness, a
federal study concluded Tuesday.
   The National Transportation Safety Board said the most common
abuse of the car safety belts is that they are worn too loosely or
_ often in the case of children _ are tucked under the arm or back
because of concern about the high angle of the harness.
   ``The lap-shoulder belts are very effective and achieve about
all that can be expected of them if they are properly used,'' said
NTSB Chairman Jim Burnett. ``But we have a lot of misuse and that
problem has to be tackled.''
   The safety board report is based on previous studies of seat
belt use by other government agencies and the insurance industry as
well as a detailed examination of 167 accidents in which at least
one occupant wore a belt.
   Lynne Smith, one of the NTSB staff investigators involved in the
study, said the findings were not meant to be a random statistical
sample, but that the data is ``consistent with the finding of
widespread (belt) misuse.''
   An examination of the accidents showed that 21 percent of the
motorists were wearing belts too loosely, reducing their
protection, the safety board said. It also cited an insurance
industry study of Maryland motorists that put the estimate at about
25 percent.
   Ms. Smith said belts should be worn with no more than the width
of a person's fist separating the belt from the body.
   The safety board urged the National Highway Traffic Safety
Administration to require that safety belts meet standards as to
the maximum amount of slack allowed or require that the belt
systems be equipped with a ``pre-tension'' device that
automatically pulls a belt tight a split second before a crash.
   In addition, the examination of accident cases by the NTSB
showed that 7 percent of the belt users had the shoulder harness
portion of their belt routed improperly under an arm or behind
their backs.
   Misuse of the belts was most prevelent among children, where
one-third had belts not properly used. In some cases, children had
belts routed under an arm or behind the back, two children were
wearing a single belt or children wore belts with the seat in a
reclining position, the report said.
   ``Such misuse ... seriously degrades the protective capabilities
of the lap-shoulder belt, reducing it to a lap-only belt with
inferior crash protection,'' the safety board said.
   Ironically, a number of auto safety pamphlets, including two
distributed by the NHTSA and one by the American Automobile
Association, have advised parents to place the shoulder belt behind
a child if the harness crosses the neck or face.
   ``The safety board does not agree,'' the NTSB report said. ``...
There is little evidence that small children or short adults are
likely to be harmed by the shoulder portion of a ... belt.''
   It said that in the accidents investigated it found no evidence
``that the shoulder ... belt induced more serious injuries to
children than it prevented.''
   The board called for the highway safety agency to revise its
brochures.
   ``We have not had a chance to read (the NTSB report) and have no
comment at this time,'' NHTSA spokeswoman Betsy Tyson said.
   Among the accidents, according to the NTSB, in which belt misuse
had tragic results, were:
   _A head-on crash in which a woman passenger, who had loosened
her shoulder harness extensively, was killed. Her husband, the
driver, had worn his belt snugly and ``walked away from the crash
with moderate injuries,'' said Suzanne Stack, an NTSB staff
researcher.
   _A crash in which a car struck a tree. The driver, who had worn
his belt properly, escaped with minor injuries while the passenger,
whose shoulder belt was routed under her arm, was killed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
