<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0359</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Having an official flower and an
official bird just isn't enough when for a state that depends on
farming, so lawmakers dug up the idea of designating ``official
Iowa soil.''
   Proponents of a resolution declaring ``Tama soil'' as the
official soil of the state of Iowa gained ground Tuesday in the
Senate, winning Agriculture Committee approval of their measure.
   The lawmakers want to place Tama, a thick, black topsoil found
in at least 17 counties in east-central and eastern Iowa, alongside
the official wild rose, eastern goldfinch, oak tree and geode.
   ``Tama soil represents the richest of soils found in the
state,'' the Senate resolution states.
   Said Sen. Emil Husak, ``It's the best we've got.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>PEORIA, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A manners expert says a self-help video she
plans to produce will be just the thing for young executives hoping
to avoid ``power failures at power lunches.''
   ``It's going to show young businessmen and women how to eat
their way to the top with style and grace,'' Marjabelle Young
Stewart said Tuesday.
   Mrs. Stewart, who has written 15 books on etiquette, said there
was a growing need for well-groomed manners in the business world.
   Instructions on how to hold silverware would be similar to a
golf lesson, she said.
   ``I'll show them the proper grip and motion, everything,'' she
said.
   Mrs. Stewart said more and more executives were scrutinizing the
manners of prospective employees, taking applicants to lunch to
``see how they get along with the other members of the club.''
   The video, ``The Code of Etiquette,'' will retail for $89.98 and
is due for release in the spring, Mrs. Stewart said.
   It also may be useful for busy parents and could replace
traditional manners lessons dispensed daily around dinner tables,
she said.
   ``Young working parents don't have time anymore to serve big
meals every night and teach their children manners,'' she said.
``Today, we're eating at the stove; eating out of the refrigerator;
eating in front of the television.''
</TEXT>
