<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DeafPresident     03-01 0394</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaf President,380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deaf President Advocated for Nation's Only Liberal Arts College
for Deaf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA M. HAMM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Deaf President Now'' was the cry, made by
voice or by fluttering fingers, as about 1,500 people rallied at
Gallaudet University on Tuesday to urge selection of the first deaf
president in the school's 124-year history.
   ``Today we are marching and speaking for our civil rights,''
Allen Sussman, former dean of student affairs, said in sweeping
sign language to the cheering crowd of students, alumni, faculty
members and administrators.
   ``I think it's high time that we are in control of our own lives
and our own institution,'' Sussman, who is a professor of
counseling and psychology, told The Associated Press. Communicating
through an interpreter, Sussman, who is deaf, said, ``I think we
can do it much better and with more sensitivity than people who are
not deaf.
   Gallaudet, established by Congress in 1864, is the only liberal
arts college for the deaf in the United States.
   ``We need a deaf president now!'' student body president Greg
Hlibok signed enthusiastically, leading the crowd in a signed and
shouted chant of ``Now! Now! Now!''
   A presidential search committee gave the board of trustees a
list of three finalists on Monday to fill the post vacated by Jerry
C. Lee, who resigned Jan. 1 to go into private industry. Two of the
candidates are deaf and one can hear.
   The trustees were expected to name a new president this Sunday
after interviewing the finalists later this week, according to
Gallaudet officials. Four of the 19 board members are deaf.
   The deaf candidates are Harvey J. Corson, 44, superintendent of
the Louisiana School for the Deaf in Baton Rouge, and I. King
Jordan, 45, dean of Gallaudet's College of Arts and Sciences. The
third finalist is Elisabeth A. Zinser, vice chancellor at the
University of North Carolina at Greensboro, who can hear.
   Katherine Ingold, a member of the search committee, said deaf
applicants would not be given special preference.
   ``The committee's role is to find the best possible president
for Gallaudet University,'' she explained. ``But if there were two
equally qualified candidates, one deaf and one hearing, of course
the preference would be a deaf candidate.''
   Gallaudet has an enrollment of 2,200 university students, 400
high school students and 200 elementary school students.
</TEXT>
