<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-NATO-Congress 1stld-Writethru a0661 03-01 0713</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Congress, 1st ld-Writethru, a0661,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Carlucci Urges Lawmakers to Mute Criticism of NATO Allies</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Reagan-Nato Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Subs lede to fix time element. Adds 5 grafs at end to UPDATE
with Senate hearing</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's allies in NATO should spend more
money for defense, but congressional denunciations aren't the best
way to get that done, Defense Secretary Frank Carlucci said Tuesday.
   ``I quite agree with the thesis that our allies need to do
more,'' Carlucci told the House Budget Committee.
   But he added that ``I don't think it is very useful to simply
berate the Europeans on this.''
   Carlucci's comments came as President Reagan was heading for
Europe to attend a two-day summit meeting of leaders of the
16-nation North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   Rep. William Gray, D-Pa., the Budget Committee chairman,
criticized NATO nations for what he said was ``unequal sharing.''
He told Carlucci ``our allies in NATO are not doing, in my
estimation, enough for their own defense.''
   Criticism of NATO has long been popular on Capitol Hill, where
legislators have complained time and again that American taxpayers
are footing a disproportionate share of the alliance's defense bill.
   Gray said the United States is devoting about 6 percent of its
gross national product to defense while no other NATO countries
spend a little more than 3 percent.
   Carlucci agreed that ``we need to make every effort to get our
allies to do more,'' but he said they now do more than is
``generally recognized.'' For example, Carlucci said, NATO supplies
90 percent of the ground troops which would be used to halt a
Soviet attack.
   America's defense budget is 5.7 percent of the nation's GNP, not
6 percent, Carlucci said. He also noted that American defense
budgets have generally stayed even or declined in recent years.
   That wasn't good enough for Gray, who noted that the recent
reductions came atop large increases in Reagan's first term.
   NATO has long set a target for each member to increase spending
by 3 percent a year after inflation, and most nations don't meet
that target, Carluicci said. The United States hasn't met the 3
percent target for at least four years, he added.
   Both Carlucci and Adm. William Crowe Jr., chairman of the Joint
Chiefs of Staff, told the committee that NATO needs to improve its
conventional defenses in the wake of the treaty banning
medium-range atomic missiles from Europe.
   That is similar to the message Reagan is carrying to NATO allies
and echoes a theme which the administration has been pushing since
the treaty was signed Dec. 8 by Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail
Gorbachev.
   Crowe detailed NATO's shortcomings in non-nuclear weapons, but
added, ``surely the prospect of having to fight 16 nations at once
remains a sobering one for the Kremlin.''
   ``But, put candidly, both the level of (nuclear) deterrence and
the nuclear threshold remain too low,'' Crowe said. ``The chiefs
have for a number of years consistently testified to that effect.''
   ``It is essential for the NATO members to correct'' the problems
in non-nuclear weapons, he said.
   At the Senate Budget Committee, Yale historian Paul Kennedy said
that U.S. allies ``ought to bear a larger share of the defense
burden'' now that they have been rebuilt with U.S. help after World
War II.
   Kennedy, author of the best-selling ``The Rise and Fall of Great
Nations,'' said the United States should spurn protectionism and
increase spending for basic technologies and for commercial
research and development.
   Jeane Kirkpatrick, former U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
agreed with Kennedy that U.S. allies should bear more of the
burden. But she criticized his view that there is a direct
correlation between military spending and economic growth.
   Sen. Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., chairman of the panel, noted that
``the help we gave and the protection we've given have helped
Europe and Asia grow back into power. Now, they are friendly
competitors. But while they've taken us to the woodshed in
international trade, we're the ones paying for the guards at the
woodshed door.''
   ``It seems to me we are draining our power trying to do too
much,'' said Chiles. ``Our adversaries are happy to see us try. Our
allies haven't done as much as they can to help.''
</TEXT>
