<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Senegal     03-01 0534</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Senegal,0551</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Post-Election Violence Winds Down</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY JAMES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers enforced calm in Dakar Tuesday
following a day of rioting prompted by the announcement that the
president was winning national elections. The president defended
his decision to impose a state of emergency.
   Streets were littered with stones and children played with spent
tear gas cannisters on Tuesday, a day after soldiers and riot
police battled demonstrators. Crews removed the shells of
burned-out cars from the roads.
   Riot police and soldiers were visible in much of the city,
especially in the most densely populated neighborhoods. President
Abdou Diouf met with members of his Cabinet on Tuesday to assess
the situation.
   Opponents had charged that the vote that gave Diouf his second
5-year term was rigged. The president, in a communique read over
national radio, said the voting was fair.
   The communique said Diouf imposed a state of emergency to
``guarantee the legitimate aims of the people: peace, security, and
economic and social progress.''
   In an interview with French television, Diouf also defended the
decision to arrest the leading opposition presidential candidate,
Abdoulaye Wade of the Senegalese Democratic Party.
   ``I have the impression that our adversaries, as I had feared,
are very bad losers and they had used many children in a maneuver
to try to sow disorder and violence,'' Diouf said.
   He said his actions were necessary to ``protect democracy.''
   The preliminary tally showed Diouf with 688,476 votes to Wade's
299,998. Two other candidates got less than 10,000 votes. The
Supreme Court in this West African nation will announce the
official results Friday.
   Radio broadcasts announcing that Diouf was receiving about 77
percent of the vote sparked widespread demonstrations Monday in the
capital.
   The headquarters of Wade's party, which was scene of
considerable violence on Monday, was quiet. The government said
Wade and other opposition leaders were being questioned about the
riots.
   More than 260 people were believed to have been arrested during
the violence Monday.
   Dakar's Cheikh Anta Diop University also remained closed and
riot police stood guard at several of the entrances.
   A week before the election, Wade had said his party would become
a liberation movement if the voting was rigged. On election day
Sunday and again on Monday, Wade and other opposition leaders
accused Diouf's Socialist Party of providing its supporters with
cards to allow them to vote several times.
   Diouf was widely expected to win re-election. Opposition
supporters view his government as a continuation of the leadership
in Senegal since it achieved independence from France in 1960.
Diouf succeeded President Leopold Senghor when Senghor retired in
January 1981.
   In another development, Director of Communications Tidiane
Ndiongue apologized to a photographer who works for The Associated
Press and was arrested for seven hours during Monday's riots.
   The photographer, Axel Schulz-Ebbers of West Germany, said he
was picked up outside opposition party headquarters and beaten.
Ndiongue said the Ministry of Information had informed police that
accredited journalists were allowed to report on the disturbances.
   Diouf's government has been praised by the United States and
other Western nations for maintaining a multiparty system, a rarity
in Africa. Diouf also has been pro-Western in international forums.
</TEXT>
