<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1855EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WhaleSurvey     03-01 0395</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Whale Survey,0404</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Record Low Number Spotted In Right Whale Survey</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A record-low number of rare right whales was
spotted during an annual survey off the coasts of Georgia and
Florida, the New England Aquarium said Tuesday.
   An aquarium team that spent February surveying the right whale
population in their popular wintering grounds detected only one
mother-calf pair and five whales traveling separately.
   The total was three below the previous low of 10 in 1984, said
aquarium researcher Scott Kraus. The highest number spotted during
the five years the survey has been conducted off the Florida and
Georgia coasts was 26 in 1986, Kraus said.
   He said it was premature to speculate on reasons for the
apparent decline in the right whale population in the Georgia and
Florida waters, which are considered popular calving grounds.
   ``We don't know whether the numbers are low because of a local
problem that kept the whales away from that area,'' said Kraus.
``Or they may be somewhere down there and we are missing them.''
   Kraus said there were reports the water temperature had been
abnormally high this winter. But he said it was not clear if that
caused the whales to winter elsewhere.
   The aquarium will match the winter survey numbers with those
recorded next spring when the whales return to waters from Maine to
Nova Scotia. That should help determine whether the right whale
population has declined or if the whales chose a new location to
spend the winter, Kraus said.
   The surveys have been conducted in North Atlantic waters for
nine years and this was the fifth year of the survey off Florida
and Georgia.
   The four prior surveys there have found right whales prefer to
winter in waters five to 20 miles off the Georgia coast and within
two miles of the beaches of northeast Florida.
   Right whales are considered the rarest of the large whale
species. The worldwide right whale population is estimated at
2,500. It it is believed that 240 to 350 live in the North Atlantic.
   There are three types of right whales, which are known for their
unusually large heads. The type found in the North Atlantic are
Black Right Whales, which have black bodies and sometimes with
white areas on the belly. Black Right Whales grow up to 60 feet
long.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
