<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CommuterChaos     03-01 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commuter Chaos,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Day of Chicago Expressway Project a Dream, Not a Nightmare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Morning rush-hour was quiet Tuesday as a massive
rebuilding job began on one of the nation's busiest freeways, a
project that had state highway officials ready for the worst.
   The $210 million overhaul will widen the Dan Ryan Expressway
from eight to 10 lanes, and while work is under way _ for six-month
periods both this year and next year _ traffic will be squeezed
into half the normal number of lanes.
   On Tuesday several lanes were closed on each side of the freeway
for building crossovers and making surface repairs.
   Commuters and traffic experts have feared that the project could
create massive traffic jams because the highway is one of the
nation's busiest, carrying 225,000 cars daily, but things went
smoothly early Monday.
   ``The congestion was apparently zilch,'' said Ed Nash, a
spokesman for the Illinois Department of Transportation. ``The Ryan
was clear the whole morning and there was no buildup of traffic.''
   The state had conducted a months-long publicity campaign, urging
commuters to use alternate routes, car pool or take public
transportation. The Chicago Area Transportation Study distributed
37,000 ride-sharing applications and doubled its list of car-pool
applicants to 6,000.
   State officials say the overhaul of the three-mile stretch will
greatly improve the commute on the 11-mile freeway.
   The work will cost more than the $179.7 million it took to build
road 25 years ago.
</TEXT>
