<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LehderTrial     03-01 0429</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lehder Trial,0443</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Attacks Pilot's Credibitility</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense attorney attacked the
credibility of a pilot testifying Tuesday in the smuggling trial of
Carlos Lehder Rivas, winning an admission that the man continued
trafficking drugs while cooperating with the government.
   Leverett Francis, 66, testified Monday that he made six cocaine
flights in 1979. Those flights, made with admitted smuggler Ed
Ward, are those listed in the indictment of Lehder, 38, and
co-defendant Jack Carlton Reed.
   Lehder, reputed to be one of the leaders of Colombia's violent
Medellin Cartel of cocaine smugglers, is on trial on charges that
he and others conspired to smuggle 3.3 tons of cocaine into the
United States from Colombia via Norman's Cay in the Bahamas from
1978 to 1980.
   Under cross-examination Tuesday by defense attorney Jose Quinon,
Francis admitted he conducted other smuggling activity while we was
cooperating with the government and testifying before a grand jury
in 1980. Francis is testifying under immunity from prosecution.
   He said he made flights to Jamaica for other people in 1980,
bringing in either hashish or marijuana.
   Francis, a former Navy pilot, bristled when Quinon used the word
`lie' when discussing inconsistent statements in his testimony and
his grand jury appearances eight years ago.
   ``I don't like the word, `lie.' I looked it up in the dictionary
last night and I suggest you do the same,'' he told Quinon.
   Quinon laboriously questioned Francis about his grand jury
testimony in 1980 and many times Tuesday Francis said he couldn't
remember what he said in 1980.
   ``I'm sure the grand jury testimony as a whole is correct,''
Francis said.
   Lehder is charged with conspiracy, possession of cocaine with
intent to distribute, importation of cocaine and operating a
continuing criminal enterprise.
   Reed, of San Pedro, Calif., is charged only with being a part of
the smuggling conspiracy.
   Defense attorneys and prosecutors got into several exchanges
Tuesday out of the jury's presence.
   After one of a number of bench conferences with the judge,
defense attorney Ed Shohat accused U.S. Attorney Robert W. Merkle
of saying to him: ``You're going to sleaze yourself right into a
hole, mister.''
   Shohat called Merkle's remarks ``patently offensive.''
   Merkle, however, argued that he made the comment to Assistant
U.S. Attorney Ernst Mueller and said: ``They're (defense attorneys)
going to sleaze themselves into a hole.''
   U.S. District Judge Howell W. Melton said he didn't plan to take
any action and told the attorneys to present the exchange to a
grievance committee if they desired to do so.
</TEXT>
