<1ST_LINE>r w AM-CIAInspector     03-01 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CIA Inspector,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Webster Opposes Independent Watchdog At CIA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CIA Director William H. Webster spoke out
Tuesday against efforts to place an independent watchdog at his
agency like those already in place at 19 other federal departments.
   Webster said a proposal by Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., to place
an independent inspector general at the spy agency ``will actually
prove to be counterproductive to an effective inspection and
investigation process.''
   He told the Senate Intelligence Committee that the presence of
an investigator with access to personnel and secret records could
deter foreign intelligence services and other sensitive sources
from sharing information with CIA, fearing its possible disclosure.
   The proposal for an independent inspector general at the CIA
grew out of last summer's Iran-Contra investigation, which found
the agency's current inspector general ``lacked the manpower,
resources and tenacity'' to uncover many of the abuses turned up
during that probe.
   The current inspector general is chosen by the agency's director
and lacks the institutional independence of the IG post at most
other federal departments. The post is now held by William
Donnelly, a 33-year CIA veteran appointed by Webster.
   Specter, a member of the Intelligence Committee, said the panel
is unable to oversee the agency as thoroughly as an in-house
watchdog would be able to do. He noted that other departments with
sensitive intelligence operations, like the Pentagon and the State
Department, have independent investigators inside their
bureaucracies.
   Specter's bill would permit the CIA director to deny
investigators access to documents or personnel if needed to protect
sensitive secrets or an active covert operation. But the director
would have to defend such an action to the congressional
intelligence committees.
   Both June Gibbs Brown, the Pentagon's inspector general, and
Sherman M. Funk, inspector general at the State Department,
testified they have had no problems with disclosure of classified
information.
   Charles Bowsher, director of the General Accounting Office,
Congress' investigative arm, said a review of inspector general
operations government-wide had found they substantially strengthen
accountability and improve operations.
   ``We believe that a statutory IG would be as appropriate and
effective for the CIA as it has been for the other agencies,''
Bowsher said.
   And he said he was concerned that making a tour of duty in the
inspector general's office a part of routine career development for
CIA employees, as Webster proposed, would further rob the office of
independence.
   Specter said that while he did not doubt Webster's good
intentions, ``the problem is that you're not going to always be
director of the CIA. Our memories are fresh about a director of the
CIA who did not always forward information to this committee'' _ an
apparent reference to William J. Casey, Webster's predecessor.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0172 </DOCNO>
