<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gephardt     03-01 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gephardt,500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gephardt Picks Up Endorsement Of Two Former South Carolina Govs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Richard
Gephardt, described as ``middle America at its very best,''
received the endorsement Tuesday of two former governors of South
Carolina.
   Standing in the sun-bathed steps of the state Capitol, the
Missouri congressman told supporters the nation's future depended
on ``our ability to gain control of our economic destiny.''
   Former governors Robert McNair and Richard Riley defended the
candidate against charges that his trade program was protectionist.
   McNair said Gephardt ``has faced up to putting America first
with a fair, sound and sensible trade bill. One who believes if
we're going to open our markets up, you open your markets up.''
   McNair said the Gephardt bill was ``not a protectionist piece of
legislation, as some have tried to portray it, but it is what's
best for this country.''
   ``He's not a protectionist at all,'' said Riley. ``He's a
pragmatist.''
   Riley, who served as governor from 1977 to 1985, said of
Gephardt, ``He's middle America at its very best.''
   Gephardt said he supported legislation that would limit the
growth of textile imports to 1 percent a year.
   An estimated 45 percent of the jobs in South carolina are in the
textile industry.
   The import restriction legislation is an issue in the Republican
as well as Democratic race.
   Republicans Bob Dole and Pat Robertson, campaigning for support
in the South Carolina GOP primary this Saturday support the bill.
GOP rivals George Bush and Jack Kemp oppose it.
   ``For people here to have the kind of opportunity we all want,
we have to have a new trade policy,'' said Gephardt.
   ``This is a state that had a great textile industry, a great
fabric industry,'' he went on. ``That industry is in trouble, has
been in trouble in part because we have not had leadership and
policies at the federal level that will guarantee fair treatment
for the textile workers and the textile companies here in South
Carolina.''
   The Missouri congressman said that as president he would press
for policies that ``will give the textile workers of South Carolina
an equal right to sell their products in markets all over the
country and give them the right to not be impacted by unfair trade
practices by countries all over the world.''
   Gephardt's campaign manager Bill Carrick described Riley, who
was governor of South Carolina from 1977 to 1985, as a leader of
the progressive wing of the Democratic Party in the state.
   He said McNair, who was governor from 1965 to 1971, was a leader
of the ore conservative wing of the party.
   He said their dual backing was ``a nice little bookend
endorsement.''
   Earlier Tuesday, Gephardt visited former President Carter in
Plains, Ga. Carter made it clear that with fellow Georgian Sam Nunn
not in the race he had no plans to endorse any of the Democratic
presidential candidates before the nominating convention next July.
</TEXT>
