<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0328</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow, Rain and Hail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Heavy snow fell in California's Sierra Nevada, Shasta and
Siskiyou mountains Tuesday on a generally gray day in the West,
while thunderstorms dumped hail in Oklahoma.
   Snowfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST included 6
inches at Blue Canyon, Calif., and 1 inch at Austin, Nev. Crescent
City, Calif., received .87 inch of rain.
   A severe thunderstorm watch was posted Tuesday afternoon for
portions of southwestern Oklahoma and northwestern Texas.
   Showers and thunderstorms developed across south-central
Oklahoma and the Texas panhandle during the morning, and dime-sized
hail fell near Vanoss, Okla.
   Scattered snow was also reported in eastern and southern
Wyoming, east-central Nevada, southwestern Utah and western upper
Michigan.
   Rain reached from central California across west-central Nevada
and into parts of Oregon, Idaho and Utah.
   Temperatures at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 10 degrees at Massena,
N.Y., to 86 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The nation's cold spot
Tuesday morning was Pellston, Mich., with a low of 16 degrees below
zero.
   For Wednesday, the National Weather Service forecast calls for
rain in the lower Great Lakes, Michigan, the lower Ohio Valley and
southern Illinois. Showers and occasional thunderstorms will reach
from Missouri across northern Louisiana and northern Mississippi,
and northeast Texas across eastern Kansas.
   Snow in the higher Rockies will turn to rain at lower
elevations, and scattered rain is expected in the Pacific Northwest.
   High temperatures will be in the 20s in Minnesota, northern
Wisconsin, upper Michigan and northern Maine; in the 30s and 40s
from southern Maine across New Jersey, the remainder of the Great
Lakes, in Iowa and northern Missouri, the northern Plains, and from
Colorado to Montana; in the 70s from Georgia and Florida across the
lower Mississippi Valley; in the 80s on the lower Texas Gulf Coast;
and in the 50s and 60s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
