<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Gulf     03-01 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Says Iran-Iraq Missile Attacks Increase Need for Arms Embargo</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HENRY GOTTLIEB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Reagan administration on Tuesday called
attacks on Iranian and Iraqi cities a dangerous development in the
Persian Gulf war and adds ``a new urgency'' to United Nations work
on an arms embargo designed to force a truce.
   Phyllis Oakley, a State Department spokeswoman, condemned the
missile raids and said they represent ``a serious escalation of the
Iran-Iraq war.''
   ``Attacks on civilians achieve no military end,'' she said.
``They fuel the psychology of hatred which is responsible for
continuing this destructive conflict.''
   Iraq said Tuesday it fired 16 missiles into Tehran. It was the
first long-range rocket attack on the Iranian capital since the war
began in September 1980. Iran said 27 civilians were killed.
   The official Iraqi News Agency said Iran hit Baghdad with two
missiles late Tuesday night, killing or wounding an unspecified
number of civilians.
   Last July, the U.N. Security Council adopted resolution 598
calling for a truce in the war and pledging to impose an arms
embargo against either party that refused to heed the call. Iraq
has said it would accept a cease-fire but Iran has declined to go
along and the United States has been pressing the world body to
impose the weapons ban on Iran.
   ``We believe adoption of an arms embargo resolution to enforce
598 has taken a new urgency with the renewal of the war of the
cities,'' Mrs. Oakley said.
   ``We urge all members of the Security Council to act on this
now, without further delay, particularly permament members who have
special responsibilities to provide leadership,'' she said.
   She was referring to the Soviet Union, said another State
Department official, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   The United States offered a compromise last week in an effort to
satisfy U.S. demands for quick passage of a U.N. resolution against
Iran and meet a Soviet desire for more diplomacy by U.N. Secretary
General Javier Perez de Cuellar, the official said.
   It would permit immediate passage of an embargo followed by a
30-day delay in implementation and another peace effort by Perez de
Cuellar.
   The official said that in response to U.S. pressure to accept
the compromise, the Soviet envoy to the Security Council, Alexander
M. Belonogov has said he is awaiting a decision from Moscow.
   On March 1, the rotating chairmanship of the Security Council
will pass from the United States to Yugoslavia.
   Mrs. Oakley said an arms embargo ``will make it more difficult
for Iran to pursue the war,'' but will not mean an end to the
conflict if Iran desires to continue the fight.
   Negotiations between Iran and Iraq will also be necessary, she
said.
</TEXT>
