<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Holmes-Killings     03-01 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Holmes-Killings,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Re-Question Stricken Porn Star in Unsolved Slayings</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pornographic film star John Holmes was
questioned again by police in the unsolved 1981 bludgeoning murders
of four people as he lay gravely ill in a hospital bed, officials
said Wednesday.
   Holmes, who starred as Johnny Wadd in a series of sex films in
the 1970s and early 1980s, is suffering from AIDS, the Los Angeles
Times reported Tuesday, quoting anonymous sources.
   Holmes' attorney, Mitchell Egers, said Wednesday that his client
did not answer the questions.
   Egers confirmed that Holmes was hospitalized with a serious
illness but refused to say if he suffered from AIDS. Rumors that
Holmes was suffering from AIDS have been circulating in the
pornographic film industry for about a year.
   The incurable ailment usually is transmitted through sex, shared
hypodermic needles, tainted blood products and from pregnant women
to their babies.
   Holmes was acquitted in 1982 of the 1981 bludgeon murders of
four people in the exclusive hillside community of Laurel Canyon.
The crime remains unsolved.
   However, the Times said a new witness had surfaced and was in
custody out of state. That, combined with Holmes' illness, prompted
police to re-question him in his hospital bed, the newspaper said.
   Detective Tom Lange, supervisor of the murder investigation,
would say only that the case remained active.
   Holmes, 43, the premier male sex film star of the 1970s and
early 1980s, made hundreds of sexually explicit films and thousands
of peep shows.
   He was featured as the detective Johnny Wadd in films such as
``Tell Them Johnny Wadd Is Here,'' ``Liquid Lips'' and ``Blonde
Fire.''
   Holmes was cleared in 1982 of killing Ronald Launius, 37;
William DeVerell, 44; Barbara Richardson, 22; and Joy Miller, 46,
all of whom were beaten to death.
   Prosecutors said the four were part of a theft ring for which
Holmes acted as a middleman to Los Angeles nightclub owner Adel
Nasrallah, also known as Eddie Nash. Holmes allegedly fenced stolen
property for the group to Nash, who allegedly paid for the loot
with drugs.
   Nash was sentenced later to eight years in prison for possession
of two pounds of cocaine worth an estimated $1 million. He was
released after serving less than two years.
</TEXT>
