<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-PLO     03-01 0626</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-PLO,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Major U.S. Jewish Groups Distancing Selves From PLO Mission
Closure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major American Jewish groups said Tuesday
they have distanced themselves from the U.S. government's hotly
contested move to close the PLO observer mission to the United
Nations.
   ``They (U.S. officials) are not doing this at the request of the
American Jewish community,'' said Phil Baum, associate executive
director of the American Jewish Congress.
   Anti-terrorism legislation ordering the Palestine Liberation
Organization's mission closed by March 21 has put the United States
in an isolated position at the United Nations. An emergency General
Assembly session is under way on the mission's future.
   Scores of speakers, including close U.S. allies, called the move
a threat to the independence of the United Nations and asked the
United States to submit the dispute to binding arbitration.
   The State Department and the United Nations both say closing the
mission would violate the 1947 treaty under which the U.N.
headquarters is based in the United States. But Attorney General
Edwin Meese III reportedly is going to enforce the legislation.
   The State Department tried to head off the legislation, but
major Jewish groups supported it. They saw it as a way to get at
their main target, the PLO's Washington office, according to Baum,
Elan Steinberg, executive director of the World Jewish Congress,
and others.
   ``Our hope was to induce the State Department to use the powers
it had to close the Washington office,'' Baum said. ``We wanted it
to send a symbolic message that the PLO is a terrorist organization
and it was not welcome in the United States.''
   In a meeting last year with Deputy Secretary of State John
Whitehead, the groups offered not to press for closure of the U.N.
mission if the Washington office was shuttered, the Jewish leaders
said.
   In September, the department ordered the PLO office in the
capital closed.
   Baum said his group told Meese in a Feb. 12 letter it would not
press for the U.N. mission's closure. He said Meese has not replied.
   Baum said major Jewish groups sent a similar letter to Congress
on Dec. 3.
   ``We recognized that the headquarters agreement was a
complicating factor,'' he said.
   But by then the legislation had won the support of such
presidential aspirants as Sens. Bob Dole (R-Kan.), Jack Kemp
(R-N.Y.) and Paul Simon (D-Ill.)
   ``It took on the life of its own,'' Baum said.
   Several speakers in the General Assembly accused the United
States of sacrificing international commitments to the pressure of
domestic politics. They said closing the mission will further
damage U.S. prestige at the United Nations and cripple the U.S.
Middle East peace initiative.
   Arab League spokesman Clovis Maksoud on Tuesday laid much of the
blame for what he called a ``corrosive legislative tantrum'' on the
American Israel Public Affairs Committee, a powerful lobby.
   He said the Reagan administration ``fell into the trap. It
underestimated the hold of AIPAC on a majority of the Congress.''
   The Committee and the Zionist Organization of America were the
only Jewish groups who kept lobbying against the PLO U.N. mission
once the government closed the PLO Washington office, Baum and
others said in interviews.
   The 159-nation General Assembly is expected to approve a
resolution Wednesday calling for arbitration and saying closure of
the mission would violate the treaty. Another resolution asks the
World Court to rule on whether the United States must submit to
arbitration.
   The resolutions are sponsored by the Soviet Union, several
Soviet allies and by members of the movement of nations professing
non-alliance with either superpower.
   Israel was initially scheduled to address the General Assembly
Tuesday, but the address was later moved to Wednesday because of
the length of other speeches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
