<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Lebanon-Kidnap 3dLd-Writethru a0735 03-01 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon-Kidnap, 3d Ld-Writethru, a0735,0930</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Scandinavian Hostages Freed in Good Condition</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS that hostages freed in Sidon, not Beirut, new info,
Norwegian-Swedish comments and changes throughout. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA ABU-NASR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Moslem kidnappers freed two Scandinavian
relief workers Tuesday, nearly a month after they had been
kidnapped in southern Lebanon, and left a note saying the hostages
were ``proved innocent.''
   Swede Jan Stening, 44, and Norwegian William Jorgensen, 58,
employees of the U.N. Relief and Works Agency, were released in
Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut.
   Norwegian Charge d'Affaires Peter Raeder told The Associated
Press, ``I saw them. They looked a little bit pale but in fairly
good condition.''
   Reporters in Sidon said the U.N. workers were freed at 8 p.m.
and turned over to Salah Salah, a representative of the Palestine
Liberation Organization.
   They said Salah took the two to Sunni Moslem leader Mustafa
Saad, whose militia controls Sidon. Militiamen then drove the
former captives to Moslem west Beirut and delivered them to UNRWA
security chief John Carolan.
   UNRWA's acting director, John Fennessy, said the two were taken
to a hotel in Christian east Beirut to rest.
   He expressed ``the relief and satisfaction of my colleagues and
myself'' that the Scandinavians ``have at last been released and
are unharmed.''
   Stening and Jorgensen were abducted near Sidon on Feb. 5. Their
release reduced the number of foreign hostages held by extremists
in Lebanon to 23.
   Also on Tuesday, a statement purporting to be from the
kidnappers of Lt. Col. William R. Higgins said the U.S. Marine will
be put on ``trial'' for espionage when his captors finish
questioning him. There was no way of authenticating the statement.
   Members of a group called the Revolutionary Cells kidnapped the
Scandinavians. In a handwritten Arabic statement delivered to a
Western news agency in Beirut late Tuesday the group announced the
two men had been released. A photograph of the Scandinavians
accompanied the statement.
   It did not say what they had been accused of, but in earlier
statements the group claimed the men were involved with the
intelligence service of an unidentified foreign power.
   U.N. officials blamed the abductions on Palestinians acting
individually without a political motive.
   Government officials in Norway and Stockholm expressed gratitude
to those who had helped secure freedom for the two.
   The one-paragraph statement from the kidnappers said:
   ``After the two employees were proved innocent, they were
released. We ask UNRWA to reverse its decision to freeze its
activities, and we remind them that we will not allow suspicious
elements to use international agencies for cover.''
   The U.N. agency, which cares for an estimated 280,000
Palestinian refugees in Lebanon, suspended most of its medical,
social and educational services after the abductions.
   The statement on Higgins was delivered to a Western news agency
in Beirut without a picture of the U.S. Marine, who was abducted
Feb. 17 near Tyre.
   It was typewritten in Arabic and signed Organization of the
Oppressed on Earth, the name of the group that claimed
responsibility for abducting Higgins, 43.
   The statement said Israel's tough response to 12 weeks of
Palestinian riots in the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip, and the
Middle East peace shuttle of U.S. Secretary of State George P.
Shultz ``make us more determined to try this criminal, Higgins.''
   It repeated the claim that Higgins was a CIA agent.
   It was the third statement issued since the Marine from
Danville, Ky., was seized by gunmen who stopped his U.N. car on the
coastal highway.
   The Organization of the Oppressed on Earth is believed made up
of pro-Iranian Shiite Moslems. It has claimed responsibility for
kidnapping 12 Lebanese Jews in Moslem west Beirut since 1984 and
says it killed eight of them.
   Higgins is one of nine American hostages in Lebanon. Held
longest is Terry A. Anderson, chief Middle East correspondent of
The Associated Press, kidnapped March 16, 1985.
   The Marine colonel was the commander of 76 U.N. observers from
16 nations who monitor truce violations on the Lebanon-Israel
border under a 1949 armistice agreement.
   His observers are attached to the 5,800-member U.N. Interim
Force in Lebanon that was sent into southern Lebanon in 1978 as a
buffer between Israel and Palestinian guerrillas.
   The statement about Higgins said in part: ``The criminal Reagan
is moving inside and outside Lebanon to ensure a quick release of
Higgins so that he will not reveal secrets and make confessions.
But we declare today that we have uncovered solid facts about an
American-Israeli deal being hatched for south Lebanon.''
   In Washington, the State Department said it had no comment
except to repeat the U.S. position ``that all the hostages should
be released immediately and unconditionally.''
   In Stockholm, Foreign Minister Sten Andersson said of the
release of the UNRWA workers, ``I would like to express the
government's great gratitude to all who have helped achieve this
result.''
   Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland of Norway issued a
statement in Oslo saying: ``On behalf of the government and myself
I'm extremely relieved and happy with the release of William
Jorgensen of Norway and his Swedish collegue Jan Stening.''
   In Vienna, UNRWA spokesman Ron Wilkinson said Stening and
Jorgensen probably would travel to Vienna where the agency has its
headquarters.
   He also said the agency will ``still have to think about our
operations'' in Lebanon, adding: ``We have to have certain
guarantees of safety.''
</TEXT>
