<1ST_LINE>r i AM-PuertoRico-Search     03-01 0231</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Search,0236</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Toll in Alien Boat Accident Hits Eight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AGUADA, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight bodies have been recovered so
far since a small craft carrying about 45 illegal aliens from the
Dominican Republic capsized near Puerto Rico, authorities said
Tuesday.
   Authorities and a survivor say most of the 45 made it to shore
safely after the boat sank Sunday night near this small fishing
village, about 85 miles west of the capital city of San Juan.
   Police Lt. Jose Vega said two bodies were found Monday and six
more were pulled from the ocean near the beach Tuesday.
   Strong waves hampered the search, which was expected to resume
Wednesday.
   Police Maj. Cesar Gracia said the Dominican residents boarded
the craft on the east coast of Dominican Republic Saturday night,
when the weather was clear for the 90-mile trip across Mona
Passage. As they neared Puerto Rico, large waves overturned the
boat about 180 feet from shore.
   The boat was estimated to be 20 to 30 feet long.
   One survivor was hospitalized and another was taken into custody
Monday by the Immigration and Naturalization Service in this U.S.
Caribbean commonwealth.
   Aguada has been the landing site for many boats bringing illegal
aliens to Puerto Rico in search of a better life. Immigration
authorities estimate the number of illegal Dominicans living in
Puerto Rico to be between 40,000 and 160,000.

</TEXT>
