<1ST_LINE>r i AM-DominicanRepublic     03-01 0361</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dominican Republic,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Protesters Clash in Capital</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUDDY L. GONZALEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers with tear gas
fought protesters hurling stones in the poor, densely populated
Capotillo neighborhood of the capital Tuesday. Ten people were hurt
and about 50 were arrested.
   The disturbances began with a strike to protest increases in the
cost of living. Schools and stores in the neighborhood closed, but
traffic and activity were normal in the rest of Santo Domingo.
   Elsewhere in this Caribbean nation of 6 million, residents of
Azua and Barahona provinces south of the capital burned tires,
blocked roads and stoned businesses and cars.
   In similar protests last week, five people were killed and 20
injured in eight of the 26 provinces of the Dominican Republic,
which shares the island of Hispaniola with Haiti. The unrest is the
worst faced by President Joaquin Balaguer since he took office in
August 1986.
   The inflation rate is running at about 30 percent a year. The
foreign exchange value of the peso meanwhile has skidded. It takes
5.3 pesos to buy one U.S. dollar, about 72 percent more than the
3.85-1 ratio several months ago.
   Many people are furious that a 5-gallon container of cooking oil
has doubled to 84 pesos. Taxi drivers resent paying 3.6 pesos for a
gallon of gas that a few months ago cost 3 pesos.
   A one-pound steAP Business Writer=
   NEW YORK (AP) _ Aluminum maker KaiserTech Ltd. sued its chairman
for millions of dollars Tuesday, alleging he violated securities
law by improperly engaging in profitable short-term buying and
selling of company stock.
   The suit against Alan E. Clore came a day after the reclusive
British investor agreed to sell his 27 percent stake in KaiserTech
to Texas oilman Charles Hurwitz, a move that appeared to irritate
KaiserTech officials and signaled management turbulence at the
Oakland, Calif.-based company.
   Neither Clore nor Hurwitz are considered familiar with the
aluminum business. Clore acquired his position at KaiserTech after
a lengthy takeover struggle last year. Hurwitz's intentions toward
KaiserTech remain unclear.
   Asked if it was considered unusual that a company would sue its
own chairman, KaiserTech spokesman Robert W. Irelan said: ``It's
the first time we've done it.''
   In a statement, KaiserTech said its suit filed in a Manhattan
federal court resulted from Clore's disclosures in a Securities and
Exchange Commission filing Monday about his sale of stock to a
Hurwitz-controlled company, Los Angeles-based Maxxam Group Inc.
   KaiserTech contended the SEC disclosures showed Clore and his
affiliates made about $4 million in undisclosed profits via
so-called ``short-swing trading'' _ trading done within a six-month
period _ of KaiserTech stock.
   Under federal securities law, a company or its stockholders are
entitled to recover such profits from a director or officer who
engages in short-swing trading.
   Clore, who usually resides in Switzerland, could not be reached
for comment on the lawsuit, part of a rapid series of events
concerning the stock of the aluminum producer.
   In Los Angeles, the investment firm Jefferies & Co. said it was
selling 1.39 million shares of KaiserTech stock to Maxxam for
$16.68 million or $12 a share.
   Combined with the 6.2 million shares acquired from Clore, plus
an option to buy his 8.2 million convertible preferred KaiserTech
shares, the shares purchased from Jefferies would give Maxxam about
one-third of KaiserTech's approximately 45 million shares
outstanding.
   Wall Street's reaction reflected skepticism about a possible
takeover move. In composite New York Stock Exchange trading
Tuesday, KaiserTech fell 12{ cents a share to $11.75, after rising
$1.12{ in the previous session.
   KaiserTech said in a statement Monday it would have preferred
that Clore had sold his stock to a broader range of investors,
reflecting concern about what Maxxam intends to do with its stake.
Maxxam officials said it was premature to speculate on whether it
would attempt to acquire more.
   Clore's maneuvering to sell his KaiserTech shares came against a
background of heavy pressure on him to cut losses that stemmed from
the October stock market crash.
   If Clore hadn't found a buyer by a Monday deadline, he could
have faced default on loans he had obtained by using Kaiser stock
as collateral. After the stock plunged in October, lenders wanted
repayment.
   His sale of stock came as the company was rebounding from six
straight years of losses. Kaiser has sold its chemical, oil and gas
businesses, slashed debt and concentrated on its core aluminum
business.
</TEXT>
