<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Refuseniks     03-01 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Refuseniks,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>170 Families Cannot Leave Because They Allegedly Know State
Secrets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN-THOR DAHLBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities told a group of activists Tuesday that
170 Soviet Jewish families cannot be allowed to emigrate because
members have been exposed to state secrets, a member of the group
said.
   Vladimir Kislik, who has been trying to leave for 15 years, said
10 Jews from Moscow and Leningrad met with officials of the
Communist Party Central Committee and Justice Ministry.
   On Jan. 20 the group had given Vitaly Siderov, a Central
Committee official, a list of more than 300 families denied
permission to emigrate and requested a review.
   Siderov promised an answer within a month. The activists
returned Feb. 21, were told the review was not ready and were asked
to come back Tuesday, Kislik said in a telephone interview.
   They met with Siderov, Alexander Gorkovluk of the Central
Committee's propaganda department and officials of the Office of
Visas and Registrations and the Justice Ministry, he said.
   From the list of 300 families, Kislik reported, the officials
said 25 people had been authorized to emigrate. He said 20 had
received notification since the list was drawn up Jan. 1.
   About 80 other people were refused exit visas because parents or
spouses have not certified that they have no financial claims,
Kislik said. Soviet regulations require an applicant for emigration
to furnish such a guarantee.
   Kislik said some families were refused for emigration because
they do not have close enough relatives in Israel, which ``fully
contradicted'' what Secretary of State George P. Shultz said
Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze told him last month in
Moscow.
   Shultz told reporters Feb. 22, after meeting with Shevardnadze,
that the Soviet minister promised ``flexibility'' in applying rules
that require applicants to have close relatives abroad.
   He said Shevardnadze also told him ``categorically'' that the
only barrier to emigration is past work involving state secrets.
   Many people whom the government alleges were exposed to state
secrets say they saw the information years or decades ago and that
it does not compromise the Soviet Union.
   ``I last worked in atomic science 22 years ago and they are
refusing me because of that reason even today,'' Kislik said.
   He added that the officials indicated they would meet with the
Jews again to discuss the cases of 20 Soviet Jews who have heart
conditions, cancer or other ailments and who want to leave. ``We
also gave them a list of people from 60 to 82 years old who want to
emigrate,'' he said.
   In February, Soviet authorities allowed 723 Jews to emigrate,
according to the Geneva-based agency that helps the emigrants
resettle. That was a slight increase from the January total of 658.
   According to the Intergovernmental Committee for Migration,
Jewish emigration from the Soviet Union last year reached 8,011,
its highest level since 1981.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
