<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CampusTakeover     03-01 0449</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campus Takeover,0464</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Protesters Draw Up Tentative Agreement, See Takeover's End in
Sight</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Minority students drew up a contract
Tuesday to end the eight-day takeover of a Hampshire College
building that was held to protest racism at the private liberal
arts school.
   ``We all want it over,'' said Anita Fearman, a spokesman for the
40 black, Hispanic, Indian and other minority students who have
occupied a dormitory office since Feb. 23.
   A tentative agreement was hammered out late Monday in meetings
with the school's president, Adele Simmons, and two other
administrators.
   Students drew up the formal contract Tuesday and college
officials were expected to sign it Wednesday. Specifics of the
contract were not released Tuesday.
   Protesters said they expected to continue holding the Dakin
House office until Wednesday despite the apparent agreement.
   Among the demands Dean of Faculty Penina Glazer said the
administration agreed to was the hiring of a full-time adviser for
the campus group that occupied the building, Students of
Underrepresented Cultures.
   The school also agreed to allow a professor to serve part-time
as dean of multicultural affairs and to try to win grants to
increase the number of Third World books in the library, she said.
   The college was founded in 1965 as an alternative to the
traditional education offered at nearby Smith, Mount Holyoke and
Amherst colleges and University of Massachusetts. Students design
their own courses of study and advance through three divisional
examinations requiring them to complete individual research
projects.
   About 100 of Hampshire's 1,100 students are minorities.
   Two weeks earlier, an occupation sparked by campus racial
violence ended at at UMass when Chancellor Joseph Duffey agreed to
demands including increase funding of minority student programs.
   Meanwhile, in Springfield, the Massachusetts Commission Against
Discrimination has found probable cause in a complaint by Roland A.
Wiggins, 54, a black professor at Hampshire College, alleging he
was denied a 10-year teaching contract in 1986 because of race.
   The panel will attempt to resolve dispute or, failing that,
conduct public hearings, Hurst said.
   Wiggins, a music professor, said he had worked under short
contracts since he was hired in 1979 and in 1985 had won backing of
faculty, students and the college appointments committee for a
10-year appointment.
   The college cited complaints that Wiggins often was unavailable
to students, submitted evaluations late and had ``offered little
leadership in the music program, although he was the senior
member,'' according to Hurst's report.
   No blacks have been granted 10-year contracts, the longest the
college provides, Hurst said in his report. The school does not
offer tenure. Six of the 86 professors at the college are black, he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
