<1ST_LINE>r i AM-JesusPostmark 1stLd-Writethru a0659 03-01 0674</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jesus Postmark, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0659,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Mail to be Postmarked `Jesus is Alive!'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: 4 grafs SUB for 16th graf pvs, Post Office ... UPDATING with
humanist protest, U.S. outlook, edits to tighten. Picks up 17th
graf pvs, Slennet, 41 ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Post Office on Tuesday began postmarking
nearly all letters mailed in Britain with the words ``Jesus is
Alive!'' as part of a private arrangement financed by an evangelist.
   Jewish leaders criticized the Christian cancellation as
potentially offensive.
   The special postmark, which also contains a small cross, will
last six weeks and was paid for by Paul Slennet, who sells
religious literature at two bookstores in Southend-on-Sea, east of
London. He said God told him to buy the postmark.
   The state-owned Post Office said Slennet paid the equivalent of
$88,500 for the privilege of having every letter mailed through 68
of Britain's 69 sorting offices stamped ``Jesus is Alive!''
   The Post Office has adopted various methods of boosting revenue
under Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's Conservative government,
which believes that state-owned services should pay for themselves.
   Receiving the postmark will be all mail _ including that sent
abroad _ excluding parcels, periodicals and those letters stamped
by businesses that have their own franking facilities. Nearly 52
million letters are mailed daily in Britain.
   ``The printing of this slogan in no way confirms Post Office
approval of its contents,'' said Post Office spokesman Duncan
Marshall. ``The slogan is not considered to be contentious.''
   Shimon Cohen, spokesman for Lord Jakobovits, the chief rabbi of
Britain, said his office was ``flooded with phone calls'' after
news of the slogan appeared in newspapers Tuesday.
   ``We recognize that this is a Christian country and we have the
utmost respect for the primacy for the church,'' Cohen said in an
interview.
   However, ``we do fear that the slogan that will be carried is by
implication addressed to non-Christians and could well cause
offense and resentment. We've made our feelings known to the Post
Office,'' he said.
   Rabbi Charles Emmanuel, chairman of the Assembly of Rabbis of
the Reform Movement of Great Britain, said: ``This country allows
me freedom of religion, and an official organization should not
have accepted such a commission that will infringe not only upon my
rights but the rights of other non-Christians.'' Marshall said his
office was aware of ``a number of complaints.'' Asked if these had
caused any change of heart, he said: ``I've had no indication of
that.''
   He said no complaints had been received from other non-Christian
groups.
   However, the British Humanist Association, a national
association for the non-religious, said the decision showed
``insensitive disregard'' for other beliefs.
   ``Imagine the furor if we had asked to have `Jesus is Dead'
printed on hundreds of millions of letters,'' said association
spokesman Martin Horwood.
   He said he is writing the Post Office asking that the postmark
be withdrawn.
   In Washington, a U.S. Postal Service official said the chance of
something similar in the United States was unlikely. Dick Rustin,
manager of the Stamp Information Branch, said limits are strict on
special cancellations and religious messages are excluded.
   Britain's Post Office regulations require paid messages to be
``non-controversial, non-political and likely to be generally
acceptable to the public,'' Marshall said.
   Slennet, 41, said he got the idea five years ago listening to a
sermon in which the preacher talked about collecting stamps and
postmarks.
   ``The Lord has since confirmed to me in various ways that this
is the right thing to do,'' he said in an interview. ``In 1986 that
small quiet voice we hear when God speaks said `postmark'.''
   He said that he has informed Christian groups around the country
of his idea and received contributions toward paying for it.
   Slennet belongs to Intercessors for Britain, an evangelical
organization. He said the slogan was chosen in the spirit of Easter.
   The Plymouth Post Office isn't printing the slogan because it
already had been booked for one commemorating England's defeat of
the Spanish Armada in 1588.
</TEXT>
