<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SouthAfrica 1stLd-Writethru a0701 03-01 0777</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-South Africa, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0701,0792</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Moves To Bar Foreign Funds For Anti-Apartheid Groups</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 5th graf pvs, The new ... to include
right-wing groups probably not affected. Picks up 6th graf pvs,
Another section ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAURINDA KEYS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government Tuesday proposed a
bill to outlaw foreign funding of political activity, a move that
could cripple anti-apartheid groups and churches thus far spared
from the new crackdown on opposition.
   No court challenge of the restrictions would be allowed.
   Last week, the government banned 18 predominantly black
organizations from political activity, including the largest
anti-apartheid coalition and largest labor federation.
   Leading anti-apartheid clergymen vowed Tuesday _ before the new
bill was introduced _ that the churches would take over some of the
programs of the banned groups and more aggressively confront the
government.
   The new legislation, called ``The Promotion of Orderly Politics
Bill,'' would prohibit all organizations from receiving money from
abroad for political purposes and would empower the justice
minister to seize foreign funds received by certain groups. His
powers would be indefinitely retroactive.
   The foreign funds provision was not expected to hurt right-wing
organizations, which receive most of their money from donations
from within South Africa.
   However, another section of the bill could apply to right-wing
white supremacist groups that oppose the government's limited
apartheid reforms. It sets a penalty of two years in jail or a fine
of about $2,000 for anyone who ``says or does anything'' to foment
hostility or violence between different racial, cultural or
religious groups. The penalties would apply to anyone who displays
a banner, emblem or slogan deemed to convey such hostility, and
also to anyone who attends a gathering where such items are
displayed.
   The South African Council of Churches, which includes most major
Protestant denominations and is engaged in civil rights work, has
received more than 90 percent of its funds from abroad in recent
years.
   The Roman Catholic Church cooperates with the council of
churches but receives substantial overseas funds separately.
   The Rev. Smangiliso Mkhatshwa, secretary-general of the Southern
African Catholic Bishops Conference, said the bill might be
difficult to enforce.
   ``If the church says supporting the families of detainees and
paying legal fees is the work of love, the work of evangelism, it
is difficult to see how the government can define for the church
what is pastoral and what is political,'' he said.
   In Parliament, Helen Suzman, veteran member of the
anti-apartheid Progressive Federal Party, condemned the arrests
Monday of prominent clergymen who were protesting the government
crackdown.
   About 25 church leaders, including Anglican Archbishop Desmond
Tutu, and 125 other protesters were detained briefly after riot
policeman blocked them from marching to Parliament with a petition
protesting the bans on opposition groups. After the most prominent
clergymen were placed in police vehicles, a water cannon was
sprayed on the other protesters, who were kneeling and singing
hymns.
   Mrs. Suzman said Tuesday police should have allowed the march to
proceed, ``thus avoiding all that sensational publicity that has
resulted in adverse headlines across the world and has added
further fuel to the campaign for sanctions. This government has a
death wish.''
   Law and Order Minister Adriaan Vlok said the clergymen had
defied a request to disperse and ``scandalously provoked'' police.
``We have to once again take the blame for the misconduct of people
who hide behind the cloth of sanctimony,'' he said.
   One of the arrested churchmen, Roman Catholic Archibishop
Stephen Naidoo of Cape Town, said in an interview Tuesday that he
and his colleagues considered it their duty to intensify the
churches' challenge of the government.
   ``There is going to be in this country a continuing moral
confrontation,'' he said.
   He predicted the authorities would deal cautiously with defiant
clergymen because ``they are intelligent enough to realize they are
dealing here with a great moral force ... and the moral
sensibilities of people all over the world.''
   The government has backed off before in the face of concerted
church resistance, the last time in 1986 when many of the same
ministers arrested Monday had gathered at Cape Town's St. George's
Anglican Cathderal to defy a ban on calling for the release of
detainees. The prohibition was not enforced and was dropped from
the next issue of emergency regulations.
   The Rev. Edward King, dean of St. George's, said it was
significant that no one in Monday's march had been charged and all
were freed without bail. ``I think they're embarrassed by this;
they don't want to put archbishops in jail. But they make their own
nooses for their own necks.''
</TEXT>
