<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NorthernIreland     03-01 0251</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Northern Ireland,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Say Dead IRA Bomber Was Their Most Wanted Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of two IRA men accidentally
killed by their own bomb has been linked to at least 25 killings
since 1979 and headed the police most-wanted list, the British news
agency Press Association said Tuesday.
   The agency quoted security sources it did not identify as saying
Brendan Burns, 33, was believed to have directed IRA bombing
campaigns along the British province's border with the Irish
Republic.
   Burns and Brendan Morley, 30, were killed Monday by the
detonation of explosives they apparently were installing in a van
about two miles outside Crossmaglen in south Armagh.
   The Irish Republican Army, which is fighting to oust Britain
from Northern Ireland and unite it with the Irish Republic, said
the men belonged to the organization.
   Press Association said Burns was involved in an IRA ambush that
cost the lives of 18 British soldiers in Warrenpoint, County Down,
in August 1969, when sectarian violence began in the
Protestant-dominated province.
   Burns also was sought in connection with a land mine explosion
that killed five soldiers at Camlough, County Armagh, in 1981, the
agency said.
   It said he was linked with the killings of Lord Justice Sir
Maurice Gibson, the province's second-highest judge, and his wife.
A land mine destroyed their car as they drove into Northern Ireland
from across the border last summer.
   Northern Ireland's police force, the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
refused comment on the report Tuesday night.
</TEXT>
