<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Kuwait-Egypt     03-01 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Kuwait-Egypt,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nasser's Son Accuses US and Israel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The son of late President Gamal Abdel Nasser of
Egypt was quoted Tuesday as saying the United States and Israel are
defaming him and his brothers to ``settle old accounts'' with his
father.
   The Kuwaiti newspaper Al-Anbaa said the interview conducted in
Belgrade, Yugoslavia, was the first with Khaled Abdel Nasser since
criminal charges were filed against him in Cairo. It quoted him as
saying he would return to Egypt for trial even though he faced
possible execution.
   Khaled Nasser is among 20 men charged in connection with four
shooting attacks on U.S. and Israeli diplomats and embassy workers
between 1984 and 1987. Two Israelis were killed and six Israelis
and two Americans were wounded.
   He and the other defendants are accused of membership in a
clandestine group called Egypt's Revolution. The indictment demands
the death penalty for Nasser, 38, and 10 other defendants, and
prison terms of up to life for the others.
   Egypt has said it is trying to extradite Khaled Nasser for trial
as one of three founders of Egypt's Revolution and its main
financial backer. The group is committed to ending the Israeli
presence in Egypt and Egyptian commitment to the 1979 peace treaty
with the Jewish state.
   Al-Anbaa said Algeria had offered political refugee status to
Nasser but he refused, saying: ``My father never imagined being
such in any country and preferred to die while fighting his enemies
rather than accept that. Therefore I am determined to return to
Cairo because death in Cairo is much better than living elsewhere.''
   Gamal Abdel Nasser led a bloodless military coup that ousted
King Farouk in 1952, and ruled as a fierce nationalist until his
death in 1970.
   While he was in office, Egypt faced the 1956 invasion by
Britain, France and Israel and Israel captured the Sinai Peninsula
and Gaza Strip in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Nasser's successor, the late Anwar Sadat, led the country
through the 1973 war with Israel and signed the peace treaty with
Israel in 1979.
   In referring to ``a defamation campaign'' in the Egyptian press
against him and his two younger brothers, according to Al-Anbaa,
Nasser said it was ``not separate from the hostile American and
Israeli blueprint which has been employed over the past 36 years
with the aim of obliterating Nasser's legendary place in the hearts
of the Arab masses.''
   ``The defamation campaign being launched against me and my
brothers is but an American and Israeli attempt to settle old
accounts,'' he said.
   ``Those who failed to face President Nasser for 18 years of his
rule and to eradicate his name from the conscience of the Egyptian
masses for 18 years after his death now return to launch their
campaigns.''
</TEXT>
