<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ExitPolls 1stLd-Writethru a0802 03-01 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Exit Polls, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0802,0541</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Rules Networks Can Conduct Exit Polls In Georgia On Super
Tuesday</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `A more...', with 2 grafs to restore dropped
word `feet,' add quote from networks' attorney. Picks up 8th graf
pvs, `Frances Duncan...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN S. CARLSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Tuesday gave the three major
television networks the go-ahead to take exit polls at Georgia
voting places during the Super Tuesday presidential preference
primaries next week.
   CBS, NBC and ABC had sued state and Fulton County election
officials to stop enforcement of a 1985 law prohibiting exit polls
or public opinion surveys within 250 feet of a polling place.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Hall Tuesday issued a preliminary
injunction stopping the state from enforcing the new law beyond 25
feet of buildings in which polling places are located.
   The ruling, which came after a hearing on the lawsuit Monday,
allows the networks to conduct the exit polls during the March 8
primaries, as long as their poll takers are stationed no closer
than 25 feet from the door.
   Hall indicated he would rule later on the networks' contention
that the law violates the Constitution's First Amendment guarantee
of freedom of speech and of the press.
   While the state ``has a legitimate interest in protecting the
`sanctity of the polling place,''' Hall wrote in Tueday's ruling,
it appears the 250 foot prohibition on exit polls ``is not
`narrowly tailored' to accomplish that goal in the `least
restrictive means available,''' as required by previous court
rulings on free speech issues.
   A more limited ban, keeping exit pollers out of polling places
and 25 feet away from their doors, ``would likely satisfy even the
most rigorous constitutional scrutiny,'' he wrote.
   ``We're delighted by the results,'' said Floyd Abrams, an
attorney representing the networks. ``It will make it possible for
more people to have more information more quickly about the
election results and their meaning on Super Tuesday.''
   Frances Duncan, the assistant secretary of state in charge of
elections, said Tuesday that copies of the judge's order will be
sent to county election officials for relay to their precinct
managers before the primaries next week.
   In exit polling, survey takers ask a random sample of voters
leaving the polling place to fill out a written list of questions
about whom they voted for and what issues are important to them, as
well as such information as their age, sex and economic status.
   During testimony in Monday's hearing, Warren Mitofsky, director
of CBS News' election and survey unit, testified that exit polls
are by far the most accurate and the quickest way to gauge what
groups of people are voting for which candidate.
   But, he said, the 250-foot distance limitation effectively
banned public opinion surveys of people leaving polling places
because the surveyor is too far away from the exit to be able to
intercept the voters randomly.
   The law had been enacted because elections officials, mostly in
metropolitan Atlanta, had complained that exit poll takers
intimidated voters, according to testimony from former state Rep.
Claude Bray, who chaired the House State Governmental Affairs
Committee when it considered the measure.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
