<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 2056EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson 2ndLd-Writethru a0837 03-01 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0837,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Meets With South African Ambassador</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS penultimate graf to CORRECT to S.C., sted N.C.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson met with the South African
ambassador Tuesday and said he conveyed the ``outrage felt by
freedom-loving peoples everywhere'' at the recent clampdown of
anti-apartheid factions in that country.
   The Democratic presidential candidate said he objected to
Pretoria's restriction of the activities of anti-apartheid
organizations and Monday's arrest of Anglican Archbishop Desmond
Tutu and other top religious leaders.
   Jackson told a news conference later that the ambassador, Piet
G.J. Koornhof, asked for a follow-up meeting with Rep. Ronald
Dellums, D-Calif., who attended the meeting and who is sponsoring
legislation on sanctions against South Africa because of its
apartheid policy of racial separation.
   The Democrat also called on the Reagan administration to take
several steps against the Pretoria regime.
   He said he informed the South African ambassador of his
proposals, which include:
   _ ``Comprehensive international economic and financial sanctions
on apartheid.'' Jackson said U.S. corporations and banks should be
ordered to leave South Africa.
   _ Invocation by the administration of a special session of the
U.N. Security Council to seek international support for such
sanctions.
   _ Broadcasting of news from South Africa via ``a new Radio Free
South Africa.''
   _ Support for the so-called frontline states around South Africa
and aid to build rail corridor railways so that Zimbabwe and Zambia
would not be dependent on South African trade routes.
   Jackson said he attempted to telephone President Reagan on the
eve of Reagan's Tuesday departure for a North Atlantic Treaty
Organization meeting in Brussels. Jackson said he spoke with
national security adviser Colin Powell and urged that Reagan seek
support from the NATO allies for Jackson's South Africa proposals.
   Jackson's press secretary, Elizabeth Coulton, said Powell agreed
the South Africa situation would be raised at the NATO meeting.
   Campaigning earlier in Maryland, one of the Super Tuesday states
that holds its primary next week, Jackson spoke to a downtown
Baltimore rally and blasted Reagan for using ``government power to
take from the poor and give to the rich.''
   Of his recent second-place finish in the Maine caucuses, Jackson
told the crowd of a few hundred, ``There are signs we are growing
every day.''
   He also walked through Baltimore's trendy Lexington Market food
bazaar shaking hands with the lunchtime crowds. He stood on a large
plant pot and shouted over the din, urging the crowd to vote for
him.
   Later, Jackson flew to his hometown of Greenville, S.C., and
proclaimed to a church full of people, ``It's good to be home.''
   ``I'm a son of the South...I know the South and its ways,'' he
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
