<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BBC-Secrecy     03-01 0303</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BBC-Secrecy,0312</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BBC Says Government Drops Objections to Program on Security</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said Tuesday the
government has withdrawn its objections to a radio program that
included interviews with intelligence officials.
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's government won a court order
in December preventing the broadcasting of the first program in the
planned three-part series, ``My Country: Right or Wrong.''
   The government argued that the series, dealing with the tug of
war between state secrecy and freedom of information, could harm
national security.
   Publicly funded BBC said the series portrays the work of
Britain's intelligence agencies and did not reveal anything an
enemy could not already know.
   The government withdrew its objections to the program after its
lawyers received a transcript of it from the BBC, the company said.
   The second and third programs have yet to be recorded.
   ``I am glad that we will be able to transmit this program,''
said John Birt, BBC's deputy director general. ``I am only sorry it
has been long delayed.''
   He did not say when the program will be broadcast.
   The High Court judge who approved the gag order had said the
government was properly concerned that nine former and serving
intelligence officials interviewed for the series may have broken
their oaths of secrecy.
   BBC spokeswoman Helen Cleary said Tuesday night: ``The BBC
initially refused to turn over the transcripts to the government,
arguing that would amount to pre-censorship. But the BBC later,
during the legal process, had to provide the transcripts as part of
its defense evidence.''
   Mrs. Thatcher's Conservative government had used the argument of
lifetime confidentiality by security agents to prevent the
publication in Britain of ``Spycatcher,'' a book by former agent
Peter Wright, who now lives in Australia. The book has been
published in the United States.
</TEXT>
