<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Meese-Stock 3rdLd-Writethru a0781 03-01 0979</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meese-Stock, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0781,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senator Questions Handling of Attorney General's Stock Profits</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 21st graf bgng: A telephone ... with 2 grafs to UPDATE
with comment from Chinn's attorney. Picks up 22nd graf pvs bgng:
Chinn was ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III's investment
manager allocated stock-trading profits to Meese's brokerage
accounts under a procedure that a senator said Tuesday raises
questions of ``possible financial favors or gifts'' to the Cabinet
member.
   In a report by its Democratic majority staff, the Senate
Subcommittee on Oversight of Government Management said stock
trader W. Franklyn Chinn pooled Meese's money with that of several
other customers in 1985 and 1986 and, after completing stock
trades, assigned profits or losses to the attorney general's
account.
   The report said it appears that in seven instances, Chinn
allocated stock trades to Meese's account in amounts exceeding the
balance available in the account to pay for those trades.
   In the seven instances, the amount of the stock trades exceeded
the balances in Meese's account by $5,000 to $140,000.
   Chinn turned a profit of nearly $40,000 for Meese on a $50,000
investment in just 23 stock trades over a 19-month span.
   E. Robert Wallach, Meese's longtime friend who is under
indictment in the Wedtech Corp. scandal, in five of the trades was
one of the customers whose money was pooled with that of the
attorney general. Wallach introduced Meese to Chinn, who became the
attorney general's financial adviser in May 1985.
   Chinn ``wasn't investing Mr. Meese's money, as much as he was
assigning profits and losses to the accounts of Mr. Meese and his
other clients at his own discretion,'' Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich.,
the subcommittee's chairman, said in a letter to the Office of
Government Ethics.
   Chinn's ``assignment of stock transactions retroactively to
those accounts appears to have no relationship to the amount of
money in those accounts,'' Levin continued.
   ``Because he did not allocate winners and losers to his clients'
accounts until after the fact, he was effectively able to assign
greater benefits to some _ including apparently Mr. Meese on
numerous occasions.''
   The procedure ``raises questions about possible financial favors
or gifts, about possible conflict of interest, (and) about the
judgment of the attorney general in being involved in a partnership
with a director of a company (Wedtech Corp.) with Mr. Meese had
directly assisted when he was working in the White House as
counselor to the president,'' said Levin.
   Levin asked the ethics office for a formal finding as to whether
Meese has complied with federal regulations governing gifts and
loans to public officials and whether he has violated an executive
order prohibiting the appearance of a conflict of interest.
   Justice Department spokesman Patrick Korten said the issues
raised by Levin were matters that had been fully examined in
congressional hearings last July and that now are before the
independent counsel studying Meese's dealings with Wedtech. He said
it would be inappropriate for the ethics office to get involved at
this point.
   ``What Senator Levin is trying to do is wrap an 8-month old fish
in today's paper,'' Korten said. ``All we have here is a highly
partisan effort to grab another headline on this thing and keep the
Meese pot boiling.''
   Meese has acknowledged interceding on behalf of Wedtech when the
Bronx, N.Y., defense contractor was seeking a $32 million, no-bid
contract to build small engines for the Army. Within months of
Meese's intercession, Wedtech was awarded the work.
   The report said that in one instance, Chinn bought and sold
5,000 shares of a new stock issue in Oliver Stores Inc. worth
$30,000 on Feb. 11, 1986.
   It wasn't until the next day, however, that Chinn instructed
Imperial Trust Co. where one of Meese's accounts was established,
that 2,000 of the shares were to be recorded for Meese's account.
The transaction gave Meese a profit of more than $1,700.
   In another instance, on Sept. 12, 1985, Chinn allocated a
purchase of $80,000 worth of stock in Rockefeller Center Properties
to Meese's account at the brokerage house of Bear, Stearns at a
time when the account had a balance of only $51,000. The trade
resulted in a profit of nearly $900.
   In a third instance, Chinn bought and sold Firemans Fund Corp.
stock on Oct. 23, 1985. It wasn't until mid-afternoon of the day he
bought and sold it that Chinn directed that 2,000 of the shares be
assigned to Meese's account. That transaction earned Meese more
than $900.
   Levin said Chinn assigned purchases to Meese's and his other
customers' accounts ``after it was known whether the purchase would
yield a profit or loss.
   ``It appears that Mr. Chinn was able to decide just which of his
clients would get profits and which would get losses,'' the senator
said in his letter to the ethics office.
   One of Chinn's lawyers, Cristina Arguedas, said that her
client's stock trading has been examined at length by independent
counsel James McKay, who is conducting a criminal investigation of
Meese. She said the independent counsel has found no wrongdoing in
connection with the stock trading.
   One of Meese's attorneys, Nathan Lewin, said the attorney
general had set up a limited blind partnership with Chinn's company
under which Meese was kept unaware of any of the details of Chinn's
stock trading. Lewin noted that Meese lost money on five of the 23
stock transactions.
   Chinn was indicted Dec. 22 with longtime Meese friend E. Robert
Wallach and a business associate, R. Kent London, on racketeering,
fraud and conspiracy charges in an alleged scheme to extract
payments from Wedtech in order to influence Meese and other federal
officials. All three have pleaded innocent.
   Meese's involvement with Wedtech has been under criminal
investigation by independent counsel James McKay since last May 11.
The attorney general has denied wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
