<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CitrusQuarantine     03-01 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citrus Quarantine,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Lifts Texas Ban of Florida Citrus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY FIKAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge on Tuesday overturned the
Texas ban on Florida citrus fruit, and state officials began
planning their next legal move against regulations allowing the
shipments.
   The ban was imposed last month ban after the U.S. Department of
Agriculture lifted a 3{-year-old federal quarantine on Florida
citrus that was prompted by outbreaks of citrus canker in Florida.
   Texas agriculture officials said the ban was necessary to
protect Texas' $65 million-a-year citrus industry from canker.
   The state now plans to seek an injunction against new federal
rules that allow shipment of Florida citrus meeting certain
standards to other citrus-producing states, said Max Woodfin,
spokesman for the Texas Department of Agriculture.
   U.S. District Judge James Nowlin said Tuesday that he lifted the
state ban, imposed last month after the new federal rule took
effect, because the federal regulation took precedence over the
state rule.
   The ban was due to end March 12, when Texas officials planned to
have gathered information on the federal rule and take some
permanent action.
   ``We feel we need to do whatever we can to protect the Texas
citrus industry,'' Woodfin said.
   The injunction request will charge that the federal rule was
issued abruptly and did not allow sufficient time to study its
possible effects, he said.
   Florida Citrus Mutual, a growers association, and Tuxedo Fruit
Co., a Florida shipper and grower, sued Texas last month to stop
the emergency state quarantine.
   Florida Gov. Bob Martinez and Agriculture Commissioner Doyle
Conner joined the court action.
   The lawsuit called the ban unconstitutional and invalid. It said
the action would mean a loss of millions of dollars to the Florida
citrus industry.
   ``We expected this decision,'' Conner said. ``Federal rules and
regulations supersede state rules and regulations as it pertains to
plant matters. The law's a little different between plant and
animal.''
   Canker, which can seriously damage citrus plants and fruit, was
found in Florida in 1984. Florida officials said Florida producers
must meet strict standards under the new federal regulation in
order to ship fruit to citrus-producing states, including Texas.
   Robert Griffith, chief of the bureau of pest eradication for the
Florida Department of Agriculture and Consumer Service, said he had
never heard of canker being found on mature citrus fruit that was
ready to be shipped.
   It would be difficult to transmit canker from fruit to citrus
groves, he said.
</TEXT>
