<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Austria-Government     03-01 0451</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Austria-Government,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chancellor Raises Possibility Of New Elections Over Tax Reform</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The coalition government of Socialists
and conservatives, already under strain because of the Kurt
Waldheim affair, could collapse over tax reform, according to
comments by Chancellor Franz Vranitzky on Tuesday.
   The coalition has been strained for months over President
Waldheim's World War II activities, and Vranitzky said again
Tuesday he would consider resigning if that issue continued to
affect his government's work.
   But Socialist Vranitzky, speaking with reporters after a Cabinet
session, dealt mainly with tax legislation.
   He said it was possible he would meet again this week with Vice
Chancellor Alois Mock in a last-ditch effort to reach agreement on
tax reform.
   Mock is chairman of the conservative Austrian People's Party.
Waldheim, running as the conservative candidate, won the
presidential election in June 1986. The term for the mainly titular
presidency is for six years, and Waldheim has rejected critics'
demands that he resign.
   Vranitzky said the question of new elections ``would lie close
at hand'' if the tax dispute is not resolved.
   The last parliamentary elections were held on Nov. 23, 1986, for
four-year terms.
   Vranitzky was asked about early elections and he said, ``I do
not seek them but I do not shy away from them either.''
   Mock and Vranitzky have had several inconclusive meetings on the
proposed tax reform.
   The Socialists insist that a major gap in the budget cannot be
filled without imposing a tax on savings deposit interest. The
conservatives strongly oppose such a tax.
   Some political observers have said the combined tax dispute and
controversy over Waldheim may be too much for the coalition to
survive.
   Vranitzky, criticizing Waldheim, said it was not enough for the
president to keep restating his position.
   He said Waldheim would have to contribute to resolving the
crisis over his presidency ``in word and deed,'' but added he did
not want to elaborate.
   Waldheim served as a lieutenant in the German army in the
Balkans during World War II. The World Jewish Congress and other
groups say he was involved with army units that deported thousands
of Jews and other people from the area to Nazi labor or death camps.
   An international commission of six historians, appointed by the
Austrian government to investigate Waldheim's past, said he was
``in close proximity'' to some Nazi atrocities in the Balkans and
knew they were going on but made no attempt to prevent them.
   The report, released last month, did not support allegations
that Waldheim was involved in atrocities. But it left open the
question of whether he was guilty of any crime.
   Waldheim, a former U.N. secretary-general, has repeatedly denied
any wrongdoings during the war.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
