<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--SchoolMotto 1stLd-Writethru a0624 03-01 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--School Motto, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0624,0217</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Council Wants Nuclear-Free Slogan For Old School</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES thruout with council offering compromise. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHESTERFIELD, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Derbyshire County Council
suggested a compromise Tuesday in its campaign to have 16th century
Chesterfield School replace a Latin motto on its stationery with an
anti-nuclear slogan.
   The left-dominated council, which runs the boys' preparatory
school in north-central England, had told the school to stop using
stationery bearing a coat of arms and the motto ``Non quo sed
quomodo'' _ ``Not whither but in what manner.''
   The school was told to use standard-issue council letter paper
bearing the slogan ``Derbyshire Council Council supports
nuclear-free zones,'' according to Headmaster Geoffrey Price.
   Price opposed the idea, and Conservative member of Parliament
Peter Rost said Tuesday he would ask Education Secretary Kenneth
Baker to intervene.
   Later Tuesday, the council's Labor Party leader, David
Bookbinder, said the council would have no objection to the school
keeping its motto on the stationery as long as it used the slogan
as well.
   Price said he welcomed the compromise but was puzzled by it.
   ``I have been suggesting this for a year or more but was told it
was unacceptable,'' he said. ``However, so let it be.''
   Chesterfield School was founded in 1594.
</TEXT>
