<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Robertson-Libel 3rdLd-Writethru a0814 03-01 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Robertson-Libel, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0814,680</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Says He'll Drop Libel Suit Against McCloskey</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New 6-7 grafs with McCloskey comment, bgng: McCloskey said,
new graf 14, At another, with more Robertson comment at news
conference</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican presidential candidate Pat
Robertson said Tuesday he will drop his libel suit against former
Rep. Pete McCloskey rather than go to trial on Super Tuesday, the
biggest day of the primary season.
   Robertson, who was accused of avoiding combat duty in the Korean
War through his father's influence, said he wants to take the case
to voluntary arbitration in an effort to clear his and his father's
names. But he said if McCloskey refuses to do that he will drop the
suit anyway.
   McCloskey's lawyer, George Lehner, said a proposal to use
arbitration was rejected by Robertson's lawyers nine months ago,
and he said to propose it on the eve of trial ``is a little
disingenuous'' and ``a red herring.''
   Lehner has said repeatedly that McCloskey will not agree to
settlement in the case unless Robertson pays legal fees _ estimated
at $400,000 _ piled up by the former congressmen.
   ``We are prepared to go to trial,'' Lehner said after learning
of Robertson's announcement. ``If he wants to drop the suit,'' the
lawyer said, Robertson must ``pay the legal fees'' amassed by
McCloskey to defend the case.
   McCloskey said it's ``not for him (Robertson) to decide'' to
drop the suit, saying he would oppose any motion by Robertson to
dismiss the case.
   ``I would rather go to trial. He's called me a liar all over the
United States,'' McCloskey said in a telephone interview. ``I would
much prefer there be a verdict as to which of us has told the
truth.''
   Robertson's $35 million suit accuses McCloskey of defaming him
in a widely publicized letter contending the former television
evangelist had used the influence of his father, the late Sen. A.
Willis Robertson, to avoid combat duty in the Korean War as a
Marine Corps officer.
   The case had been scheduled for next Tuesday, the same date as
Republican primaries and caucuses in 17 states, including Florida
where Robertson was campaigning.
   ``In order to compete in that trial I would have to break off my
campaign today and run the risk of losing Florida, Texas, South
Carolina and other parts of the South,'' Robertson said at an
airport news conference. ``That was an impossible decision for me
to make and an unfair one.''
   He has proposed that the issue be resolved by the Iowa Libel
Dispute Program run jointly by the University of Iowa College of
Law and the American Arbitration Association.
   Robertson said if McCloskey refuses arbitration he would take
pre-trial evidence and testimony already collected to an
unspecified panel of experts and have them give a public opinion on
McCloskey's contentions.
   ``If he doesn't (go to arbitration), we will prove to the
American people that he truly doesn't want the truth to come out,''
Robertson said.
   At another news conference later in Orlando, Robertson
complained about the judge's actions, saying: ``She has done
everything she can to get us to drop the case. I have done
everything I could to make a settlement based on the truth.''
   In his letter, McCloskey wrote that he and Robertson had been on
the same Korea-bound troop ship in 1951 but that Robertson was
taken off the vessel in Japan where he was given a non-combat post
after telling other Marines his father would arrange a transfer.
   McCloskey also wrote that when Robertson later was sent to Korea
he was known as the ``division liquor officer'' because he made
frequent trips to Japan.
   Robertson has denied that his father used any influence to get
him off the troop ship.
   While campaigning in Miami on Monday, Robertson called McCloskey
a ``pathological liar'' and charged that he circulated the Korea
story in an effort to hurt Robertson's political campaign.
   He also contended McCloskey is a supporter of Vice President
George Bush, one of Robertson's opponents in the campaign for the
GOP presidential nomination.
</TEXT>
