<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Brazil-Strike 1stLd-Writethru a0843 03-01 0461</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brazil-Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0843,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strikers, Military Police Clash in Southern Brazil; Dozens Hurt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing throughout. No pickup</NOTE>
<DATELINE>RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 500 military police
troopers fought about 2,500 striking coal miners in southern Brazil
on Tuesday and dozens of people were injured, according to a union
lawyer and a state senator.
   The melee took place in Criciuma, a town in southern Santa
Catarina state, 800 miles southwest of Rio.
   The union lawyer, Alfredo Gava, told The Associated Press by
telephone from the region, ``Many miners from other companies and
townspeople joined in the protest, which turned the city center
into a war zone. By the end, there were more than 5,000 people
throwing rocks and objects.''
   Gava said at least 30 police and miners were injured and one
miner was arrested. The chief of local police, Luis Gonzaga
Schmidt, reported that five people were held for a few hours, then
were let go.
   The chief put the number of injured _ police, miners and others
caught up in the turmoil _ at 20.
   However, State Sen. Itamar da Silva, who was at the site of the
brawl, said that 33 military police and 33 miners were hurt.
   Authorities said the troopers were under orders not to attack
the strikers, but retaliated when they themselves came under attack.
   Gava said the trouble began when police tried to remove striking
mine workers who were demonstrating peacefully in front of a branch
of the government-run bank, Banco do Brasil.
   ``The downtown square was almost completely destroyed,'' Gava
reported. ``Miners pulled down walls to break up the bricks for
ammunition against police and stoned houses and office buildings in
the immediate area.''
   TV Globo, Brazil's largest private network, showed a burning
motorbike in the square and military police with truncheons and
behind big shields rushing at miners. Troopers threw tear gas and
exploded concussion bombs to disperse the mob.
   Gava said the miners had been striking for 21 days to force
Carbonifera Prospera Mining Co. to adhere to a Jan. 1 agreement for
a 145 percent pay raise to make up for losses to 17 percent monthly
inflation. Pay scales were not immediately available.
   The company, along with five others in Criciuma, signed the
accord, but while the others paid up, Prospera went back on the
deal after the company was sold to the government-run National
Steel Co., Gava said.
   Company representatives said over TV Globo that Prospera's
responsibility to adhere to the agreement ended with the sale of
the company.
   TV Globo said the company had agreed to meet with union
representatives Wednesday.
   Da Silva, a Social Democrat, called the attack on the strikers
``unmotivated'' and said the state senate would investigate the
fray.
</TEXT>
