<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Deaths 1stLd-Writethru a0810 03-01 0334</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Deaths, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0810,0340</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS dates in 2nd graf on Besser obit to 1956 to 1958
sted of 1955 to 1959 and that Besser replaced Shemp sted of Curly;
AMs separate moved as a0867 on Besser.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Joe Besser</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Joe Besser, one of the later members of The
Three Stooges and who played the whining brat ``Stinky'' in ``The
Abbott and Costello Show,'' died Tuesday. He was 80.
   Besser was one of the Stooges from 1956 to 1958, replacing Shemp
Howard. He played the character Joe, who would often whine, ``Oooh,
you crazy,'' as he was slapped around by Moe Howard.
   In the 1940s, his portrayal of an exasperated, whining child
earned him a spot in Olsen and Johnson's long-running Broadway
show, ``Sons of Fun.'' In the 1950s and 60s, Besser became a
regular on several shows, including ``The Ken Murray Show,'' ``The
Joey Bishop Show'' and ``The Abbott and Costello Show.''
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Timothy Scott</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Timothy Scott, 32, a dancer and creator of
Mr. Mistoffolees in the Broadway hit musical ``Cats,'' died Feb. 24
of complications from AIDS.
   Scott appeared in Broadway companies of ``King of Hearts'' and
``Dancin.'' On television he performed in ``Baryshnikov in
Hollywood'' and during the 1980 Academy Awards broadcast.
   Scott also had a small part in the film version of ``A Chorus
Line.'' In 1982, he auditioned for the role of Mr. Mistoffelees and
stayed with ``Cats'' for about 18 months.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Victor Hass</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Victor P. Hass, who was book editor of the
Omaha World-Herald for 35 years and wrote hundreds of essays for
the newspaper, died Tuesday at age 78.
   Hass joined the World-Herald in 1937. He wrote more than 1,800
essays for the World-Herald under the heading ``Leaves From a
Bookman's Notebook.''
   Hass retired in 1971 as a regular member of the newspaper's
staff, where he was a copy editor. Hass continued as book reviewer
and essayist until 1975.
</TEXT>
