<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MercyKilling 1stLd-Writethru a0709 03-01 0411</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mercy Killing, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0709,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Elderly Man Charged In Mercy Killing Of Wife At Nursing Home</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS grafs 3-4 bgng `Mrs. Carlson...' to ADD background on
couple, how many children, what they did for a living. Picks up 5th
graf, `Judge Paul...'. Adds one graf on end to explain first-,
second-degree murder charges.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 77-year-old man who told authorities
he shot and killed his ailing wife in a nursing home so she
wouldn't have to ``go through any more pain'' was charged Tuesday
with first- and second-degree murder.
   Oscar Carlson of Evansville is accused of killing Agnes Carlson,
71, who suffered from advanced Alzheimer's disease.
   Mrs. Carlson, who was a cleaning woman in a doctor's office
before being stricken with Alzheimer's, was shot four times with a
.22-caliber pistol Monday at Crestview Manor Nursing Home in
Evansville, said Douglas County Sheriff Terry Eilers.
   Carlson, a former farmer and bus driver, was arrested without
incident at the nursing home and was being held in the county jail
in Alexandria, the sheriff said. The couple had three children.
   Judge Paul Ballard set bond at $100,000 Tuesday and scheduled a
second hearing Monday to determine when Carlson could be released,
Eilers said.
   ``We're planning on convening a grand jury relatively soon,''
Douglas County attorney Ann Carrott said Tuesday.
   Mrs. Carlson had been a patient at the home periodically and was
to undergo surgery Monday for a broken hip she suffered Sunday in a
fall, Eilers said.
   Carlson told nursing home administrators he wanted to visit his
wife before she was taken to the hospital and he went to her room,
Eilers said.
   Police were called when shots were heard, and authorities found
Carlson slumped over the victim's body, Eilers said.
   ``He said he realized what he was doing and he would have to
come with us,'' Eilers said. ``He stated to us he planned this
because he did not want her to suffer any more. He said he didn't
want her to go through any more pain.''
   Asked if Carlson had indicated whether he had discussed the
action with his wife, Eilers said: ``His wife was unable to discuss
anything with anybody.'' He said she was in very advanced stages of
Alzheimer's, a degenerative disease of the central nervous system
characterized especially by premature senility.
   The first-degree murder charge alleges that the killing was
premeditated, while state law defines second-degree murder as a
spontaneous killing.
</TEXT>
