<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Swaggart-Assemblies 1stLd-Writethru a0858 03-01 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Swaggart-Assemblies, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0858,0523</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Church Balks At Increasing Sanctions Against Swaggart</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 3 graf after 2nd graf to add that source says
decision now up to national organization; no immediate comment from
national church headquarters, picking up 3rd graf `The
Louisiana...'.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ALBERTO S. FRANCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Louisiana Assemblies of God church leaders
have rejected a request by national church officials that they
reconsider their sanction against television evangelist Jimmy
Swaggart, a church official confirmed Tuesday.
   The official, who asked to remain anonymous, said the 19-member
state presbytery decided to send back its original censure barring
Swaggart from preaching for three months. That decision came Monday
during a nine-hour meeting at Louisiana district headquarters in
Alexandria, La.
   ``The ball's in their court,'' the source said, indicating that
it would now be up to national Assemblies of God officials to
decide whether to abide by the state panel's recommendation.
   There was no immediate comment from the national headquarters in
Springfield, Mo.
   The Rev. Raymond Hudson, general treasurer, said he had no
comment and other officials were not at home Tuesday night. Calls
to the home of spokeswoman Juleen Turnage were met by busy signals.
   The Louisiana Presbytery's original sanction was a two-year
rehabilitation program that also included counseling for Swaggart,
who heads a ministry which reportedly has an annual income of $150
million.
   Swaggart stepped down from the pulpit Feb. 21, telling the
congregation at his Baton Rouge worship center in a tearful
confession that he had sinned against his family and God. Swaggart
reportedly paid a prostitute to pose naked for him and then tried
to make a deal with a minister who confronted him about it.
   The latest development in the scandal surfaced in a story by
KATC-TV in Lafayette, La. The station said it had also learned that
the national presbytery had recommended barring Swaggart from the
pulpit and television for a year, with an additional year of
regulation of his ministry afterwards.
   A Louisiana Assemblies of God official contacted by The
Associated Press Tuesday night confirmed that the state panel had
sent its previous sanction back to the national council. The
official talked only under conditions he not be identified.
   When asked if Louisiana officials had sent back their original
censure to the church's national leaders, the source said, ``It
would be correct to say that.''
   Cecil Janway, the Assemblies of God district superintendent for
Louisiana, said when the state panel met Monday that there would be
no announcement of its decision.
   ``Decisions made by the Louisiana district presbytery today will
be returned to the executive presbytery. There will be no further
announcement or comment from the Louisiana district council,''
Janway said.
   There was no indication whether Swaggart attended that meeting,
which lasted from 10 a.m. to 7 p.m. The Rev. Jim Rentz, who is
substituting for Swaggart at the Family Worship Center in Baton
Rouge, attended the meeting.
   Forrest Hall, secretary-treasurer of the Louisiana district
council, acknowledged Monday that national Assemblies of God
representatives were at the Alexandria meeting.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
