<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WorkingYouths     03-01 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Working Youths,0416</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Judge Fines Seven Church Members in Child Labor Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge ruled Tuesday that two
companies who used young people in a church job-training program
had violated child-labor laws and ordered stiff penalties for seven
people who ran the program.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Potter threatened to fine the seven
$21,000 a day if they continued to use the children, as young as 9
years old. He wrote that the children were ``manifestly being
exploited.''
   Shiloh True Light Church members acknowledged during the January
trial that their children worked at construction sites and in shops
where they carried bricks, laid foundations and more recently,
operated forklifts and power saws.
   They said they had been doing so for at least 100 years.
   Potter ordered McGee Brothers Co. of Union County to pay $98,225
in back wages plus nearly $36,000 in interest. McGee Brothers and
co-defendant Wendell's Woodworking Inc. of Mint Hill also were
ordered to pay nearly $70,000 in court costs.
   Spokesmen for the companies were not immediately available for
comment. There was no answer at the company offices, and their
lawyers were not in their offices.
   U.S. Department of Labor officials in Atlanta said they had not
received a copy of the decision and could not comment on whether
the $21,000-per-day fine was retroactive to Oct. 5, when Potter
issued an order to stop using the children.
   ``The minors are clearly dependent on the defendants' business
for their employment and are the class of person whom the act is
designed to protect,'' Potter wrote in a 58-page opinion.
   ``They are manifestly being exploited by defendants in this
case, whether or not they proclaim their purpose to be in
furtherance of their religious beliefs,'' Potter wrote.
   When the owners of the companies, both church members, continued
the program for the church after Potter's October order, the Labor
Department asked they be found in contempt of the injunction and be
fined $20,000 a day.
   On Tuesday, Potter said Wendell's would be fined $5,000 per day
and its two owners, Wendell Long and Herbert Long, be fined $500
each per day thay they remained in contempt of his order.
   The judge ordered McGee Brothers to pay $10,000 per day and
order five brothers who owned the company to pay $1,000 each per
day that they remained in contempt of the order.
</TEXT>
