<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz 3rdLd-Writethru a0774 03-01 0799</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0774,0820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Weighs Resuming Mideast Peace Shuttle After Reporting to
Reagan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Three grafs SUB for 12th graf pvs, In Amman ... UPDATING with
Mubarak comment. Pick up 13th graf pvs, Instead, it ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz
appeared ready on Tuesday night to resume his diplomatic shuttle in
the Middle East after reporting to President Reagan.
   A U.S. official said Jordan's King Hussein told Shultz at a
three-hour meeting in London earlier Tuesday that he was interested
in Shultz's effort to set up Arab-Israeli negotiations.
   The official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said Hussein
did not directly endorse the U.S. initiative, but told Shultz he
appreciated the effort being made to open talks.
   ``It was a serious discussion, covering the whole waterfront,''
the official said. ``Nobody is saying yes or no.''
   A statement issued by the Jordanian Embassy in London said
Hussein reiterated Jordan's position that an international peace
conference should be attended by the five permanent members of the
U.N. Security Council _ the United States, the Soviet Union, China,
Britain and France _ and ``all parties to the conflict, including
the Palestine Liberation Organization.''
   Shultz arranged to confer with Reagan briefly Tuesday night and
more fully on Wednesday before Reagan begins his talks in the
Belgian capital with 15 other allied leaders attending a North
Atlantic Treaty Organization summit.
   Shultz would return to the Middle East at the conclusion of the
summit Thursday night and try over the next two days to get
acceptance of the U.S. formula for negotiations to deal with both
Palestinian unrest in areas under Israeli control and an overall
Arab-Israeli settlement.
   ``He's a key, in my opinion,'' Shultz said of Hussein before
their meeting at the king's residence in London's Kensington
district.
   ``He has immense standing and is a person who has been here a
long time.'' Talking to reporters on the way to London from the
Middle East, Shultz acknowledged he made little progress in four
days of shuttle diplomacy.
   He said he could detect a narrowing of differences, but ``I
don't know if I could describe them in any way that would be
perceptible to anyone else.''
   Yet, Shultz said, ``assuming everyone continues the attitude
they have to keep working, to keep working, we'll do it.''
   President Hosni Mubarak of Egypt, however, in his first comment
on his talks with Shultz, said Tuesday he had reservations about
the U.S. plan and he would disclose them only after a final formula
was reached.
   Mubarak and Shultz conferred in Egypt Sunday. Mubarak spoke to
reporters while visiting neighboring Sudan. Egypt's Middle East
News Agency carried his statements from Khartoum.
   In Amman Monday, reporters were told that Jordan was not putting
pressure on the PLO to form a mixed negotiating delegation for
peace talks with Israel.
   Instead, it was reported, Jordan had taken the position the PLO
was the sole representative of the 1.5 million Palestinian Arabs
who live on the Israel-held West Bank and in Gaza, where clashes
have killed more than 70 Arabs.
   The U.S. proposal calls for Israel, Jordan and Palestinians to
open negotiations about April 1 on self-rule for the Palestinians
in Israeli-held territory. Talks on an overall Mideast settlement
would begin by December.
   Shultz met twice with Jordanian officials, but he had to seek an
authoritative answer from Hussein, who was in London for dental
treatment.
   Diplomatic sources in Jerusalem, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, said Shultz told Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir of Israel
he would return to the Middle East after the NATO summit if Hussein
gave at least qualified support to the U.S. proposal.
   On his flight to London, Shultz stressed a need for the United
States to step up contacts with Palestinians.
   Shultz confirmed the United States had persuaded Israel to relax
restrictions in permitting two Palestinians, Hanna Siniora, a
Jerusalem editor, and Fayez Abu Rahme, a Gaza lawyer, to go to
Washington to meet with him five weeks ago.
   ``We have communicated with them in some important, substantive
ways,'' Shultz said of U.S. approaches to the Palestinians.
   He said he had got the Palestinians' reaction indirectly while
in the Middle East from Egypt and Jordan.
   ``It isn't as though there's no feedback, '' Shultz said.
``There is feedback. It's not a substitute for directly sitting
down with people, and that in a sense is what we've been calling
for all along. In the end we've got to sit down together, so we
have made a major effort to communicate with them.''
   A group of 15 Palestinians invited to meet with Shultz in
Jerusalem Friday did not show up under PLO orders. He was similarly
snubbed in October on a trip to the Middle East.
</TEXT>
