<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, Adv 04,0863</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Public Quarrel Of Bishops Seen As Eroding Their Joint Influence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When the Vatican's doctrinal umpire was asked at
a recent New York news conference whether current controversy among
American bishops might weaken their collective voice, he wouldn't
say.
   However, the question is regarded a potentially more underlying
threat to the bishops' joint influence than the surface cause of
their present public quarrel _ a statement on AIDS.
   Cardinal Joseph Ratzinger, a powerful dispenser of church
discipline, said only that he wouldn't talk about the matter until
he speaks with U.S. bishops about it this spring.
   He has been critical of organizations of bishops such as the
National Conference of Catholic Bishops, and he left hanging the
potential of Vatican intervention of some kind.
   The bishops' unusual out-in-the-open dispute _ over an AIDS
statement issued by the bishops' 50-member administrative board in
mid-December _ has focused on some content of the statement itself.
   But several knowledgeable churchmen saw in the conflict a
potential erosion of the bishops' collective teaching function via
their conference, which has become increasingly vigorous on issues
from economics to nuclear weaponry.
   ``The loser will be the bishops' conference itself,'' writes
Monsignor Howard Basler in the Brooklyn Tablet.
   Catholic sociologist Eugene Kennedy of Loyola University says
the controversy ``plays into the hands of people who question the
purpose and effectiveness of the national conference's
collegiality.''
   Collegiality, the mutually shared responsibility of bishops and
others, was stressed by the reforming Second Vatican Council of
1962-65, and has been manifested increasingly in the U.S. bishops'
joint teaching documents.
   Kennedy, author of numerous books on church developments,
including his study of the growing scope of the conference,
``Re-Imagining American Catholicism,'' said in an interview:
   ``If personalities begin to speak outside the conference and
indicate that the conference wishes do not match their own, then
the harm to the conference could be irreparable.''
   Asked if that was happening, he said, ``Exactly.''
   He said it ``would please certain people in Rome who have long
been suspicious and wary of the bishops' conference in the United
States. There are several Curial officials who wish to diminish its
influence on a practical level.''
   Ratzinger, head of the Vatican's watchful Congregation for the
Doctrine of the Faith, has said there is ``no theological basis''
for national bishops' conferences.
   He says such organizations risk smothering Rome's direct line of
authority with individual bishops. That authority plainly can be
more readily exercised with lone bishops than with national blocs
of them.
   In any case, those objecting to the AIDS statement have been
largely those regarded as among the bishops' conservative wing,
tending to be more closely aligned with the conservative Ratzinger.
   Kennedy said he presumed ``good motives'' of those challenging
the AIDS statement, but ``the effect is to damage the process of
collegiality itself.''
   ``Collegiality is the process used to avoid seeming personality
conflicts,'' he said. ``Collegiality means everybody is heard, with
a focus on the issue, rather than on two or three personalities.''
   Individual bishops always are free to dissent from conference
conclusions, but a highly inclusive consensus usually is achieved,
and any bishops disagreeing simply disregard the recommendations in
their dioceses, rather than challenging the process.
   In the present conflict, several bishops, notably New York's
Cardinal John O'Connor and Boston's Cardinal Bernard Law, have
publicly assailed the AIDs document. Several others, including
Chicago's Cardinal Joseph Bernardin and Cincinnati's Archbishop
Daniel E. Pilarczyk, have defended it.
   The document repeatedly insists on the church's teaching of
abstinence from sex before marriage and fidelity within marriage as
the only sure safeguards against AIDS, saying that without them,
there is no such thing as ``safe sex.''
   But one paragraph caused the fuss. It says public educational
programs, directed at people who may reject church standards, could
include information about condoms, which some medical experts say
may help prevent AIDS.
   Critics charged this implied approving condoms, condemned by the
church as birth-control devices. Defenders insist the document does
not approve condoms, but saw them as a ``lesser evil'' compared to
the ``greater evil'' of spreading a deadly disease.
   The bishops' administrative board meets March 21 to consider the
furor, and may put it before the entire conference of bishops in
June. Meanwhile, Ratzinger said he would discuss it with bishops in
their ad limina (periodic) visits to Rome beginning in March.
   The bishops' conference first was formed in 1917 to coordinate
church efforts in World War I. The Vatican threatened to supress it
in 1922 on grounds it infringed on jurisdiction of individual
bishops.
   The bishops managed to preserve it, insisting it was a voluntary
organization, depending on each bishop's free choice to
participate, and by their consensus, exercised collective
responsibilities and moral suasion.
   The U.S. conference has inspired 42 similar national Catholic
bishops' conferences around the world, acting to carry out mutual
responsibilities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Fri AMs, March 4</NOTE>
