<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionRoundup Adv04   03-01 0664</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Roundup, Adv 04,0689</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, March 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic, Protestant and Eastern
Orthodox representatives have urged the U.S. Senate to ratify,
without amendments or delay, the U.S.-Soviet treaty for reducing
intermediate-range nuclear forces.
   The Rev. Arie Brouwer of the National Council of Churches,
including most major Protestant and Eastern Orthodox bodies, called
the treaty a ``first step toward developing real security for us
and the world's people.''
   Roman Catholic Archbishop Roger Mahony of Los Angles, head of
the U.S. bishops' international policy committee, said the treaty
should become part of a continuing process of disarmament, making
for more stable Soviet-U.S. relationships.
   The religious leaders testified before the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A site-selection task force this week
recommended that the Board of Pensions of the Presbyterian Church
(USA) be based in Philadelphia.
   The choice, subject to ratification by the church's general
assembly in June, was among these three potential sites:
   Louisville, where the newly merged denomination has established
its headquarters; Atlanta, where the former Southern branch had its
headquarters, or Philadelphia where the Northern branch had its
pension board.
 
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MIAMI, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the anguish of American Jews over the
current violence in Israel, their commitment to the Jewish state
has not been weakened, says a veteran observer of the Middle East
scene.
   Hyman Bookbinder, American Jewish Committee special
representative, told a conference sponsored by the Miami Herald and
the University of Miami that U.S. Jews have felt ``agony, anguish,
frustration _ even anger at times.''
   But he added: ``It would be a serious mistake to interpret these
reactions as rejection of Israel or even a dilution of commitment.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the fundamentalist wing of Southern
Baptists predicts that that its candidate for president will be the
Rev. Jerry Vines of Jacksonville, Fla., opposing the Rev. Richard
Jackson of Phoenix, Ariz.
   Both take a conservative view of Scripture, the Rev. Paige
Patterson, a fundamentalist leader, said in predicting their
candidacies, but he said Jackson has been co-opted by the moderates.
   To maintain the nine-year resurgence of
conservative-fundamentalists at the denomination's convention in
June, he said, they must back ``an inerrantist for president who
will do their bidding.''
   ``Inerrantists'' maintain Scripture is without factual error.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lithuanian Information Center says several
persons associated with celebrations last month of the 70th
anniversary of Lithuanian Independence are being held under house
arrest by Soviet police.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has declined to
reconsider a lower court decision that parents don't have a right
to substitute home teaching for school-required textbooks that
offend parental religious sensitibilites.
   The high court let stand a federal Court of Appeals ruling that
the Hawkins County, Tenn., school board was not obligated to
provide alternative reading arrangements for pupils whose parents
objected to various textbooks.
   A district court had ordered school officials to excuse students
for home instruction from the controversial reading assignments,
but the appeals court said the state is not obliged to shelter
children ``from exposure to some ideas they find offensive.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roman Catholic worshipers in this
diocese _ and others across the country _ last weekend took home a
little cardboard piece that folds into a small ``bowl.''
   During the Lenten season between now and Easter, they're asked
to place in the ``bowl'' each week the cost of a small meal _ the
accumulated proceeds of which go to feed the hungry.
   Called ``Operation Rice Bowl,'' the program is sponsored by
Catholic Relief Services, with 75 percent of the total collected
going to world-wide relief, and 25 percent of it retained to help
the local poor.
   Youngstown Bishop James Malone said the project is an excellent
means of observing the Lenten practice of almsgiving and ``adds an
element of awareness of the hunger that others suffer.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, March 4</NOTE>
</DOC>
