<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--Zinman Adv11-13   03-01 0929</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Zinman, Adv 11-13,0967</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11-13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 11-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Artists: A Can-Do Conductor in a Can-Do Town</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   David Zinman, who has been the music director of
the Baltimore Symphony since 1985, is as delighted with the
orchestra as he is with the city itself.
   Just before Zinman arrived in Baltimore from his previous
orchestra in Rochester, N.Y., Baltimore philanthropist Joseph
Meyerhoff, who'd been picking up the symphony's bills, died.
   ``To my horror, we had an accumulated deficit of $2.3 million
and we were losing $1 million a year. We would be out of business
in a year unless we raised money,'' he said.
   A new executive director and the board, with some new members,
were told by consultants they probably couldn't raise a $14 million
endowment. ``They went out and raised $40 million in Baltimore in
22 months _ a new world's record.
   ``It was done by business leaders, which is essentially the way
it has to be done. The selling point was, if you want to have a
city that's taken seriously, we have to have an orchestra,'' Zinman
said. ``Baltimore had a renaissance in the last 15 years. It's a
can-do town. People who live there feel they can do what they want
to do.
   ``We did a tour of Europe and Russia last May. One of
Baltimore's banks paid for it. The governor and a senator came
along. They did a presentation lunch in London, with a big slide
show. Orchestra musicians played. People were invited to our
concert the next night.''
   The year's tour for the orchestra started March 7 in New York.
It will continue in Davis, San Francisco, Los Angeles, Costa Mesa
and Palm Springs, Calif., and Tucson, with cellist Yo-Yo Ma as
guest. Next year, the orchestra will tour the East Coast with flute
soloist James Galway.
   This season, Zinman started Saturday morning ``informal
concerts,'' repeats of Friday night concerts with a top price of $9
and a little conversation.
   ``They said, `You have to talk to the audience.' I'm a fan of
`Prairie Home Companion.' I decided to do it like an old radio
show,'' Zinman said. ``We have a phony sponsor _ tapioca _ and a
tapioca jingle. Next year we'll do eight of them, broadcast live by
National Public Radio. I explain the musical themes for them to
follow while they listen. We recommend that little kids don't come;
it's serious classical music with zaniness in between pieces.
   ``I'm an American. I'm not Viennese. I have wild ideas and
fantasies. Why not let them loose when you have the chance?''
   This season, Public Radio is broadcasting 13 regular symphony
concerts and the British Broadcasting Corp. is doing several.
   After the tour, Ma and the Baltimore Symphony will record
Britten's ``Symphony for Cello and Orchestra'' and Barber's ``Cello
Concerto'' for CBS. The orchestra has made a Berlioz album for
Telarc and an album by resident composer Christopher Rouse for
Nonesuch. Telarc plans to record the Schumann symphonies and an
all-Elgar compact disc with the Baltimore Symphony.
   ``I work with my orchestra a lot,'' the 51-year-old conductor
said. ``My contract calls for 20 weeks a year. I do about 24. The
days are over when I want to flit about, guest conducting.
   ``I want to make the Baltimore into a great orchestra. In order
to do that you have to spend time digging in the garden. You can't
just smell the flowers. You have to make them grow; you have to be
there. Guest conducting doesn't do much for you musically. What
really does a lot for you is to work with your orchestra to develop
a repertoire and a style of playing that is uniquely your own. You
really then get to make the music you're capable of making.
   ``With guesting, you're doing pieces you know pretty well. You
come in like a lover, smile, make love and go away. It's a little
like the singles scene. When you're with the wife, you really have
to be there for the long haul.''
   The conductor's family includes a son who has a synthesizer
business, a daughter in a Brisbane, Australia, dance company and a
12-year-old son living with Zinman and his wife in Baltimore.
   Zinman, a New York native, met the late Pierre Monteux,
conductor of the London Symphony who was then 83, at Tanglewood one
summer. Three years later, Zinman began to assist him.
   ``He was a great model to emulate,'' Zinman said. ``He was a
master of balance and was at home in all styles of music. He had a
great tradition behind him. He'd played in a string quartet for
Brahms. He conducted Diaghilev's ballets, including the first `Rite
of Spring.' He was a warm human being who got along with orchestra
musicians. He was a psychologist and had wonderful patience.''
   At the 1983 Holland Festival, Monteux recommended Zinman to the
Netherlands Chamber Orchestra when a scheduled conductor got sick.
From that, Zinman became music director of the Netherlands Chamber
Orchestra from 1964 -77 and of the Rotterdam Philharmonic from
1979-82. He was the Rochester Philharmonic's music director from
1974-85.
   Someday he'd like to help young conductors.
   ``I would like to take three pupils, use them as assistants and
coach them. It's a question of finding a way to schedule that and
get the money to do it,'' he said.
   ``I really believe you must pay back what you've borrowed.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 11-13</NOTE>
