<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--BlackLizard Adv11-13   03-01 0860</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Black Lizard, Adv 11-13,0880</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv11-13</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, March 11-13 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Books and Authors: Dark Suspense Novels Rage On</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHLEEN MACLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERKELEY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The characters who inhabit Black Lizard
books are contemporary losers struggling through scenes set in the
sizzling middle of hell on earth.
   Although that may not spur hordes of readers to rush out to buy
one, Black Lizard co-founders Barry Gifford and Don Ellis report
their dark suspense novels nevertheless have become a big hit, with
sales approaching $1 million this year.
   They're not worried that fans of traditional mysteries or gothic
romances shun harsh Lizard novels such as ``A Ticket to Hell,''
``The Alcoholics,'' ``Swamp Sister'' or ``A Moment to Prey.''
   ``I don't read mysteries, I don't know anything about mysteries
... I can't read them,'' said Gifford, contending most are poorly
written and focus primarily on advancing the plot. Black Lizard
books may contain a mystery, but many don't include a corpse or
even a crime, he said.
   As the editor who selects the Black Lizard lineup, Gifford has a
clear vision of what fits and what doesn't, and he has no intention
of trying to attract the fainthearted.
   These thrillers are ``not just hard-boiled. They're books with a
certain psychological edge,'' he said. Many of Black Lizard's
readers are young, and Gifford speculated they may share the
generally nihilistic views presented in the novels.
   Consider this classic Black Lizard example from ``Cassidy's
Girl'' by David Goodis:
   ``A feeling of vague uneasiness took root inside him and grew
and sharpened and became acute. He knew he was disappointed because
the battle hadn't continued. Of course, he told himself, that
didn't make sense. But then there were very few elements in his
life with Mildred that made sense. And lately, he recalled, there
was absolutely nothing that made sense. It was getting worse all
the time.''
   In Black Lizard's own bibliography, the novels are described as
presenting ``distinctive and absolutely authentic (mostly) American
voices; satirical, maddening, compelling, fascinating.''
   According to Gifford and Ellis, Black Lizard has become so
successful that major publishing companies are trying to imitate
the innovations of the small Creative Arts company that has carried
the Black Lizard imprint since 1983.
   That's when Gifford was browsing in a Paris bookstore and
discovered a stack of Jim Thompson and Harry Whittington novels,
many of them the same ``dark'' 25-cent paperbacks that he loved to
read as a kid while hanging out at his Tampa, Fla. neighborhood
drugstore.
   While the books' popularity had plunged in the United States
since the '50s, they remained a strong favorite with the French,
who have shown steady appreciation of the ``serie noire'' storyline
of such authors as Thompson, Whittington and Goodis.
   ``It best represents the vision of America that the French like
to retain,'' Gifford said. ``It's kind of like the Wild West.''
   Filmmaker Francois Truffaut claimed Goodis as one of his
favorites, filming the writer's ``Shoot the Piano Player.'' Goodis
also wrote ``Dark Passage,'' and did the screenplay as well for the
Humphrey Bogart-Lauren Bacall film. Gifford's own ``Port Tropique''
is in pre-production for a movie.
   He said his friend, best-selling novelist Elmore Leonard,
routinely calls to suggest Black Lizard nab a certain new author or
novel. ``It's become a writers' series as well,'' Gifford said.
   But the company's budget remains relatively small and it's
impossible for it to lure big names such as Leonard. And some New
York publishing houses trying to duplicate Black Lizard have landed
certain books and authors by paying higher fees.
   Even so, Black Lizard founders are confident that by retaining
the novels' strong identity it will survive and flourish. ``You can
fill it (a company's booklist) with a lot of glop, but pretty soon
your readership falls away,'' said Gifford.
   ``I think we're just going to get better at what we do, not
necessarily bigger,'' Ellis said.
   Despite Black Lizard's surge in popularity, Gifford said he
wasn't sure what to expect at first: ``I thought it would either
catch on right away or we wouldn't sell more than 10 books. I
didn't expect a mediocre reaction.''
   They started out printing 5,000 copies for each of their first
three books. Today they begin with 10,000 copies each, reprinting
when necessary. Their booklist totals 43. Black Lizard is
publishing its first hardcovers this spring and bookstore chains
such as B. Dalton and Waldenbooks have placed orders.
   Black Lizard books are easy to spot. In addition to the
trademark lizard logo taken from a Peruvian stone rubbing and
strategically placed on each cover, most of the novels also feature
haunting, lurid cover designs by San Francisco artist Jim Kirwin.
   Gifford said they decided to tone down the focus of the novel
cover after the first three, making it less violent and graphic yet
``something that can penetrate the psyche. ... It's almost like a
dream.''
   The covers have become so successful that contrary to the old
maxim, some people judge Black Lizard books by their covers and buy
them for that reason alone.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, March 11-13</NOTE>
