<DOCNO> AP880301-0232 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0447EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   03-01 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0554</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Never Die Young'' (CBS) _ James Taylor
   
   ``Never Die Young'' is classic James Taylor, which is to say
warm, melodic, soothing, thoughtful, reminiscent of ``Sweet Baby
James'' _ progressive but just as personal.
   The LP's title comes from the fine cut: ``Never give up, never
slow down, never grow old, never die young.''
   Love seems to be in bloom once again in the rock world. Well,
sort of. Bruce Springsteen recently turned away from larger issues
to tackle the subject in ``Tunnel of Love.'' ``Never Die Young'' is
Taylor's two-cents' worth. It's prettier and more cutting. On the
cover of ``Tunnel of Love,'' Springsteen leans on a convertible on
a beach. Taylor puts a lone wolf on ``Never Die Young.'' It's the
call of the wild.
   His affinity for the wild life helped destroy his marriage with
singer-songwriter Carly Simon, and he talks a lot here about
troubled relationships.
   Take ``Valentine's Day,'' which starts as a silly sweet ode to
romance: ``Beneath the tide the fishes glide, fin to fin and side
to side, for fishy love has now begun, fishy love, finny fun.''
   But in later verses, its true nature surfaces: ``Me and you, you
and him, him and her, us and them, we keep score, love as war,
Valentine's Day.''
   ``Runaway Boy'' is a slice of Zydeco that inspires Taylor to
declare he's cleaning up his act: ``I'm gonna give up believing I
was born to run, and stop acting like a man that gets shot from a
gun. I'm putting down roots, I want to soak up the sun and stay
right here until my days are done.''
   ``Sweet Potato Pie'' is the most commercial cut, a happy bounce
down a latter-day Tin Pan Alley. Taylor even rhymes June, moon,
spoon and loon.
   ``Never Die Young'' is tough, pretty, loose, funny _ just about
perfect. Luckily for us, Taylor took his own advice.
   _ By Kathryn Baker, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Pontiac'' (MCA-Curb) _ Lyle Lovett
   
   Country singer Lyle Lovett looks more like a Pet Shop Boy than
an Oak Ridge Boy, so it's no surprise that ``Pontiac'' is slightly
off center. The tone is set by the opening song, ``If I Had a
Boat,'' wherein Lovett recalls the time Tonto told off the Lone
Ranger. It's impossible not to like.
   Other highlights are the title cut, which could have been writen
by Randy Newman in a dark mood; ``L.A. County,'' with a violent
climax that Lovett nearly sneaks past the listener; and three
hilarious songs about the art of compromise _ ``Give Back My
Heart,'' ``She's No Lady'' and ``She's Hot to Go.''
   Lovett includes several graceful bows to traditional Nashville
as well. The best is ``Walk Through the Bottomland,'' which
features Emmylou Harris' harmony on the chorus.
   Lovett, who co-produced, doesn't clutter the arrangements. But
along with pedal steel and piano, he effectively uses horns and, on
the title song, a cello. Altogether, ``Pontiac'' is a most
enjoyable ride.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0233 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0112EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights TwoTakes   03-01 0507</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, Two Takes,0530</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The October stock market crash will contribute
to a significant slowdown in economic growth this year but the
country should be able to avoid a recession, economists for top
U.S. corporations say.
   The National Association of Business Economists said Monday its
latest member survey found economists were more upbeat than three
months ago when more than half of them said the record fall in
stock prices on Oct. 19 would lead to a recession in 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has agreed to delay a
ruling that would have given some banks limited investment banking
powers.
   Monday's ruling provided the securities industry with a
last-minute boost in its effort to keep banks off its turf.
   The one-page stay by the 2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in
New York came a day before the scheduled expiration of a
seven-month moratorium on new bank powers passed by Congress last
summer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AMARILLO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The partnership controlled by T. Boone
Pickens Jr. has offered to buy Homestake Mining Co., the nation's
largest gold producer, for about $1.9 billion in cash.
   In a letter to Homestake Chairman Harry Conger, Mesa Limited
Partnership offered Monday to negotiate an agreement to buy all
common shares of the San Francisco-based mining company for $20 a
share. Homestake has about 93 million shares outstanding, and did
not immediately respond to the offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two companies controlled by
television producer Burt Sugarman have proposed taking over
Virginia-based newspaper publisher and broadcaster Media General
Inc. for $1.75 billion.
   But the family of Media General's chairman, D. Tennant Bryan,
which controls a majority of the company's voting stock, indicated
Monday it wasn't interested in the proposal from Sugarman, whose
investments range from game shows to waste disposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stop & Shop Cos. Inc. has agreed to be acquired in
a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout by the investment firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts Inc.
   But hostile suitor Dart Group Corp. said Monday it remained
intent on trying to gain control of the retailer.
   Stop & Shop said a Kohlberg Kravis subsidiary, SSC Holdings
Corp., will purchase at least 66 percent of the 28 million
outstanding Stop & Shop shares at $44 each.
   Dart, meanwhile, extended until March 9 an offer of $37 a share
for all outstanding Stop & Shop stock and indicated it planned to
go ahead with a proxy fight to replace Stop & Shop directors later
this month.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of American Express Co. is suggesting
creation of a new international financial organization to help ease
the debt crisis of developing nations by buying their loans.
   Chairman James D. Robinson III said Monday the organization
would buy outstanding Third World loans at a discount and then
offer the banks which had held the loans new, long-term securties
in exchange.
   Robinson said he hoped the proposal will spark a dialogue
because of the risk of a debt crisis.
</TEXT>
