<TEXT>
   Fidelity Investments, the nation's largest mutual
fund firm, plans to lay off 800 workers hired to handle the rapid
growth it enjoyed before October's stock market crash.
   Fidelity attributed the 10.5 percent work force reduction
announced Monday to a slump in new stock transactions, slower money
management business since the Oct. 19 crash and a drop in
individual retirement accounts due to new federal laws limiting the
tax deductability of IRA contributions.
</TEXT>
