<TEXT>
   The value of Midwestern farmland is up
about 7 percent from depressed 1986 levels, but still is little
more than half what it was seven years ago, the Federal Reserve
Bank of Chicago says.
   The bank said Monday its survey of about 500 agricultural
bankers in five Midwestern states shows farmland values rose 3.2
percent during the last three months of 1987 _ the fourth
consecutive quarterly increase.
</TEXT>
