<DOCNO> AP880301-0237 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Pepper-Seven-Up     03-01 0400</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pepper-Seven-Up,0413</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dr Pepper, Seven-Up In Tentative Agreement To Combine Operations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Blending the operations of Dr Pepper Co. and The
Seven-Up Co. will allow the companies to continue an aggressive
style in the beverage industry, company officials say.
   The boards of directors at holding companies for Dr Pepper and
Seven-Up announced the merger of operations on Monday. The
transaction, which is contingent on a definitive agreement and
regulatory approval, was expected to be completed in 60 to 90 days.
   Groups led by the Dallas-based investment partnership Hicks &
Haas acquired Dr Pepper and Seven-Up October in separate
transactions during 1986. One group acquired Dr Pepper Co. for $416
million in August 1986 and another group bought Seven Up Co. for
$240 million two months later.
   Thomas O. Hicks and Robert B. Haas, co-chairmen of both
companies, said the merger was a culmination of ``superb
achievement'' at both companies since their acquisition. No
management changes were expected, the pair said in a prepared
statement
   ``The combination of our two companies will enable us to
continue our aggressive style in this industry, as demonstrated by
our recent introduction of two new products, 7Up Gold and Diet 7Up
Gold,'' said John R. Albers, who is chief executive of both
companies.
   The operations of the two companies have been increasingly
integrated in recent months, the companies said. For instance, they
each have used manufacturing facilities in St. Louis to produce
soft drink concentrate.
   ``The merger will allow the companies to be completely operated
as one company, which has obvious advantages internally and in the
marketplace,'' said Albers.
   The trade newsletter Beverage Digest estimated the two companies
captured about 10.7 percent of the $38 billion soft drink market in
1987, up from 10.4 percent the previous year.
   The soft drink leaders are Coca-Cola Co., whose various brands
accounted for 40.3 percent of the soft drink market last year, and
Pepsi-Cola Co., which had 30.2 percent, according to the newsletter
based in Greenwich, Conn.
   ``This formalizes a close and efficient relationship,'' said
Emanuel Goldman, who follows the beverage industry for the
investment firm Montgomery Securities in San Francisco. ``It will
help them compete better in the marketplace.''
   Upon completion of the merger, significant owners of the
combined enterprise will include senior management; Hicks & Haas;
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.; Cadbury Schweppes PLC; Donaldson,
Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp. and Citicorp Venture Capital.
</TEXT>
