<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Stop&Shop Bjt   03-01 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stop & Shop, Bjt,0480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dart To Continue Stop & Shop Offer Despite Buyout Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dart Group Corp. says it plans to continue its
hostile bid for Stop & Shop Cos. Inc., even though its target has
agreed to a $1.23 billion leveraged buyout in an attempt to thwart
Dart.
   Dart extended through March 9 its hostile $37 a share offer for
Stop & Shop's 28 million outstanding shares, totaling about $1.03
billion, and indicated it planned to proceed with a proxy fight to
replace Stop & Shop directors later this month, spokesman Jeffrey
Gast said Monday.
   The tender offer had been scheduled to expire Monday night.
   Stop & Shop, a major Northeastern retailing chain, earlier
Monday had announced its tentative agreement to be taken private in
a leveraged buyout led by the firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.,
which will pay its stockholders $44 a share.
   The firm will purchase at least 66 percent of Stop & Shop's
outstanding Stop & Shop shares. If all the outstanding stock were
purchased, the leveraged buyout would total $1.23 billion.
   The company's shareholders still must approve the deal.
   In a leveraged buyout, investors acquire a company mainly with
borrowed funds that are repaid with the target company's cash flow
or the sale of its assets.
   Stop & Shop has 113 supermarkets and 169 Bradlees department
stores in 12 states in the Northeast.
   Under the buyout plan , which may include participation by the
company's top executives, Stop & Shop will retain its present
management and remain based in Braintree, Mass.
   The company's stock has risen by more than $25 a share since
Dart first announced its takeover intent in January. In New York
Stock Exchange trading on Monday, it rose another 87{ cents to
$43.50 a share.
   Harry Wells, an analyst at Adams, Harkness & Hill in Boston,
guessed that Dart was unlikely to match the $44 a share offer.
   ``You've got to be able to support the debt with some level of
safety ... and ($44) is about as much as one can reasonably afford
to pay (for Stop & Shop),'' Wells said.
   Dart, which owns 738,200 Stop & Shop shares, is best known for a
series of unsuccessful but profitable takeover attempts of major
retailers.
   In its most recent bid, Dart dropped a $6 billion hostile offer
for Minneapolis-based Dayton Hudson Corp. following the October
stock market crash.
   Other Dart takeover attempts included a 1986 bid for Safeway Co.
and a 1987 bid for Supermarkets General.
   KKR, which took Safeway private in a leveraged buyout following
the failed Dart bid, is one of the nation's biggest investment
partnerships specializing i leveraged buyouts.
   Last week, the firm acquired New York-based Seaman Furniture Co.
for $350 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0240 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0204EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GM-Saturn     03-01 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GM-Saturn,0380</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saturn Begins Recruiting Workers for Tennessee Assembly Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp.'s newest carmaking division
has begun recruiting the first 3,000 factory workers for its Spring
Hill, Tenn., assembly plant, Saturn Corp. said Monday.
   The Saturn plant will begin production in the summer of 1990 for
the 1991 model year. Most workers will be hired in mid-1989, when
Saturn begins production on pilot models, said Saturn spokeswoman
Laurie Kay.
   Saturn representatives will tour GM facilities around the
nation, explaining directly to workers for the first time how
Saturn will work and what a job there would be like.
   Saturn already has received a number of resumes, but the push
announced Monday is the first real recruitment effort it has made.
   Under an agreement between GM and the UAW, GM workers will get
the first 6,000 Saturn jobs available over time, including the
initial 3,000. Saturn workers will be covered by a separate labor
contract from the national GM-UAW pact.
   Like Japanese automakers that have hired for U.S. factories,
including Mitsubishi Motors Corp. and Mazda Motor Corp., Saturn's
hiring process will be lengthy.
   Potential Saturn workers will go through an assessment process
intended to give them an idea of what Saturn work will be like and
whether they want to do it, while giving Saturn an idea of how well
the prospective employee works in a team situation, Kay said.
   Saturn employees will work in teams, instead of performing more
traditional auto assembly work that consists of repeating one
precise task over and over. Kay said the Saturn plant probably will
run on two shifts.
   Workers' salaries will amount to 80 percent of GM hourly
workers' base pay, with the 20 percent difference made up in
incentive pay linked to such factors such as productivity increases
and Saturn's profitability, Kay said.
   Active or laid-off workers who leave the GM system for Saturn
automatically give up any recall rights and seniority at GM plants,
she said.
   But at Saturn, their jobs would be protected during industry
slumps because the company will be required to look for ways to cut
its inventory that exclude laying off workers, Kay said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0241 </DOCNO>
