<1ST_LINE>u b PM-Dollar-Gold     03-01 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Higher, Gold Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar rose marginally against most major
currencies in very thin European trading early today. Gold prices
were higher.
   Traders said activity was muted before the release later today
of the January index of leading U.S. economic indicators, although
the report was expected to have little impact.
   Midmorning dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday:
1.6909 West German marks, up from 1.6875; 1.3945 Swiss francs, up
from 1.3903; 5.7205 French francs, up from 5.7150; 1.8963 Dutch
guilders, up from 1.8945; 1,245.75 Italian lire, up from 1,244.25;
and 1.2578 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2622.
   The British pound slipped to $1.7712 from $1.7725.
   The dollar rose in Tokyo in heavy speculative trading, closing
at 128.63 Japanese yen, up from Monday's close of 128.12 yen. In
later London trading today, the dollar was pegged at 128.50 yen.
   London's major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of
$429.15 a troy ounce at midmorning, down from an opening bid of
$431.30 but up from Monday's late bid of $425.
   A trader said gold drifted off its higher opening levels as
market participants took profits on the metal's rally in New York
late Monday.
   In Zurich, gold was bid at $428.70 an ounce, up from $426.
   Earlier, gold closed in Hong Kong at a bid of $433.80 an ounce,
up from $430.19.
   Silver bullion was quoted in London at a bid of $6.21 a troy
ounce, up from $6.14.
</TEXT>
