<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0803EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Goodyear     03-01 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Goodyear,0364</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Giuliani Assumes Suing of Goodyear In False Claims Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government has filed a lawsuit seeking at
least $21 million from Goodyear Tire and Rubber Co. for allegedly
falsifying price information about balloon-type devices used to
guide bombs.
   The suit, originally filed last year by a competitor, was taken
over by U.S. Attorney Rudolph Giuliani and filed Monday in
Manhattan.
   The suit names Goodyear, a subsidiary called Goodyear Aerospace
Corp., and Loral Corp., which bought the subsidiary last year.
   ``Goodyear is confident that once the facts in the case are
examined objectively, the suit will be found without merit and the
charges dropped,'' Goodyear spokesman Walt McClenny said from his
Akron, Ohio, office.
   The case involves two devices called Air Inflatable Retarder
Assemblies that are used to slow and guide the flight of MK
500-pound and 1,000-pound bombs dropped from low-flying airplanes.
   The government charged that Goodyear Aerospace misrepresented
prices and costs of the labor involved; that the company unlawfully
induced a subcontractor to lower its price; and that it failed to
disclose substantial price reductions proposed for a subcontractor.
   Goodyear Aerospace was the only maker of the devices from 1982
to 1986. Irvin Industries Inc. entered the competition and filed a
$100 million antitrust suit in 1986.
   Irvin allegedly turned up information about fraud against the
government that it used in another suit it filed in 1987. That suit
was filed on behalf of the government under a ``whistleblower'' law
that allows the government to take over a suit.
   The suit filed Monday asks for at least $21 million in damages
under the False Claims Act and common law theories. In addition,
the government is seeking $10,000 for each unspecified false claim.
   A spokesman for Loral, who asked not to be identified, said that
those alleged practices would have occurred before Loral bought the
company and the potential for a lawsuit was known before the
purchase.
   He added, however, that ``Loral is confident the appropriate
management practices are in place that are consistent with
government procurement practices.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0805EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-AutoRecall     03-01 0110</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Auto Recall,0112</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mazda Recalling 11,889 Imported Sedans for Emission-Control Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mazda Motor Corp. said it is recalling 11,889 of
its 1988 Mazda 929 upscale sedans for possible improper positioning
of an emissions-control hose.
   In a statement issued Monday from Los Angeles, the Japanese
automaker said improper routing of a short section of the hose may
put it in contact with the car's air-conditioning piping, leading
eventually to a failure of the emissions-control system.
   Owners are being notified by mail to take their cars to a Mazda
dealer for free inspection and repositioning of the hose if
necessary. Mazda said the procedure takes about 15 minutes.
</TEXT>
