<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Penney-Building     03-01 0145</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Penney-Building,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>J.C. Penney Selling its Manhattan Skyscraper</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   J.C. Penney Co., which is relocating to Texas,
has decided to sell its midtown Manhattan headquarters rather than
lease the skyscraper as originally planned.
   The 45-story building could sell for up to $480 million, or $300
a square foot, according to real estate analysts.
   The expected price is well below the record $500 per square foot
commanded by similar buildings in the area sold before the Oct. 19
stock market crash.
   Penney plans to move its headquarters to Plano, Texas, near
Dallas, by the end of June and had been trying to lease the
building since last September.
   Harvey McCormick, a spokesman for the giant retailer, said
Monday that Penney already has received bids from prospective
buyers, but he refused to name them.
   Penney bought the building in 1977 for $55 million.

</TEXT>
