<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 0912EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-PillsburyMoves     03-01 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury Moves,0446</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury's Stafford Quits, Spoor Succeeds Him</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   William H. Spoor, formerly at the helm of of
Pillsbury Co., is coming out of retirement to take over his old job.
   The company announced Monday that its board of directors at a
regular meeting in Naples, Fla., elected Spoor chairman and chief
exectuive officer to replace John M. Stafford, who resigned. It
didn't give a reason for the management shakeup.
   Contacted in Naples on Monday, Spoor told the St. Paul Pioneer
Press Dispatch that other management changes will be announced
today. ``There won't be any firings, but we will be changing people
and responsibilities,'' Spoor said.
   Spoor described himself as a ``very interim'' CEO, adding,
``This doesn't please me at all.''
   ``The one thing this isn't is power plays and politics,'' he
said. ``Jack (Stafford) and I are good friends. I chose him to
succeed me.''
   Asked why Stafford quit, Spoor said, ``You'll have to ask him.
It just reached a point where it was no longer worth it to him.''
   Johnny Thompson, company spokesman, said Stafford was
unavailable for comment. He said his departure was voluntary and
that he left with no ties to Pillsbury.
   Pillsbury also said the board of directors appointed a search
committee to seek a chief executive for the company to succeed
Spoor.
   Stafford, 51, presided in fiscal 1987 over the company's first
earnings decline in 16 years. Earnings were $1.82 million, or $2.10
a share, down from $2.08 million, or $2.38 a share, in fiscal 1986.
   Stock analysts who were projecting fiscal 1988 earnings of about
$2.80 a share were told by Stafford in February to lower the
projections by about 30 cents a share, Thompson said.
   ``That may have been the straw that broke the camel's back,''
said Craig Carver, a food industry analyst with Minneapolis-based
Piper Jaffray & Hopwood Inc. ``He has been under increasing
pressure by the board. That may have been what did him in.''
   Carver said declining performance in Pillsbury's restaurant
division led to the the sharp earnings decline in fiscal 1987. But
when Stafford told analysts to lower their projections for fiscal
1988 earnings, he said it was because of an expected earnings
decline in the consumer foods division, which includes frozen
pizza, desserts and mixes.
   The announcement came as a surprise, Carver said.
   Spoor, 65, remained on the company's board of directors after
retiring as chairman and chief executive in 1985. In September his
involvement in the company increased when he was selected chairman
of the executive committee.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
