<1ST_LINE>u f PM-EconomyRdp 2ndLd-Writethru   03-01 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0529</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Reach Post-Crash High; Business Economists More Upbeat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs with construction report, picks up 4th
graf pvs, Three consecutive ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported today that its main
economic forecasting gauge tumbled 0.6 percent in January, but an
upward revision in the index of leading economic indicators for
December eased fears of a recession this year.
   In a separate report, the government said construction spending
fell 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline since a 3.3
percent drop in March 1987.
   The Commerce Department said that construction spending fell to
a seasonally adjusted annual rate of $395.2 billion in January
following a 0.4 percent increase in December.
   In the report on leading indicators, the Commerce Department
revised its report for December to reflect a 0.3 percent increase
in the index rather than the 0.2 percent decline it initially
reported. The index had fallen in October and November.
   Three consecutive monthly declines in the index is the
traditional, but not infallible, signal of an impending recession.
Thus, the revision in the December index was taken by economists as
a heartening sign that the country is unlikely to suffer a downturn
this year.
   On Monday, the stock market jumped to its highest level since
the Oct. 19 market meltdown amid new signs of economic optimism.
   Analysts said there was no major economic news to account for
the burst of stock-buying on Monday, which sent the widely-watched
Dow Jones industrial average up by 48.41 points to 2,071.62.
   But traders were heartened to see the Dow industrials vault past
the 2,051.89 level after failing to do so last week. The average
stood at that point on Jan. 7 for its previous highest closing
reading since the crash.
   In late-morning trading today, however, the closely watched
indicator stood at 2,068.80, down 2.82.
   Separately, a survey released Monday indicated that economists
for major corporations have become more upbeat about the economy
than they were three months ago, not long after the Oct. 19 stock
collapse that wiped out half a trillion dollars in stock wealth.
   The National Association of Business Economists said its latest
member survey that only one-fourth of its members predicted a
recession in 1988, down from more than half in the previous survey.
   But an overwhelming 83 percent of the analysts said a downturn
was very likely before the end of the next president's first year
in office.
   In other economic news on Monday:
   _Prices farmers got for raw products in February declined an
average of 0.8 percent from January but still were 6.6 percent
above those a year earlier, the Agriculture Department said.
   _Gold prices tumbled in Europe but rebounded sharply in New
York, based on a stunning rally in platinum that traders ascribed
to fear of unrest in South Africa, a leading producer of precious
metals.
   At midmorning in London today, dealers fixed a recommended gold
price of $429.15 a troy ounce, down from an opening bid of $431.30
but up from Monday's late bid of $425.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
