<1ST_LINE>r f PM-WritersTalks 2ndLd-Writethru f0046 03-01 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Writers Talks, 2nd Ld-Writethru, f0046,0511</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entertainment Writers' Talks Go Down To Wire</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with four grafs, talks in recess, picking up 3rd graf
pvs; also moving on general news wires</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROGER GILLOTT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Script writers and entertainment producers,
trying to hammer out a strike-averting contract settlement, called
a recess today after a 21-hour bargaining session.
   The Writers Guild of America said in a brief statement that
negotiators recessed at 7:15 a.m. and agreed to return at noon.
   Both sides declined to say if an agreement was near, but
alliance and union officials earlier expressed pessimism.
   The old contract for the 9,000 members expired at midnight
Monday with no resolution to the union's demands for greater
creative control on the set and more money from television
residuals.
   ``It doesn't look optimistic,'' said Cheryl Rhoden, spokeswoman
for the WGA, which represents about 6,500 writers on the West Coast
and 2,500 on the East Coast.
   ``The situation is not good,'' agreed Herb Steinberg, spokesman
for the Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers.
   The writers produce scripts for productions ranging from daytime
soap operas and talk shows to prime-time dramas and feature films.
   A strike would be felt first by daily daytime programs and talk
shows, Ms. Rhoden said. She said it would take longer for the
effects of a walkout to become visible on shows produced in advance
that need fewer scripts.
   Negotiators were still at the bargaining table at 5 a.m. this
morning and were expected to wrap up today.
   West Coast union members would vote tonight on whether to
approve the producers' final offer or strike. East Coast members
will vote Wednesday, and results of the two votes aren't expected
to be available until about noon Wednesday.
   Brian Walton, the guild's chief negotiator, said going into the
final round of talks Monday evening that the WGA would stay at the
bargaining table as long as possible.
   But he criticized the producers' alliance for allegedly
spreading stories of widespread financial problems in the industry.
   Steinberg responded that the industry as a whole was doing well
but makers of one-hour television series are suffering because of
difficulty selling their products into syndication.
   Main issues separating the two sides were disputes over creative
rights, residuals from foreign markets and residuals for one-hour
programs.
   The median annual income for writers is $40,000, but about half
of the WGA's members are unemployed at any given time, Ms. Rhoden
said.
   The entertainment arm of the writers' union, which has a
reputation as one of Hollywood's most militant, last went on strike
three years ago. That walkout lasted two weeks before writers voted
to accept a package offering them essentially the same terms as the
one they had earlier voted down.
   Ms. Rhoden said the guild also represents about 600 television
news writers, who struck ABC and CBS last spring, but they operate
under a different agreement and weren't affected by the
negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0253 </DOCNO>
