<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Mixed To Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened steady to lower
today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   A late rally Monday sparked some overnight farmer selling of
corn and soybeans, and that helped limit further gains on the
opening today, analysts said.
   Wheat traders were encouraged by news of new purchases by the
Soviet Union and by the Agriculture Department's announcement that
it had sold less than 16 million bushels in last Friday's weekly
auction of surplus wheat.
   But advances in wheat futures were limited by concerns about
this afternoon's USDA auction, the first in a series of three
weekly auctions that will replace the once-a-week sales, analysts
said.
   ``That's taking a little edge off the enthusiam over the Soviets
buying wheat overnight,'' said Jerry Gidel, an analyst in Chicago
for G.H. Miller & Co.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent lower to \ cent higher with
the contract for delivery in March at $3.14{ a bushel; corn was
unchanged to \ cent lower with March at $2.03} a bushel; oats were
unchanged to } cent higher with March at $1.95 a bushel; soybeans
were \ cent to } cent lower with March at $6.35\ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were higher in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent to .55 cent higher with April at 71.80
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .28 cent to .60 cent higher with
March at 80.15 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to .30 cent
higher with April at 43.27 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
.05 cent to .28 cent higher with March at 51.90 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled sharply lower on Monday.
