<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions March 5-6 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Sunflower Seeds More Than A Symbol in Kansas</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For some Kansas farmers, sunflowers have
become more than a state symbol.
   Wild sunflowers have always flourished here _ hence Kansas'
reputation as the Sunflower State _ but now, farmers in the
northwest and north central part of the state are making money by
growing the tall, green and yellow plants for sale to snack-food
processing plants.
   ``We're the newest crop in the state, and the fastest-growing,''
said John Featherstone, one of two California men who opened the Ag
Dynamics sunflower seed processing plant in Goodland, Kan., in
October 1986.
   The two sought to locate their plant at Goodland, a small
farming community near the state's border with Colorado, because
its high altitude, low humidity, long growing season and irrigation
are perfect for cultivating the high-quality sunflowers used in
snack foods, Featherstone said.
   Although most of the sunflower processing has been done in
Minnesota and North Dakota, the prime growing area is shifting
southward to Kansas, officials said.
   According to an informal survey by the state Department of
Agriculture, the total number of Kansas acres planted in sunflowers
increased from about 60,000 acres in 1982 to about 200,000 in 1987.
Farmers yield about 2,000 pounds of sunflower seeds an acre.
   From 1985 to 1987, the number of acres planted in non-oil seeds
in Kansas increased by about 41,000.
   Sunflower seeds are used to produce oil and bird seed, in
addition to snack foods.
   ``It's not ever going to take over wheat,'' said Agriculture
Secretary Sam Brownback, ``but it does bring in some money for
these people.''
   It wasn't always that way. Kansas has been strong in growing
basic crops with stable markets, but has lagged behind other states
in growing and marketing specialty crops.
   ``They can grow the stuff but the problem has always been
marketing,'' Featherstone said. ``Marketing is more than just
taking orders.''
   When Ag Dynamics first moved into the Goodland area, for
example, some farmers were growing sunflowers for use in sunflower
oil and bird seed. But growers were reluctant to venture into the
snack-food market because they were unfamiliar with the crop and
skeptical of its money-making potential.
   Depressed prices for traditional money-makers, such as corn and
wheat, convinced many to take the plunge into the sunflower
business. Ag Dynamics helped ease the transition for some by
guaranteeing a market their specialty crop.
   ``We cover his (the farmer's) product by selling contracts to
roasters on the other end,'' Featherstone said.
   But Brownback cautions that each farmer must decide whether
alternative crops such as sunflowers are right for his or her
situation.
   Many established farmers have no incentive to try alternative
crops, Brownback said, but smaller farmers with less capital or
those with debts receive needed cash when they grow on contract.
   At the Goodland plant, seeds are dehulled, cleaned, sorted and
bagged and then shipped out of state to several nut companies,
where they are roasted, bagged and distributed, Brownback said.
   Ag Dynamics sells its sunflower seeds to about 40 nut companies,
including Planters. They also export about 25 percent of the crop
to other countries, such as Mexico.
   For the 1988 crop, they will contract with farmers to grow about
30,000 acres, Featherstone said. Their first year, they contracted
for about 350 acres.
   Improving the field-to-market organization has brightened the
future for Kansas sunflower growers considerably. Processing plants
in North Dakota and Minnesota also are beginning to contract with
Kansas farmers for the sunflower seeds they use to produce snacks.
   ``A major portion of the crop is now swinging down into
Kansas,'' Featherstone said.
   And the quality of the seeds grown in northwest Kansas is so
good, Brownback said, ``We're getting some people requesting Kansas
sunflowers.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions March 5-6</NOTE>
