<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetNoon     03-01 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Noon,0484</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market stumbled today after vaulting
to a new post-crash high on Monday.
   The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks was down
1.33, or 0.06 percent, to 2,070.29 at noon on Wall Street.
   Analysts had expected to see the market follow through on
Monday's advance, but the move failed to materialize in the early
going. Some said the morning's activity was highlighted by big
investors cashing in their gains.
   Stocks losing ground outnumbered gainers by 775 to 602 with 461
issues unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 103.25 million at noon, off from
133.99 million at the same time Monday when dividend plays on
utility stocks ignited an early trading burst.
   ``It's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go
next,'' observed Eldon Grimm, senior vice president for Birr,
Wilson Securities.
   Analysts said traders found little to inspire them in the
economic data released this morning. The government said its chief
economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in January,
but an upward revision for December eased fears of an imminent
recession.
   Also today, the Commerce Department said construction spending
tumbled 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10 months.
But as in the case of the leading index, the drop followed a
revised 0.4 percent increase in December.
   Analysts said the figures were in line with expectations and had
little impact on trading.
   Aside from the economic data, market traders were expected to
focus on the latest rash of takeover deals, which helped propel
Monday's surge.
   Among the most active stocks on the NYSE, Federated Department
Stores gained 1] to 67~ following R.H. Macy's offer of
$73.80-per-share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding
shares. Campeau Corp., which has been chasing Federated with a bid
of $68 per share, said Macy's offer was ``simply not competitive.''
   But other results were mixed. Sears, Roebuck was up \ to 38;
General Electric was down \ to 45\, Pillsbury was up 1 to 37},
Wendy's was down [ to 7]; and International Business Machines Corp.
was up ] to 117~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.51 to 149.95 at mid-day. At the American Stock Exchange, the
market value index was up 0.65 to 289.11.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41
to 2,071.62, reaching its highest point since the October crash.
The run left the Dow average 20 points higher than the previous
post-crash peak of 2,051.89 on Jan. 7.
   Analysts noted that while today's early performance was
disappointing, the market appeared firm enough to avoid the kind of
slide that followed the January advance. The day after hitting that
peak, the Dow plunged 140 points.
</TEXT>
