<HEAD>Texas International Suspends Dept Payments</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas International Co. has suspended
payment of interest and principal on subordinated debts totaling
$155 million.
   The Oklahoma City-based oil and gas company announced Monday
that interest payments on the $155 million subordinated debt had
become more than the company can handle.
   Payments on other debt obligations will continue, said James
Gregory, director of investor relations for the company.
   ``Our business environment has simply come to the point where it
is presently not in the best interests of either our shareholders
or our subordinated debt holders for us to remain current on our
subordinated debt as it is currently structured,'' said James A.
Kishpaugh, president and chief executive officer.
   The first payment suspended was a biannual interest payment of
$869,000 due Monday on the company's 10 percent Second Delayed
Convertible Senior Subordinated Notes due Dec. 31, 1993, Gregory
said. Principal on those notes is about $32 million, he said. The
company has about 11 other issues of subordinated notes, he said.
   ``The problem is we're not generating enough cash flow from our
Egyptian assets'' to be able to handle both current debt and move
ahead in the company's exploration plans, Gregory said.
   By the end of 1987, Texas International had expected crude oil
production to be between 3overy on the Khalda concession
in the Egyptian western desert, Gregory said.
   Instead, the concession is producing 20,000 barrels daily, with
Texas International receiving about 10 percent of that, he said.
   Gregory said the company plans to meet with creditors and
establish a plan to allow it to continue its exploration activities
in Egypt and elsewhere.
</TEXT>
