<1ST_LINE>r f BC-EEC-Budget     03-01 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-EEC-Budget,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Italy's Opposition to 1988 Budget Endangers EEC Reforms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Financial reforms agreed to by leaders
of the European Economic Community two weeks ago appeared
threatened Tuesday by Italy's refusal to pay its share into the
1988 budget.
   Sources within the 12-nation Common Market said Italy's
objections to the budget draft could lead other EEC states to
disavow their earlier consent to the reforms. ``Once one country
begins to question the agreement, all others will want to do the
same,'' one official said.
   The official, who asked to remain anonymous in keeping with
established practice, said the problem is likely to be sent to a
meeting of EEC foreign ministers to be held March 5 at Konstanz,
West Germany.
   ``Of course, we are very disappointed that we have to deal with
this problem at this stage,'' said a German official who asked not
to be named. ``The whole situation endangers the 1988 budget ...
everything is blocked,'' he said.
   The much-heralded reforms, agreed in Brussels Feb. 13, were
designed to rein in the EEC's skyrocketing farm spending and give
the trading bloc a sound financial footing for the next five years.
   But Italy's objections had forced Common Market budget ministers
last Wednesday to suspend efforts to adopt the overdue spending
plan.
   In a letter Monday to West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, Prime
Minister Giovanni Goria rejected the formula as offending ``the
principles'' on which the reforms stand.
   An official message from Rome Tuesday said Italy's contribution
to the fund was at least $143 million higher than agreed at the
summit.
   West Germany, which currently holds the EEC presidency, gave
Italy until noon Tuesday to change its mind.
   But the deadline passed and the Italian government remained
adamant in opposing the new formula for calculating national
contributions to a budget supplement set at 7.6 billion European
currency units, or $8.2 billion.
   That amount is needed to bridge the gap between anticipated
spending needs totaling the equivalent of $54.6 billion and revenue
available under current EEC rules.
</TEXT>
