<DOCNO> AP880301-0262 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1307EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-KaiserTech     03-01 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-KaiserTech,0352</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texan Moves to Buy Control of Huge Aluminum Producer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas financier Charles Hurwitz has moved
to gain control of KaiserTech, the world's fifth largest aluminum
producer, with an agreement to pay up to $230 million for a 32.1
percent voting share.
   Hurwitz' bid to KaiserTech Chairman Alan E. Clore competed with
a bid by Marc Rich, a Swiss aluminum business owner. Hurwitz, like
Clore, has no experience in the aluminum industry.
   The announcement Monday said the company would have preferred
that the British industrialist's' holdings be sold more broadly.
Clore was under intense pressure to sell from creditors.
   If Clore hadn't found a buyer by a Monday deadline, he could
have faced default on loans he had obtained using Kaiser stock as
collateral. After the stock plunged because of the October market
crash, lenders wanted repayment.
   The Oakland-based company's stock rose $1.125 a share Monday to
close at $11.875 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   Under the deal, Los Angeles-based Maxxam Group Inc., a company
controlled by Hurwitz, agreed to buy from Clore and his lenders 6.2
million shares of KaiserTech stock for $12 a share.
   Once Maxxam purchases the stock, it has an option to acquire 8.2
million shares of KaiserTech convertible preferred stock at $13.75
to $14 a share. Maxxam also must pay $8 million to $10 million in
expenses, the nature of which was undisclosed.
   In addition, Maxxam is negotiating agreements with other parties
to buy an additional 2.8 million shares of KaiserTech common stock
for $12 a share.
   It was not clear what effect Maxxam's purchase would have
immediately on the KaiserTech board. All 14 seats are up for
election shortly. Included are eight board members appointed by
Clore, including Clore and James Pasman, Kaiser's chief executive
officer.
   The probable changes in KaiserTech's executive suite and
boardroom come as the company is rebounding from six straight years
of losses. Kaiser has sold its chemicals, oil and gas businesses,
has slashed debt, and is concentrating on its core aluminum
business.
</TEXT>
