<DOCNO> AP880301-0263 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1327EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Rover     03-01 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Rover,0249</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>British Aerospace Interested in Buying Rover Group From Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Aerospace PLC has expressed interest in
acquiring state-owned Rover Group PLC, the moneylosing automaker
that the government previously said it intended to sell.
   Trade and Industry Secretary Lord Young said Tuesday that the
government would negotiate until April 30 with British Aerospace,
which was privatized in 1985. If the negotations fail, Lord Young
said the government would explore other options for divesting its
99.8 percent stake in the automaker.
   Rover Group Chairman Graham Day said he welcomed British
Aerospace's interest.
   ``For Rover Group we see this as a very exciting opportunity.
The two groups are complementary and not competitive,'' he said.
``In addition, it offers a speedy route to privatization, with the
minimum disruption to our management, work force, dealer network
and suppliers.''
   The government had said it would sell the Rover Group, makers of
the Land Rover vehicle and Sterling cars, by 1992.
   Rover Group is comprised of the Austin Rover carmaker and the
Land Rover utility vehicle maker. It sold the Leyland trucks unit
last year.
   In Rover's most recent earnings report, the group said it lost
$74 million on revenue of $2.8 billion in the first six months of
1987. But the loss was 80 percent less than in the year-earlier
period.
   The government took over the automaker, formerly called British
Leyland, in 1975 to prevent its collapse.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
