<1ST_LINE>r f BC-GM-Fairfield     03-01 0222</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-GM-Fairfield,0232</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM To Sell Fairfield Plant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRFIELD, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. has announced an
agreement in principle to sell its Fairfield auto parts stamping
plant to Cynba International Inc.
   Cynba, headed by automotive executive Anthony Barclae, proposes
to continue operating the stamping plant, GM officials said at a
news conference Tuesday.
   GM declined to reveal the sale price. It is one of two plants in
southwest Ohio that GM is closing as part of a nationwide program
to cut operating costs and stay competitive.
   GM shut down its Norwood auto assembly plant last Aug. 26,
eliminating 4,300 jobs there, and plans to close the Fairfield
operation in August.
   Barclae proposes to buy the Fairfield plant and equipment. He
also promises to try to hire laid-off GM employees, GM officials
said.
   The deal is contingent on a feasibility assessment. Barclae has
90 days to explore business opportunities and talk with city, state
and United Auto Workers union officials and to decide whether to
buy the plant.
   About 2,500 people once worked at the Fairfield plant. Current
employment stands at 971.
   Barclae owns and operates two sheet metal stamping and assembly
plants _ Shadyside Stamping Corp., in Shadyside, Ohio, and Pigeon
Manufacturing Corp., in Pigeon, Mich. He also operates Cameo Color
Coat Inc., a Detroit-based automotive corrosion resistance painting
company.
</TEXT>
