<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     03-01 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mostly Lower, Gold Prices Up</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: AMs planned by 5:30 p.m. EST.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar ended mostly lower against major
foreign currencies Tuesday after another sluggish trading session
in Europe. Gold prices rose.
   Traders said the dollar came under some mild selling pressure
late in the day, possibly because of a slightly worse-than-expected
U.S. leading indicators statistic for January.
   The Commerce Department said the index fell 0.6 percent in
January, but the decline was partly offset by a revision in the
December index to a 0.3 percent rise from a previously announced
0.2 percent fall.
   Many dealers discounted the dollar's slight decline Tuesday and
said the market remains stagnant.
   The British pound, meanwhile, was boosted by higher interest
rates in Britain. Sterling rose to $1.7775 from $1.7725 Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday
included: 1.6855 West German marks, down from 1.6875; 1.3915 Swiss
francs, up from 1.3903; 5.7065 French francs, down from 5.7150;
1.8940 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8945; 1,244.35 Italian lire, up
from 1,244.25; 1.2570 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2622.
   The dollar rose in Tokyo, closing at 128.63 Japanese yen, up
from Monday's close of 128.12 yen. Later in London, the dollar was
lower at 128.30 yen.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $428.70 a troy ounce,
compared with Monday's late bid of $425. In Zurich, gold was higher
at a bid $429.50 compared with $426 Monday.
   The metal closed in Hong Kong at a bid $433.80, up from $430.19.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.29 a troy ounce, compared
with $6.14 Monday.
</TEXT>
