<DOCNO> AP880301-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1402EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-USTrade Bjt   03-01 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-US Trade, Bjt,0702</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Trade Figures Send Mixed Message</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ERIC TALMADGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking at Japan's trade figures for the past year
is like looking at a glass of water _ the glass is either half
empty or half full, depending on one's perspective.
   From the Japanese side, the figures show improvement, with
exports beginning to decline in volume terms after years of growth
that provoked resentment among its trading partners.
   From the American side, the trade deficit with Japan rose again,
mainly because the soaring yen inflated the cost of Japanese
imports.
   In Tokyo, government officials are optimistic that recent trade
statistics show a trend toward reducing Japan's huge trade surplus.
But independent economists are voicing reservations over long-term
trade prospects.
   Referring to the latest U.S. trade figures, a Ministry of
International Trade and Industry official said the tide is slowly
turning and that, although the figures showed the biggest deficit
in history, the imbalance with Japan actually decreased.
   ``It depends on whether you look at trade in yen or dollar
terms,'' he said.
   Japan's exports rose 5.6 percent in dollar terms but fell 8.2
percent in yen terms in the last three months of 1987, compared to
a year earlier. At the same time, imports rose in terms of both
dollars and yen.
   ``As for volume, Japan's imports are growing, with a big
increase from the newly industrialized countries and Europe, though
the increase with the United States was not so large,'' said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   According to U.S. figures, the trade deficit last year was a
record $171.2 billion, up from $156.2 billion in 1986. The United
States' largest bilateral deficit again was with Japan _ a record
$59.8 billion, up from $58.6 billion in 1986 and $49.7 billion in
1985.
   Ron Napier, vice president and Japan economist with the
investment firm of Salomon Brothers Inc., does see a short-term
easing in the trade imbalance, but warns that good figures in the
short term may be misleading.
   ``The first quarter looks good, and we will see a brief lull
because Japanese automakers have too much inventory already in the
United States,'' he said. ``But I don't really think the figures
for the final quarter of 1987 signal that Japan's trade surplus has
topped out. There were basically no trends in 1987.''
   Barriers keeping U.S. exporters out of certain Japanese markets,
such as highly controversial restrictions on imported beef, citrus
fruits and rice, add to the trade imbalance problem and have come
under heavy fire from the U.S. government.
   But the most pressing question now may not be barriers or
exchange rates, Napier said.
   ``I think that the yen-dollar rate is no longer a problem for
U.S. exporters. More marketing focus is needed in this country,
which traditionally has not been a target,'' he said.
   Napier said the United States lags behind Europe and the newly
industrialized countries in expanding exports to Japan because of a
lack of distribution facilities, an insufficient sales force and
scanty product representation.
   ``It was interesting to hear that U.S. Steel would be exporting
again, but that they chose Europe as their market,'' he said.
   The official at the Japanese trade ministry agreed.
   ``Success depends on exporters' efforts,'' he said. ``Exporters
in the U.S. now have the chance to compete. Japanese consumers are
changing and there are more and more foreign products for sale in
supermarkets here.
   ``Domestic demand for foreign goods is increasing, so now is the
time for the U.S. to try to expand in the Japanese market.
Exporters should act immediately to take advantage of developments
here,'' he added.
   ``As for the future prospects of Japan's trade with the U.S., I
think that with the yen-dollar rate our imports will continue to
steadily increase.''
   Napier also offers some comfort to Americans wondering if the
trade imbalance with Japan will ever end.
   ``The marketing focus is starting to change, with more attention
being given to Japan,'' he said. ``It may take awhile, but this
will eventually have an impact.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
