<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1421EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-BargeBuy     03-01 0236</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Barge Buy,0244</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Archer Daniels Midland Agrees To Buy St. Louis Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Archer Daniels Midland Co., a major processor
of raw agricultural commodities, has signed a letter of intent to
buy CLC of America Inc., a St. Louis-based barge line, the
companies have announced.
   The barge company emerged in December from a complex Chapter 11
bankruptcy, during which it fended off several buy-out offers. ADM
agreed to pay about $60 million in common stock for the company in
a transaction to be completed by June, company officials said.
   The acquisition will substantially increase Archer Daniels
Midland's ability to to transport grain and finished products, ADM
vice-president Richard E. Burket said Monday.
   ``We've been doing a greater volume and have greater needs for
river transportation,'' Burket said.
   CLC has a fleet of 515 barges, 13 line haul towboats, 12
switching boats and barge fleeting facilities in Wisconsin, Iowa,
New Orleans and St. Louis.
   The transaction does not include Morgan Drive Away Inc., a
subsidiary of CLC that provides highway transportation of mobile
homes, recreational vehicles and other commodities, CLC officials
said.
   Industry observers view the merger as a mark of confidence in a
barge industry slowly recovering from years of financial turmoil.
CLC faced a staggering pile of debts when it filed for bankruptcy
in January 1986, but in the last two years, barge shipments have
increased and barge rates have risen.
</TEXT>
