<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     03-01 0416</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0435</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market crept ahead today after
vaulting to a new post-crash high Monday.
   The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 blue-chip stocks
recovered from a small loss earlier in the day to stand at
2,071.95, up 0.33, or 0.02 percent, at 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   Analysts had expected to see the market follow through on
Monday's strong advance, but the trend was mostly disappointing
with two hours of trading to go. Some said the morning's activity
was highlighted by big investors cashing in their gains.
   Stocks losing ground outnumbered gainers by 802 to 688 with 424
issues unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 147.54 million at 2 p.m., well
behind the levels reached at the same time Monday when dividend
plays on utility stocks ignited an early trading burst.
   ``It's sort of a pause to take profits and see where we go
next,'' observed Eldon Grimm, senior vice president for Birr,
Wilson Securities.
   Analysts said traders found little to inspire them in the
economic data released this morning. The government said its chief
economic forecasting gauge dropped a sharp 0.6 percent in January,
but an upward revision for December eased fears of an imminent
recession.
   Also today, the Commerce Department said construction spending
tumbled 2.9 percent in January, the biggest decline in 10 months.
But like the leading index, the drop followed a revised 0.4 percent
increase in December.
   Analysts said the figures were in line with expectations and had
little impact on trading.
   Aside from the economic data, traders focused on issues swept up
in the latest rash of takeover deals, which had powered Monday's
surge.
   Among the most active stocks on the NYSE, Federated Department
Stores gained 1[ to 67| following R.H. Macy's offer of
$73.80-per-share for about 80 percent of the company's outstanding
shares.
   GAF Corp., which received a sweetened buyout offer from its top
management, dipped [ to 49~.
   Other results were similarly mixed. Sears, Roebuck was up \ to
38; General Electric was down ] to 45[, Pillsbury was up 1\ to 38,
Wendy's was down [ to 7]; and International Business Machines Corp.
was up [ to 117|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
down 0.46 to 150.00. At the American Stock Exchange, the market
value index was up 0.79 to 289.25.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 48.41
to 2,071.62, reaching its highest point since the October crash.
