<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GAFOffer     03-01 0479</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GAF Offer,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GAF Buyout Offer Sweetened, Agreement Reached</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WAYNE, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A management group led by GAF Corp.'s
chairman has raised its bid for the company to $1.4 billion, and
the board of directors agreed to submit the offer to shareholders
``without endorsement,'' GAF said Tuesday.
   The deal, now valued at $1.4 billion, would provide $46 in cash
and junior securities with a face value of $6.50 for each share.
   In December, the group led by Chairman Samuel J. Heyman had
offered $1.35 billion, or $40 in cash and $8.50 in securities per
share.
   That represented a downward revision from its $2.3 billion first
offer, made in September, of $64 in cash and $2.50 face value in
debt securities. Heyman said rising interest rates made it
impossible for the group to continue the original bid.
   A special committee of the board of the specialty chemicals and
building materials company has agreed to submit the new proposal
``without endorsement'' to shareholders, GAF said.
   To permit that, shareholders must first vote on an amendment to
the company charter.
   The amendment would allow shareholders to act in place of the
board in considering a merger offer, as the Heyman-led proposal has
been presented.
   The committee had earlier rejected the $64-a-share proposal as
being inadequate. GAF said it had decided to let stockholders
decide based on the favorable opinion of the offer by Salomon
Brothers Inc., retained by the committee as financial advisers.
   The decision was also made following the committee's
instructions to Salomon Brothers to solicit other possible
purchasers, GAF said.
   The committee said that if it receives an ``economically
superior alternative proposal'' for GAF, it could cancel its
agreement with the buyout group.
   ``We think the price is a fare and full price,'' Heyman said.
``It's seven times the price of the stock only four years ago.''
   GAF stock, which reached a low of $31.50 after the Oct. 19 stock
market crash, has traded around $50 with speculation about an
agreement.
   It was $49.75, down 25 cents, on the New York Stock Exchange in
afternoon trading Tuesday.
   The agreement will put the management offer ``to the test of the
marketplace,'' said Heyman, who wrested control of GAF in 1983
after a bitter proxy fight to oust former Chairman Jesse Werner.
   During his tenure, GAF has made hundreds of millions of dollars
in unsuccessful buyout attempts of Union Carbide Corp. and
Borg-Warner Corp.
   ``We're primarily an operating company, but we're not retiring
from the takeover arena,'' the 48-year-old executive said Tuesday.
   Heyman owns 2.8 million shares of GAF, or about 10 percent of
its outstanding stock.
   He said the takeover would be financed by loans from a bank
syndicate led by Chase Manhattan, a limited debt offering and the
group's own money.
   GAF also said it had reached tentative settlements of lawsuits
brought in connection with the buyout offer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
