<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-BPAmerica     03-01 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-BP America,0311</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>BP America Returns To Profitability</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   BP America Inc., enjoying higher oil prices in
1987, reported a return to profitability.
   The former Standard Oil Co., now a segment of British Petroleum
Co. PLC, earned $564 million in 1987. Standard Oil incurred a $188
million loss in 1986, its final full year not under BP's control.
   Due to tax accounting requirements of the United Kingdom, BP
America could not report fourth-quarter net earnings, spokesman
John Andes said Tuesday. The company's results were released Monday.
   Income from operations in the fourth quarter was $613 million,
compared with $109 million in Standard Oil's fourth quarter of
1986. In all of 1987, operating income totaled $2.26 billion,
compared with an operating loss of $242 million in 1986.
   The 1986 annual loss included $1.13 billion for writedowns and
restructuring charges.
   Operating income reflects what BP America contributed to its
parent company's results. Operating income does not include regular
tax charges or interest payments on debt.
   The report was the first release of financial results by BP
America since June, when British Petroleum bought the 45 percent of
common stock of Standard Oil Co. that it did not already own.
   BP America sales were $15.4 billion, compared with $13.9 billion
in 1986. For the fourth quarter, sales were $4.01 billion, up from
$3.35 billion for the year-ago period.
   ``As these results show, BP America's performance is highly
dependent on crude oil prices,'' said Robert B. Horton, chief
executive officer of the company.
   ``In 1987, higher crude oil prices, lower costs and increased
production have significantly improved the contribution made by the
exploration and production segment,'' he continued. ``We also
benefited from the resumption of activity at the Bingham Canyon
mine (in Utah) at a time of higher copper prices.''
</TEXT>
