<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Unilever,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Net Profit Flat at Consumer Product Giant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unilever, the Anglo-Dutch home products giant,
reported Tuesday that its fourth-quarter net profit was flat as
revenue slipped a bit.
   The company, which is made up of Unilever PLC of Britain and
Unilever NV of the Netherlands, said its after-tax profit was
unchanged at 186 million pounds, which is the equivalent of about
$331 million. Sales dipped 0.7 percent to 4.45 billion pounds, or
about $7.92 billion, from 4.48 billion pounds.
   Unilever said pre-tax profit on its North American activities
doubled to the equivalent of $178 million.
   For all of 1987, Unilever reported a net profit of 756 million
pounds, or about $1.35 billion. That was up 14 percent from
earnings of 664 million pounds the previous year.
   Sales for the year fell 3 percent to 16.55 billion pounds, or
about $29.5 billion, from 17.14 billion pounds in 1986.
   Pre-tax profit on North American activities also doubled for the
year, rising to the equivalent of $425 million.
   Unilever said that for the full year, sales gains were recorded
in most product groups and substantial contributions were made by
recent acquisitions, including the U.S.-based Chesebrough-Pond's
Inc., which was purchased in December 1986 for $3.15 billion.
</TEXT>
