<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Europe-Takeover     03-01 0545</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Europe-Takeover,0567</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Clears New Share Issue</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAF CASERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Brussels court on Tuesday approved
Societe Generale de Belgique S.A.'s issuance of 12 million new
shares in a ruling that could intensify the battle for control of
Belgium's biggest holding company.
   Societe Generale announced in January it was raising its capital
to 40.2 million shares from 28.2 million shares, shortly after
Italian investor Carlo De Benedetti indicated he wanted to gain
control of the company.
   De Benedetti raised questions about the new capital issue in
court, and the courts stripped the shares of voting rights in two
previous decisions.
   Tuesday's ruling would retore voting rights for those shares
temporarily and if approved by a higher court, the issue would
dilute the stake of all shareholders.
   Belgian industrialist Andre Leysen, who is aligned with De
Benedetti, said he has an option on 10 million of the 12 million
new shares.
   But the management of Societe Generale, which opposes De
Benedetti's bid, has said the option is no longer valid because
Leysen failed to form an alliance in support of Societe Generale
early last month.
   Societe Generale Director Etienne Davignon said the new shares
are owned by seven companies from Belgium, Luxembourg and France
that have formed an alliance which is siding with the 166-year-old
company.
   The alliance claims to hold 52 percent of Societe Generale's
original 28.2 million shares.
   De Benedetti has claimed he and his allies control 47.2 percent
of Societe Generale's shares, but Davignon said it was only 43
percent.
   If a higher court confirms the capital increase, Davignon said
it would reduce De Benedetti's stake to about 28.5 percent.
   Meanwhile, De Benedetti said in a statement from Milan he
intends to call a shareholders meeting to decide the future of the
company after its public offer to buy more Societe Generale shares
ends March 4.
   A source close to De Benedetti said ``we are fully confident we
will have a majority of shares at the meeting.''
   Leysen's holding company Gevaert N.V said in a statement it was
``now in a position'' to buy the new shares as it had agreed to do
on Feb. 3.
   The shares were initially placed with a Societe Generale
subsidiary but have since been sold to the seven companies allied
with it, Davignon said.
   The top official of Societe Generale, Rene Lamy, said last week
the agreement with Leysen was no longer valid ``since Leysen has
failed to cement a Belgian federation'' in support of Societe
Generale.
   Leysen could not get a deal with several Belgian and European
groups to keep the company anchored in Belgium earlier this month.
   Instead, he reached a partnership agreement with De Benedetti
and the Copeba holding company, the Belgian subsidiary of the
French Paribas group.
   Together they founded a new holding company called Europa 92.
   The management of Societe Generale first announced the capital
increase Jan. 18, just after De Benedetti said he wanted to take
control and turn it into a holding company with interests across
Europe.
   Societe Generale has interests in about 1,400 companies
worldwide and in about half of Belgium's top 50 companies. It has
an important stake in Belgium's gas, electricity and petroleum
sector and in Belgium's largest bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
