<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 1718EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     03-01 0547</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down Slightly, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell marginally against most key
currencies Tuesday, reflecting what dealers called a narrow trading
range that has emerged over the past several days.
   Gold prices rose overseas but were mixed in the United States.
As of 4 p.m. EST, Republic National Bank of New York quoted gold at
$430.45 a troy ounce, down 15 cents from the price late Monday.
   Currency dealers said there was little news to influence the
behavior of the dollar. They said a Commerce Department report on
the index of leading indicators, an important economic barometer,
failed to convey a definite trend.
   The department said the index fell 0.6 percent in January but it
revised the December figure from a 0.2 percent drop to a 0.3
percent increase. That revision snapped a string of three straight
monthly declines, which has often signaled an impending recession.
   ``We need something more specific to set the market one way or
another,'' said Zlatko Glamuzina, chief currency dealer at the New
York branch of the Italian bank Banco di Sicilia.
   Gary Dorsch, senior money market economist at LNS Financial
Group Inc. in Chicago, said ``there appears to be very little
impetus for traders to move out of the dollar's range, at least in
the near term.''
   By contrast, he said, currencies such as the British pound and
Canadian dollar seemed to be appreciating because of relatively
high interest rates in Britain and Canada.
   ``We're seeing a lot of deflation in commodity markets and
weakness in gold prices, which supports the idea that global
interest rates will be steady to lower,'' Dorsch said. ``So
international money managers are searching for higher yields.''
   The dollar rose in Tokyo, closing at 128.63 Japanese yen, up
from the Monday close of 128.12 yen. Later in London, the dollar
was lower at 128.30 yen. By the time trading concluded in New York,
the dollar was trading at 128.32 yen, marginally higher than 128.24
rate late Monday.
   The British pound rose to $1.7775 from $1.7725 Monday on the
London market. Later in New York, sterling was quoted at $1.7766,
more than the $1.7742 quoted late Monday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York compared with late Monday
levels included: 1.6864 West German marks, down from 1.6874; 1.3916
Swiss francs, down from 1.3931; 1.2578 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2592; 5.7100 French francs, down from 5.7155; 1,243.25 Italian
lire, up from 1,243.
   Late dollar rates in Europe compared with late Monday included:
1.6855 West German marks, down from 1.6875; 1.3915 Swiss francs, up
from 1.3903; 5.7065 French francs, down from 5.7150; 1.8940 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.8945; 1,244.35 Italian lire, up from
1,244.25; 1.2570 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2622.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $428.70 a troy ounce,
compared with $425 late Monday. In Zurich, gold rose to $429.50 vs.
$426, and in Hong Kong gold closed at $433.80 vs. $430.19.
   On the New York Commodity Exchange, gold for current delivery
rose 50 cents a troy ounce to $431.
   Silver bullion prices rose in London to $6.29 a troy ounce,
compared with $6.14 Monday. On the New York Comex, silver for
current delivery fell 1.7 cents an ounce to $6.222.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880301-0288 </DOCNO>
