<1ST_LINE>r f BC-AmericanStandard     03-01 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-American Standard,0283</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Says It Might Sweeten Cash Portion of Anti-Takeover
Recapitalization</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Standard Inc., target of a hostile
$2.12 billion takeover attempt by Black & Decker Corp., said
Tuesday it was taking steps to sweeten the cash portion of a
recapitalization designed to foil the bid.
   The company said it had begun talks with unidentified third
parties regarding the possible sale of debt securities as a means
of increasing the cash part of the recapitalization, which would
pay shareholders $1.9 billion plus give them a stake in the
recapitalized company.
   A recapitalization, in which a company restructures its amount
of debt and equity, is used often to thwart unwelcome takeovers.
The strategy usually plunges a company into debt, making it less
attractive as an acquisition.
   Under the American Standard recapitalization plan, which would
raise the company's long-term debt from $412 million to $2.3
billion, stockholders would receive $59 in cash, $5 worth of
high-yielding debt securities and one new share of stock in the
recapitalized company for each share of old stock.
   The company's announcement Tuesday did not elaborate on how much
it intended to raise the cash portion of the recapitalization but
said there was no assurance that any change would be made in the
existing proposal.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading, American Standard
stock rose 12{ cents a share to $68.62{. Black and Decker stock
rose 62{ cents a share to $19.12{.
   Black & Decker, a tool and appliance maker based in Towson, Md.,
has been attempting since late January to acquire American
Standard, a New York-based maker of plumbing, air conditioning and
auto equipment.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
