<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     03-01 0749</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0779</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wheat Futures Prices Slip Amid USDA Auction Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheat futures prices slipped substantially lower Tuesday on the
Chicago Board of Trade as the Agriculture Department launched a new
series of auctions aimed at reducing government stockpiles of
surplus wheat.
   On other markets, other grains and soybeans ended mostly lower;
energy futures retreated; most livestock and meat futures advanced;
precious metals were mixed; and stock-index futures were higher.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   The USDA's weekly auctions of suplus wheat, begun in November,
have gradually lost steam. So on Tuesday the agency launched a new
series of sales to be held three times a week.
   The agency has set targets of 10 million bushels for each of the
new auctions during the first two weeks, which creates the
potential for adding 30 million bushels a week to the open market.
   The old weekly auctions usually had targets of 25 million
bushels. Sales in recent weeks had fallen well short of that goal,
however, with less than 16 million bushels sold last Friday.
   Traders fear the new auctions, which divide the sales by regions
of the country, will be more successful and depress cash prices by
adding to available supplies of wheat, analysts said.
   ``The possibility of selling 10 milllion bushels the first time
out is probably going to be a little tough,'' said Jerry Gidel of
Chicago-based G.H. Miller & Co. ``But it's the fact that they're
coming right back tomorrow, then on Friday again, that has the
market a little on edge.''
   However, analyst Jim Quinton of Agri-Visor Services Inc. in
Bloomington, Ill., said the new auctions probably would have little
long-term impact on futures prices.
   Quinton attributed Tuesday's wheat losses of up to 5 cents a
bushel to profit-taking by speculators.
   Results from Tuesday's auction will likely be released on
Wednesday.
   Wheat settled 4{ cents to 5 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in March at $3.11 a bushel; corn was unchanged to } cent
lower with March at $2.03} a bushel; oats were unchanged to { cent
higher with March at $1.94{ a bushel; soybeans were 1 cent lower to
1{ cents higher with March at $6.35 a bushel.
   Energy futures prices, particularly for refined products, fell
sharply on the New York Mercantile Exchange, where analysts said
bulls and bears have been waging a technical tug-of-war.
   ``This market seems to be moving briskly within a range, which
is what it probably will continue to do before it decides which way
it wants to go,'' said Peter Beutel, an analyst in New York for
Elders Futures Inc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil traded as much as .46 cent
lower, but settled .11 cent to .29 cent lower with April at $15.72
a barrel; heating oil was .82 cent to 1.15 cents lower with April
at 43.47 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .93 cent to 1.10
cents lower with April at 45.29 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   Cattle futures moved higher in mostly technical trading,
analysts said.
   Hog futures advanced on bargain buying after Monday's sharp
decline, said Tom Price, vice president of Linnco Futures Inc. in
Chicago.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .52 cent higher with April at
71.95 a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .85 cent higher with
March at 80.42 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent to .40 cent higher
with April at 43.47 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were
unchanged to .42 cent lower with March at 51.60 cents a pound.
   Gold moved slightly higher while silver futures retreated a bit
on New York's Commodity Exchange.
   Gold for April delivery sank to $425 a troy ounce during the
session, but rebounded to settle at $432.40.
   Richard Levine, vice president of Elders' precious metals
divison, noted that gold had touched $425 on Monday as well, and
predicted it would bounce off that level once more before falling
to $400 a troy ounce in the next three or four weeks.
   Silver drifted lower in featureless trading, he said.
   Gold settled 50 cents to 60 cents higher with April at $432.40 a
troy ounce; silver was 1.7 cents to 2 cents lower with March at
$6.222 a troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures inched higher on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for March delivery of the Standard &
Poor's 500 index setttled .35 point higher at 267.65. The
underlying spot index was .59 point lower at 267.23.
</TEXT>
