<HEAD>Ford, Union Reach Agreement On Contract For Mexico Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ford Motor Co. said it reached separate
agreements early Tuesday with bargainers representing workers at
two plants in Mexico, including one idled since Feb. 8 by a strike.
   Two-year agreements were reached with the Council of Automotive
Workers of Ford Motor Co., representing about 1,000 hourly
employees at the Chihuahua Engine Plant and another 1,100 at the
Hermosillo Stamping and Assembly Plant, Ford said in a statement.
   Chihuahua workers went on strike Feb. 8, eight days after their
previous two-year contract was extended, the statement said.
Production of 2.3-liter, four-cylinder engines for the domestic
market and export to the United States and Canada was to resume
Wednesday, it said.
   The Hermosillo workers' contract expired at midnight Monday. But
Ford did not indicate whether production of two- and four-door
Mercury Tracers for export to the U.S. and Tracer station wagons
for export to the U.S. and Canada was interrupted.
</TEXT>
