<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Earns-Affiliated     03-01 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Earns-Affiliated,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Affiliated Reports Fourth Quarter Net Loss; Annual Profit Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Affiliated Publications Inc., owner of the Boston
Globe, said Tuesday it had a net loss in its fourth quarter, partly
due to its equity share of the loss suffered by its McCaw
Communications Cos. affiliate.
   Affiliated posted a net loss of $3.62 million in the quarter
ended Dec. 27, compared with a profit of $40.1 million, or $1.14
per share, in the same period a year earlier.
   Revenue during the quarter rose to $135.6 million from $110.3
million a year earlier.
   Affiliated said its equity share of McCaw's losses from
continuing operations during the quarter was $19.2 million.
Affiliated said the operating loss stemmed from expansion of
McCaw's McCaw Cellular Communications subsidiary and accounting
changes relating to the unit.
   For the year, Affiliated posted a profit of $201.1 million, or
$5.73 per share, compared with $66.1 million, or $1.85 per share, a
yer earlier. Revenue rose to $490.1 million from $401.1 million in
1986.
   Gains from the sale of discontinued operations and results from
discontinued operations in 1987 came to $40 million against $26.3
million in 1986. Earnings for 1987 included equity in an
extraordinary $17.9 million credit from McCaw Communications.
   McCaw, based in Kirkland, Wash., is the parent of McCaw Cellular
Communications, the country's largest operator of cellular
telephone systems.
   In addition to a major interest in McCaw, Affiliated owns Globe
Newspaper Co., publisher of the Globe; Billboard Publications Inc.,
and The Globe Pequot Press Inc.
</TEXT>
