<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CitrusFight 1stLd-Writethru f0192 03-01 0203</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Citrus Fight, 1st Ld - Writethru, f0192,0204</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Florida Governor Joins Court Action to Block Texas Ban</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with federal judge overturning ban,
editing to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bob Martinez joined a court action
to block Texas from banning fresh Florida citrus on Tuesday, the
same day a federal judge in Texas overturned the ban.
   The ban was imposed last month after the U.S. Department of
Agriculture lifted a 3{-year-old federal quarantine on Florida
citrus that was prompted by outbreaks of citrus canker in Florida.
   U.S. District Judge James Nowlin said Tuesday in Austin, Texas
that he lifted the state ban because federal rules allowing the
shipments took precedence over the state rule.
   Martinez had notified Texas Gov. William P. Clements that he was
joining a court petition to be filed by Florida Agriculture
Commissioner Doyle Conner supporting a court action brought by
Florida citrus growers.
   Texas officials had refused to allow Florida citrus into their
state despite the lifting of the federal quarantine on shipments of
Florida fruit to other citrus-producing states. Florida producers
must take a number of actions to ensure their fruit does not
introduce citrus canker into other states.
</TEXT>
