<FILEID>AP-NR-03-01-88 2338EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Currency     03-01 0216</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Currency,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Traders' Group Demands Slower Korean Currency Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A major foreign trade group asked the
government Wednesday to slow the South Korean currency's
appreciation against the U.S. dollar.
   In a report to the government, the Korea Foreign Trade
Association said the recent sharp rise of the won against the
dollar could lead to a series of collapses among exporting firms.
   A stronger won _ and conversely, a weaker dollar _ raises the
costs of Korean products in the United States, a major export
market.
   The United States has been pressuring South Korea to revalue its
currency at a faster pace to help reduce the nation's growing U.S.
trade surplus, which soared to $9.5 billion last year.
   The association said if the won's value rises 10 percent against
the dollar, the average export profitability of South Korean-made
products would fall by 3.7 percent.
   The won has appreciated by 4.13 percent against the dollar so
far this year, accounting for about half the range registered for
all of 1987. As of Wednesday, the won was quoted at 760.90 to the
dollar, down 31.30 won from year-end 1987.
   If the won continues rising at that pace, its appreciation rate
for all of this year could surpass 24 percent, the association said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
